<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-Soviet Bjt   10-01 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet, Bjt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Sizes Up Soviet Shifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says a
shakeup in the Soviet hierarchy that swept President Andrei A.
Gromyko out of the Kremlin shows that General Secretary Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is intent on pursing his policy of reform.
   But Shultz was hesitant Friday to offer a deeper analysis of the
changes, which also displaced Anatoly F. Dobrynin, a former
ambassador to the United States.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev is a strong and determined person,'' Shultz said
at a news conference. ``He has a major reform program that he is
working on. And if there is any message from this, it is that he
intends to pursue that program.''
   Gromyko is retiring from the Politburo, while Dobrynin is
leaving his post as foreign policy adviser for the Communist Party.
Both played key roles in relations with the United States for at
least a quarter-century, and Shultz had kind words for them.
   He called Gromyko ``a strong figure'' and wished Dobrynin well.
   The shakeup also downgraded Yegor K. Ligachev from ideology
chief to supervision of agriculture.
   The Soviet foreign ministry spokesman, Gennady Gerasimov, said
``people are just retiring. If you want my comment, it's a change
of generation... The generation that is coming to power waited in
the wings maybe for too long.''
   Gromyko, who last held the largely ceremonial post of president,
was foreign minister and Dobrynin was the Soviet envoy to
Washington during the detente period of U.S.-Soviet reconciliation
in the 1970s.
   ``All these changes are restructuring,'' Gerasimov told
reporters here.
   Shultz recalled working with Gromyko in 1985 to reopen
U.S.-Soviet arms control negotiations and on arrangements for the
summit meeting between President Reagan and Gorbachev in Geneva
that November.
   Shultz was reluctant to assess the developments in Moscow.
``It's a little hard and a little early to say what they mean,'' he
told reporters.
   But Shultz then added: ``Mr. Gorbachev is a very strong and
determined person. He has a major reform program that he is working
on. And if there is any message from this it is that he intends to
pursue that program.''
   For the last three years, Shultz has been working closely with
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze. They have held 30 meetings
since Shevardnadze succeeded Gromyko in the post.
   ``I have never had any question in my mind that Mr. Gorbachev
and Mr. Shevardnadze are in control of their foreign policy,'' said
Shultz.
   From the start, Shultz said, Shevardnadze ``was a strong and
able individual. You could see that right away.''
   Phyllis Oakley, the State Department spokeswoman, said in
Washington: ``We will, of course, be studying those changes and
what they mean for the U.S.-Soviet relationship.''
   Reading from a statement, the U.S. official added: ``I would
like to point out that our policy toward the Soviet Union is based
on U.S. interests, not on personalities or who holds what position
in Moscow.
   ``We have in place a sound framework that can deal with the best
and worst in Soviet behavior. We naturally hope and expect that
U.S.-Soviet relations will continue developing in a constructive
direction, as they have in the last seven years. At this point, I
have no reason to doubt that those positive trends will continue.''
   Nonetheless, Mrs. Oakley had a word of criticism for Moscow. She
chided the Soviet leadership for having criticized United Nations
peacekeeping forces in Afghanistan on the very day, earlier this
week, that UN peacekeepers worldwide won the Nobel Peace Prize.
</TEXT>
