<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     10-01 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaigns Again In Dukakis' Back Yard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has struck again at
Democrat Michael Dukakis' home turf, a tactic aides say will
continue as the Republican campaign tries to keep the Massachusetts
governor on the defensive.
   In a campaign stop kept secret until just a few hours before,
Bush on Friday scooted to Springfield in central Massachusetts to
receive endorsements from local law enforcement groups. It was just
eight days after Bush blasted into Boston to get the nod from the
police union there.
   The endorsement ``comes from you who know the truth, not just
about me but about my opponent as well,'' Bush said, thanking the
local branch of the International Brotherhood of Police Officers
and the Springfield Police Department Supervisors Association.
   Officer Robert Jacobson, president of the IBPO local, said his
group decided to endorse Bush because of his support of the death
penalty and because of the prison furlough program that Dukakis had
supported.
   ``Our members have never supported furloughs for first-degree
murderers, but Michael Dukakis did,'' he said. ``Until public
opinion drove him to change his mind, they continued.''
   The program has since been altered to exclude first-degree
murderers.
   Ron Kaufman, the Northeast regional coordinator for the Bush
campaign, said the efforts to embarrass Dukakis on his home turf
would continue.
   Bush's first public events were in New Jersey, where he also
received the endorsement of local police groups.
   Bush was introduced in Paterson by Passaic County Sheriff Edwin
Englehardt, who chopped at the American Civil Liberties Union. It's
a group Bush frequently attacks and dares Dukakis to quit.
   The Paterson officers, he said, ``don't want a man in that White
House who is a sympathizer and a card-carrying member of the ACLU,
that great organization that's against everything that's right for
America.''
   Bush then repeated his blast of Dukakis as an ACLU member.
Dukakis supported the ``basic revolving-door program for
murderers'' while he, by contrast, wanted murders executed, Bush
said.
   ``My opponent had the nerve yesterday to come in here and talk
about oceans you can't swim in,'' Bush said. ``You tried to drink
the water in Boston Harbor recently? Don't do it.'' He was
referring to pollution, and not to the brine content of Boston
Harbor's sea water.
   From the Paterson municipal center, Bush went to nearby
Ridgefield Memorial High School, where he barely mentioned the
campaign in a soft-spoken appeal to the students to fight drug use.
   Bush then returned to the attack in Springfield, Mass., where he
also declared: ``I am running as myself, and my opponent is running
from himself.''
   He then paid a courtesy call on Archbishop John Whealon in
Hartford, Conn., and finished the trip with a rally in West
Hartford. Bush renewed the attack on an array of issues, including
crime and Dukakis' plan to crack down on tax cheats.
   It was wrong to hire ``three divisions of IRS agents'' to go
into ``every kitchen in America'' looking for people who haven't
paid their fair share of taxes, he said.
   In Washington, Bush spokesman Steve Hart disputed a statement by
former Central Intelligence Agency director Stansfield Turner that
Bush rehired Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega as a CIA
source in 1981.
   Turner told several news organizations that he had fired
Noriega, the head of Panama's military and de facto ruler of the
country, in 1976 because Noriega was an ``unscrupulous character.''
   The Dukakis campaign has made an issue of the Reagan
administration's dealings with Noriega up until his recent
indictment in the United States on drug charges.
   The vice president had no public events scheduled today or
Sunday. He planned to resume campaigning Monday with a trip to
California to watch the return of the space shuttle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InaugurationDate     10-01 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inauguration Date,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pell Urges Moving Up Presidential Inauguration Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee says presidents should be sworn in earlier because the 2{
months between Election Day and Inauguration Day creates an
unnecessary ``period of vulnerability.''
   ``The incumbent president no longer has real political authority
and the incoming president lacks constitutional authority, and the
whole world knows it,'' Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said Friday.
``It is a period of vulnerability which can and should be
eliminated.''
   In a Senate floor speech introducing a resolution for a
constitutional amendment, Pell said the change would eliminate ``10
weeks of crippled leadership'' and avoid an ``unhealthy and
unnecessary situation.''
   The senator wants to move up Inauguration Day for the president
and vice president from Jan. 20 to Nov. 20. The constitutional
amendment also would move the swearing-in day for Congress from
Jan. 3 to Nov. 15.
   Pell has introduced similar measures in the past. With time
quickly running out in this session of Congress, action this year
appears unlikely.
   From 1793 to 1933, the swearing in of new presidents took place
March 4. The 20th Amendment pushed it back to Jan. 20 beginning in
1937.
   Pell, who introduced the resolution along with Sen. William V.
Roth Jr., R-Del., said the move also would avoid `@lame duck''
administrations in which officials might be ``tempted to expend
funds, make contracts and grants and promulgate regulations that
may be either politically motivated or inspired by sheer
self-interest.''
   Pell said the development of voting machines and instant
election result tabulations eliminates the justification for the
long lag time between elections and inaugurations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
