<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Off Trail To Prepare For Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen was off the campaign trail to prepare for his debate with
Republican counterpart Dan Quayle after returning to the nation's
capital to pick up an endorsement and criticize the GOP ticket.
   Bentsen, the Texas senator, was meeting today with advisers and
colleagues in advance of his Wednesday debate with Quayle in Omaha,
Neb.
   Among the senators advising Bentsen are Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and David Boren of Oklahoma,
Bentsen spokesman Michael McCurry said Friday.
   Bentsen aides and several advisers who helped Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis ready for his debate with
George Bush also were involved in the preparations. Rep. Dennis
Eckart of Ohio has been tapped to stand in as Quayle in practice
sessions.
   Bentsen spent several hours each day during a four-day trip this
week studying briefing books on likely debate topics and plans to
spend Sunday, Monday and Tuesday in Texas in final preparations. He
also is attending a fund-raiser Sunday for his Senate campaign.
Texas law allows him to run for both the vice presidency and
re-election to the Senate.
   The campaign trip, which ended in Washington on Friday with
Bentsen accepting the endorsement of the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket by
the 1.9 million-member National Education Association, offered
contradictory pictures from the Bentsen camp on the upcoming debate.
   Aides repeatedly told reporters Quayle was a proven debater
whose television skills are better than Bentsen's and whose
grilling in the news media has lowered expectations to the point
where it is extremely difficult for Bentsen to win.
   But, the expectations game aside, Bentsen repeatedly portrayed
the Indiana senator as a legislative lightweight, saying Quayle had
an ``empty resume,'' had opposed most of the progressive bills
passed by Congress this year and that he would pray for Bush's
health if the Republican ticket wins the election.
   He added Bush to that attack Friday, saying the vice president's
talk of balancing the federal budget and serving as the education
president is ``as empty as Dan Quayle's resume.''
   Bentsen told the NEA gathering he and Dukakis have lifelong
commitments to education and asked them to contrast that to
education program cuts sponsored by the Reagan administration.
   ``For advocates of public education, the choice is clear,'' the
senator told the teachers' union, which frequently interrupted his
brief speech with applause.
   Bentsen also delivered some tough talk on trade and defense
Friday, promising that if he and Dukakis are elected they will
demand access to the markets of all countries that have free access
to U.S. markets. Bentsen also said he and Dukakis would maintain a
powerful military and nuclear deterrent while calling on U.S.
allies to pay their fair share of ``defending the democracies.''
   Bentsen singled out Japan during that discussion, which took
place at a rally in Charlotte, N.C.. He said Japan pays far too
little of the burden of deploying troops and munitions and that it
should ``belly up'' and bear more of the burden.
</TEXT>
