<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Party     10-01 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Party,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Says Fighting Inflation Is The Top Priority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party says China's top economic
priority for the next two years is to combat inflation, which shot
up about three-fold to more than 20 percent in the past year.
   Officials said Friday they will tighten credit, ban the resale
of raw materials and consumer goods and take other measures to
control a system plagued by hoarding, price-gouging and
profiteering.
   ``The next two years are the most critical period,'' the party's
policy-making Central Committee said Friday in a communique at the
end of a five-day closed meeting.
   ``Significant reform measures aimed at checking inflation should
be taken with urgency,'' said the communique quoted by the official
Xinhua News Agency.
   The committee called for reducing consumer demand and increasing
supplies of food, textiles, consumer products and raw materials in
order to hold down prices, Xinhua said.
   Vice Premier Yao Yilin, head of the State Planning Commission,
said the new policies received unanimous approval during the
Central Committee meeting, attended by 165 of the 175 members and
103 alternates.
   The simultaneous existence of controlled and free markets has
encouraged profiteering, with many factory officials obtaining raw
materials from the state at artificially low prices and then
selling them on the free market for huge profits.
   Inflation has soared from about 7 percent last year to more than
20 percent this year due in part to the failure of provincial and
local officials to comply with repeated orders to approve fewer
loans, cut back on spending and stamp out widespread speculation.
   Loose central bank control and overissuing of currency have also
contributed to the problem.
   Party leaders began signaling in August that a slowdown in price
reform was planned. Many economists consider price reform crucial
to China's decade-long effort to replace cumbersome central
planning mechanisms with more flexible market mechanisms.
   But government-ordered increases in food prices in May combined
with speculation-fueled increases on the free market triggered
widespread public discontent and waves of panic buying.
   Wang Deyan, president of the Bank of China, called for strict
controls on credit as part of the new inflation-fighting policy. He
said heads of branch banks should be punished if they disobeyed
guidelines set by Beijing, the official People's Daily said Friday.
   Wang said his bank will set rigid loan quotas for its branch
offices and no loans will be given for private or hotel
construction or to poorly-managed enterprises.
   He said these measures will ``give full play to the bank's role
in regulating the national economy,'' the paper said.
   In another report Friday, the Economic Daily said new
anti-profiteering measures banned the resale of raw materials
including petroleum, steel, aluminum, tin, rubber, and newsprint as
well as consumer items such as cars, motorcycles and televisions.
   The Industry and Commerce Administration and the Ministry of
Commerce earlier banned the local resale of 22 categories of raw
materials and consumer durables.
   The Central Committee meeting ended shortly before the
government's annual gala reception at the Great Hall of the People
to celebrate the Oct. 1 National Day holiday.
   Inside the Great Hall, bedecked with blinking neon lights,
Premier Li Peng and other top government leaders who usually brush
off reporters' questions commented at length on the economy. Party
General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, who headed the Central Committee
session, did not attend the event.
   In a speech before he toasted the 39th anniversary of the
Communist government, Li said: ``Orders must be obeyed. ... The
whole nation must reach a common understanding and act in unison.''
   Li also gave more economic bad news: Grain production will be
down this year, with the fourth disappointing harvest in a row. He
blamed heavy floods in some areas and prolonged drought in others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wright-CIA     10-01 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wright-CIA,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel Undertakes Informal Probe Of Wright Disclosure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee apparently has
begun an informal investigation into whether Speaker Jim Wright
violated rules against disclosing government secrets when he talked
openly last week about a purported CIA covert operation in
Nicaragua.
   On Friday, the ethics panel asked the House Intelligence
Committee to notify it whether Wright had been given access to
classified information from the spy agency on its activities in the
region.
   The senior Republican on the Intelligence Committee, Rep. Henry
Hyde of Illinois, said he was confident the panel would cooperate
with the request for information, even though it declined earlier
this week to send such information to ethics.
   The ethics committee's request came as GOP members of the
Intelligence Committee said they were prepared to ask the full
House to investigate Wright if action were not forthcoming soon.
   Democrats responded angrily to that announcement, charging that
the move was motivated by politics and by frustrations of Contra
supporters over the perilous state of the anti-government
Nicaraguan rebels.
   ``I think it's mean, I think it's ugly, and I think it's beneath
the dignity of the members of this House,'' said Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich.
   But the move by the ethics committee was a signal that the
Wright investigation was not being ignored, and Republicans seemed
satisfied _ at least for the moment.
   ``What was sought has been accomplished,'' Hyde said. ``I don't
see any point in airing this at this juncture.... We are not
interested in squeezing this for any political advantage. We want
it dealt with.''
   The controversy began Sept. 20, when Wright answered a
reporter's question by saying he had ``clear testimony from CIA
people'' that the agency had recruited agents in Nicaragua to stir
up demonstrations and civil unrest. Wright said the administration
hoped to provoke a crackdown by the leftist Sandinista government
and scuttle peace talks with the Contras.
   Wright later elaborated, saying the information was elicited
from the CIA under congressional questioning. But he subsequently
denied that he had relied on any such information in making his
comments, saying the agency's role in Central America was well
documented in published material. And he has said he feels morally
obligated to talk about any government action that is contrary to
its stated support for the region's peace process.
   The Republican resolution, which still could be brought before
the full House at any time, would require the ethics committee to
investigate the charges and direct other committees _ including
Intelligence _ to cooperate by providing relevant information to
the panel.
   But ethics committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said his
panel's pace did not mean the matter had been shelved, and he
accused Republicans of being too impatient and eager to stir up
public controversy.
   ``I think all of this is hype, just to keep it going,'' Dixon
said, adding that he would not speed up his panel's process solely
to head off a floor debate that could embarrass Wright. ``I have
tried not to react to the political pressure,'' he said.
   Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., and the other Republicans acknowledged
that it would be difficult to pass the resolution in the
Democrat-controlled House but said they believed important
institutional principles were at stake, including cooperation with
the executive branch on intelligence matters. He denied any
partisan motive for the move.
   ``It is election time, obviously, but that hasn't got anything
to do with the reason we are here,'' he said.
   House rules prohibit any disclosure of classified information,
including CIA testimony before the Intelligence Committee.
Suspected violations are subject to investigation by the ethics
committee, which already is probing Wright's financial and other
dealings.
</TEXT>
