<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     10-01 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gruberova Makes Met Debut With `Lucia'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No AMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edita Gruberova won't make an operagoer forget
the excitement of Dame Joan Sutherland or the warmth and pathos of
Beverly Sills singing the title role in ``Lucia di Lammermoor.''
   But she did a fine job Friday night in her first appearance as
Lucia at the Metropolitan Opera.
   Miss Gruberova, who has a clear voice with super-high range,
floated some beautiful pianissimos. She sang all the embellishments
and added some of her own. Her approach was very careful, lessening
excitement a bit.
   Brian Schexnayder sang Lucia's brother. His lustrous baritone is
more an autumn voice than a winter voice. A heavier voice would
better convey the ``heavy'' who makes Lucia marry against her
wishes.
   Tenor Francisco Araiza sang Edgardo, whom Lucia loves. He has a
very attractive middle voice that constricts into a less pleasing
sound at the top of his range. Stanford Olsen sang the smaller part
of Arturo, whom Lucia marries and then stabs to death offstage.
Olsen was a happy surprise. Audiences don't usually hear such a
sweet, firm lyric tenor in this part.
   Edoardo Muller, conducting ``Lucia'' at the Met for the first
time, didn't always seem to be in synch with the chorus but gave
Miss Gruberova every consideration during Lucia's famous mad scene.
In keeping with current practice, she didn't race wildly about but
was gently mad.
   The Met added a scene that it hasn't had in a production of
``Lucia'' in more than 30 years. It's a brief scene right before
the mad scene in which Lucia's brother visits Edgardo to tell him
that she is married.
</TEXT>
