<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b w AM-Budget 6thLd-Writethru a0412-420-427-408 10-01 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0412-420-427-408,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Finishes All Appropriations Bills Minutes Before New
Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines a0412-a0420-a0427-a0408. Minor editing throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress, racing against the clock, completed
work Friday on the last of 13 spending bills just three minutes
before the start of the new fiscal year, even as President Reagan
chided lawmakers for the ``dog-ate-my-homework era of congressional
budgetry.
   It was the first time since 1976 that Congress had passed all 13
separate spending bills.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said the lawmakers'
accomplishment on the fiscal 1989 spending bills ``renewed faith
and confidence in this institution.''
   At 11:57 p.m., senators accepted by voice vote House language on
a $14.3 billion foreign aid measure, finishing a marathon day in
which Congress cleared five appropriations bills for fiscal 1989.
Two minutes later, a puffing House clerk ran into the Senate
chamber carrying the House legislation, technically sealing the
agreement reached by the vote minutes earlier.
   Fiscal 1988 ended at midnight.
   Reagan had planned to hold a late-night signing ceremony at the
White House for the final spending measures. But with Congress
still working, he canceled the ceremony and instead issued a
statement complaining about the ``dog-ate-my-homework era of
congressional budgetry.''
   White House spokesman Bill Harlow said Reagan would have no
comment on the final passage of all 13 bills until Saturday.
   Had Reagan signed the bills before midnight, it would have
marked the first time since 1948 that all 13 spending measures were
enacted before the start of the fiscal year.
   Since that time, the budget process has been marked by squabbles
that have resulted in some or all of the spending measures being
wrapped together. That practice rankles presidents because, as the
bills grow to cover more and more federal agencies, the political
consequences of a veto become more serious.
   Even though the fiscal year opened Saturday without the
president's signature on six of the bills, the effect will be
almost nil.
   Few federal employees work over the weekend. And even without
spending legislation in place, essential workers would report,
including the military, doctors, air traffic controllers and
others. But if all the spending bills are not enacted by Monday,
agencies for which money has not been provided would not be able to
keep their doors open.
   The House opened business Friday by approving a $282 billion
Defense Department spending measure on a 327-77 vote and sent it to
the Senate. The Senate later approved it, but added some provisions
which sent the bill back to the House, as both chambers must
approve identical bills. The House concurred with the changes.
   The Senate also voted 90-4 in favor of a House-approved $46.6
billion agriculture bill, and sent it to Reagan.
   All told, Reagan has signed seven fiscal 1989 appropriations
bills into law, most recently the $10.8 billion transportation bill
on Friday. The first was a $17.8 billion measure for energy and
water projects enacted on July 19.
   As the midnight deadline approached Friday, the Senate gave
final approval to a $3.2 billion District of Columbia
appropriations bill that carried a strong anti-abortion amendment
and gave Georgetown University the right to deny certain rights to
gay groups.
   D.C. Delegate Walter Fauntroy angered by the intrusion into
local affairs, said he would encourage city officials to disobey
the abortion-funding prohibition to trigger a congressionally
mandated shutdown of city government. Such a move would leave
Congress with the responsibility of governing the nation's capital.
   The federal government contributes $537 million to the D.C.
government.
   As the clock ticked on, legislation providing $1.8 billion for
Congress' own operating expenses received final approval. That left
the $14.3 billion foreign aid measure.
   The uncharacteristic rapidity with which the spending measures
were being completed this year is largely due to last November's
budget summit agreement between Reagan and congressional leaders.
That pact set the broad spending targets for 1989, and set a tone
in which administration and Capitol Hill officials consulted
frequently in an effort to resolve disputes.
   ``It shows what can happen when the president and Congress
cooperate,'' Byrd said.
   Last year's budget process produced nothing but partisan
brawling over spending levels and taxes. With neither the
administration nor Congress willing to budge, the beginning of
fiscal 1988 came and went without the passage of a single
appropriations bill.
   What emerged _ and not until late December, three months into
the fiscal year _ was a 1,400-page, $600 billion measure wrapping
all 13 spending bills into one.
   Reagan signed the measure. But in January, he promised on
national television to never again sign an omnibus spending bill,
and scores of lawmakers pledged to send the bills to the White
House one at a time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-GulfTalks Bjt   10-01 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf Talks, Bjt,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General To Try To Break Iran-Iraq Talks Stalemate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Talks expected to begin after 4:30 p.m. EDT. Lead prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
will offer new proposals to end a stalemate in peace talks between
Iran and Iraq, said Greece's foreign minister after he met with
officials from both countries.
   Foreign ministers Tariq Aziz of Iraq and Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran gave no hint of progress, but both expressed cautious optimism
about the negotiations before today's face-to-face meeting.
   The two Persian Gulf neighbors and enemies are observing a
U.N.-brokered cease-fire in their 8-year-old war, which has caused
more than a million casualties.
   Perez de Cuellar and his special representative to the talks,
Swedish U.N. Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson, held separate meetings
Friday evening with Aziz and Velayati.
   All four arranged to meet today for the first round of direct
talks between Aziz and Velayati since the last round of
negotiations ended in Geneva Sept. 13.
   The meeting at the U.N. headquarters will be held under airtight
security.
   ``The building will be buttoned up,'' said a U.S. Secret Service
agent.
   The State Department has provided Velayati with a bullet-proof,
armor-plated blue Cadillac limosine, he said.
   Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulis met separately with
Velayati and Aziz on Friday and later said he discussed the war
with both men.
   ``Efforts have been undertaken on the part of the
secretary-general to resolve the deadlock that has evolved in that
area, and always there is hope that the deadlock will be
overcome,'' Papoulis said.
   Papoulias is the chairman of the Council of Foreign Ministers of
the 12 European Community nations.
   When the Geneva talks halted, Iraq demanded that the next step
must be that the Shatt-al-Arab waterway dividing the two nations be
cleared of sunken ships and silt so it is navigable again. It is
Iraq's only outlet to the Persian Gulf.
   Iran insisted that the remaining provisions of Security
Council's 1987 Resolution 598 be implemented before dealing with
other issues.
   The two belligerents have observed a truce since Aug. 20, the
first demand of Resolution 598, and five days later opened peace
talks, another provision.
   The remaining requirements are to withdraw their forces to the
border; exchange prisoners of war; continue peace talks to settle
their differences; and that an impartial commission be appointed to
apportion blame for the outbreak of the war.
   Aziz was asked on Friday en route to his meeting with Perez de
Cuellar wheter he was hopeful of a breakthrough and he said he was,
but did not elaborate.
   After the meeting, Aziz was asked if any breakthroughs were in
the offing, especially on the Shatt-al-Arab, and he answered:
   ``I don't want to make any hasty conclusions because we have not
yet met the Iranians and we will see if they have anything new,''
suggesting Baghdad is holding fast and looking for compromise on
Iran's part.
   Velayati told reporters when he emerged from his meeting with
Perez de Cuellar: ``We do hope that during these talks ... in New
York we could reach a tangible result, and we hope that we could
reach a concrete conclusion for the implementation of the other
provisions of Resolution 598.''
   His comments indicated Tehran has not altered its bargaining
position.
   Iran's U.N. ambassador, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, said ``We
should be hopeful. Diplomats must always be hopeful; we have no
other choice.''
</TEXT>
