<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DobryninProfile     10-01 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dobrynin Profile,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador to United States an Astute Analyst, Key Adviser</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kremlin Shake-Up, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly F. Dobrynin, Moscow's man in Washington
from the Cuban Missile Crisis to the reform era of Mikhail
Gorbachev, was known in diplomatic circles as an astute analyst of
U.S. affairs and a key foreign policy adviser.
   Dobrynin, 68, retired from his position as secretary of the
powerful Communist Party Central Committee on Friday in a major
reorganization of the top party apparatus that broadened
Gorbachev's base of support.
   Dobrynin's smoothness and ability earned him praise from former
U.S. ambassador to Moscow Malcolm Toon, who called him ``one of the
ablest diplomats of the 20th century.''
   Alexander N. Yakovlev, the Soviet ambassador to Canada during
some of Dobrynin's years in Washington and one of Gorbachev's
closest advisers, was assigned responsibility for international
policy in a streamlined Central Committee structure.
   No reason was given for Dobrynin's retirement from the job in
which he had a key voice on Soviet foreign policy decisions.
President Andrei A. Gromyko, who was Dobrynin's boss for many years
as Soviet foreign minister, also stepped down Friday from the
Communist Party's ruling Politburo.
   The tall and portly Dobrynin was recalled to Moscow in March
1986 after 24 years in Washington. During that time, he became
viewed as the dean of the diplomatic corps and gained respect as an
astute analyst of U.S. policies.
   Far less was known of his work in Moscow, where he was in the
public eye much less than in Washington. In one well-publicized
trip, he accompanied Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze to
Afghanistan in January 1987 before the pro-Soviet government
announced a policy of ``national reconciliation'' with anti-Marxist
rebels.
   In the U.S. capital, Dobrynin personified the back-channel
diplomacy of sensitive, secret dealings between the superpowers.
   He was an unswerving defender of Soviet policies but won respect
of high-ranking U.S. officials for being able to get their point of
view across in the Kremlin.
   Although he appeared largely unchanged by living in the United
States for more than two decades, Dobrynin was fond of taking his
granddaughter to fast food restaurants on Saturdays.
   Dobrynin long had special access to the U.S. State Department,
and secretaries of state invited him in for drinks and private
chats.
   But during the first years of the Reagan administration,
then-Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig revoked Dobrynin's
privilege of using the department's garage entrance and private
elevator, a practice that had allowed Dobrynin to avoid the press.
   Dobrynin, who spoke fluent but heavily accented English, was
born Nov. 16, 1919, near Moscow. His father was a plumber.
   He was an aeronautical engineer during World War II and entered
diplomatic service afterward. He worked at the Foreign Ministry in
Moscow until 1952 when he was sent to Washington as a embassy
counselor.
   He returned to Moscow in 1960 to become chief of the Foreign
Ministry's U.S. and Latin American department. Two years later, he
returned to Washington as ambassador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
