<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     10-01 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says His Superfund Worked Better Than Administration's</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis stood behind his
record on environmental issues, telling California voters that as
Massachusetts governor his state outperformed the Reagan
administration in cleaning up toxic waste.
   Dukakis, stressing the environmental theme as he usually does
when campaigning in California, also said he would convene
``serious summits on the environment'' when dealing with the
Soviets.
   Dukakis flew to this key electoral state Friday and immediately
made a quick visit to the Stringfellow Acid Pits, one of the
nation's most notorious toxic waste sites.
   Then he held a town meeting in Riverside before flying north to
a series of fund-raising events in San Francisco and Sacramento.
The major event on today's schedule was a speech on ocean dumping
at an environmental rally.
   Most of the questions he received in Riverside concerned the
environment, including one about an issue George Bush has raised
effectively against Dukakis.
   The Bush campaign has been running television ads the past week
that show scenes of the pollution in Boston Harbor and that blame
Dukakis for not acting swiftly to clean it up.
   ``I consider the cleanup of Boston Harbor to be one of the finer
achievements of my administration,'' the Massachusetts governor
said. He said that under his leadership, ``the largest single water
cleanup project in America'' was under way to reduce the harbor
pollution.
   The multibillion-dollar project was being carried out with a
minimium of federal assistance, he said. Dukakis' opponents and
critics insist he was part of the problem because he delayed taking
decisive action much earlier.
   Dukakis said people in Riverside who have lived near
Stringfellow should know that his state was the first that passed
``and I'm the first governor who signed a state Superfund law'' to
provide funds to clean up toxic waste dumps.
   ``We've now cleaned up up almost 300 sites and we're working on
another 400,'' he said. ``The current administration has completed
about 25 or 30.''
   Dukakis also said that he discussed the environment Wednesday
when he met with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   ``Environmental pollution knows no boundaries,'' said the
Democratic nominee. ``We're not only going to have serious summits
on arms control, we're going to have serious summits on the
environment.''
   On the flight to California, State Assembly speaker Willie Brown
said ``the environment and drugs will probably be Mr. Dukakis'
strongest issues in California'' against Bush.
   Brown, who supported Jesse Jackson for the Democratic
presidential nomination, said his presence on the Dukakis plane was
evidence the party was united.
   In another part of the West, Dukakis won a newspaper endorsement
from The Seattle Times, which has endorsed only Republican
presidential candidates since 1920.
   The endorsement editorial that will appear in Sunday's editions
said Dukakis had shown ``a broader, deeper understanding of the
economies of the states and nation.''
   Dukakis' campaign on Friday also ran a new television ad during
a break in NBC-TV's Olympic coverage. The 30-second stop, called
``The Packaging of George Bush,'' consists of actors playing Bush
advisers who tell the candidate to ``wrap himself in the American
flag'' because he has no programs of benefit to middle-class
Americans.
</TEXT>
