<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeficitCommission     10-01 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit Commission,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Reduction Panel To End Closed-Door Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level advisory commission on deficit
reduction, after trying to keep out of the spotlight by holding
closed-door meetings, is going back to public hearings.
   The National Economic Commission announced Friday that it will
hold a public session next Wednesday, its first since mid-July.
   The announcement came after one commissioner objected to the
strategy of keeping the sessions secret until after the
presidential election.
   The 12-member panel, which was created by Congress to come up
with solutions to the huge federal budget deficits, held three
meetings in August and September purposely without a quorum to get
around open meeting requirements of the Federal Advisory Committee
Act.
   At those sessions, the commissioners heard testimony on such
politically sensitive topics as Social Security and possible new
sources of revenue to close the gap between spending and taxes.
   The panel, chaired by Democrat Robert Strauss and Republican
Drew Lewis, is working against a Dec. 21 deadline to make its
recommendations to a new president.
   In a speech earlier this week, commission member Dean Kleckner,
president of the American Farm Bureau Federation, said the
commission was wrong to keep its deliberations out of the spotlight
to avoid becoming embroiled in the presidential election.
   ``Should the commission, over the very strong objections of
several of us, become a tax-hike vehicle, then the
revenue-versus-spending issue should be, must be, debated ahead of
Nov. 8,'' he said. ``The people who pay the bill ought to have a
chance to express themselves.''
   Commission spokesman James Hildreth said the commission's
decision to resume public hearings occurred because commissioners
were ``starting to get nervous that they might be technically in
violation (of the law) because too many people would show up.''
   He said that the last briefing session would have actually had
eight members present if airline flights of two commissioners had
not been delayed because of bad weather.
   ``There was just a general uneasiness that perhaps we had better
do something to make sure we didn't get involved in any diverting
controversy about violating laws,'' Hildreth said. ``We are not
trying to do anything illegal, secretive or anything else.''
   Then-Treasury Secretary James A. Baker had urged the commission
in March to keep its deliberations out of the public eye during the
presidential campaign. Baker had argued that the panel's findings
would carry more weight if they did not become embroiled in
election-year politics. Baker is now chairman of George Bush's
presidential campaign.
   The commission is composed of six Republicans and six Democrats
with two other members to be named by the president-elect after
Nov. 8.
   Hildreth said no decisions had been made at any of the meetings
so far and none will be made until after the president-elect
appoints his members.
   The Wednesday session will hear testimony on government benefit
programs other than Social Security and new priorities that the
government may be asked to fund in a new administration. Hildreth
said two other sessions on health care and defense are planned
before the election and they would also be open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
