<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Japan-Markets     10-01 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Markets,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices slumped during the last trading day of
the week Saturday and shed all the gains made the previous day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed the
half-day session at 27,700.13 points, down a heavy 223.54 points or
0.80 percent. The index, a 223.54-point winner Friday, lost exactly
the same amount it gained the previous day.
   ``Share prices were lower mainly because it's Saturday when
trading usually slows down,'' said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   He said Japan's economic outlook was quite good for investment
and added that the Nikkei's decline was not serious.
   Other dealers said the index dropped because investors were
inclined to sell stocks for profit after the gain Friday.
Otherwise, there was no negative economic factor in the market,
except for a lack of energy, they said.
   Due to the lack of specific direction, trading was rather thin
with volume on the first section totaling 550 million shares.
   The foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
