<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FeedGrain     10-01 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Feed Grain,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Changes Rules On Set-Aside Farm Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who grow corn and most other feed
grains in 1989 will have to idle only 10 percent of their base
acreage to qualify for price supports and other government benefits.
   This year farmers had to set aside 20 percent under the acreage
reduction program, or ARP, to qualify for benefits. But drought cut
yields sharply and siphoned off much of the nation's grain
stockpile. Thus, restrictions were eased on next year's plantings.
   Signup dates will be announced later, Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng said Friday.
   Besides corn, the 10 percent ARP will apply to 1989 crops of
sorghum and barley. Oats will have a 5 percent idling requirement,
the same as in 1988.
   Lyng also announced some other provisions of the 1989 feed grain
program including:
   _Target prices for 1989 corn will be $2.84 per bushel, down from
$2.93 this year; sorghum, $2.70 per bushel, down from $2.78;
barley, $2.43 per bushel, down from $2.51; and oats, $1.50 per
bushel, down from $1.55.
   _Price support loan rates for corn will be $1.65 per bushel,
down from $1.77 this year; sorghum, $1.57 per bushel, down from
$1.68; barley, $1.34 per bushel, down from $1.44; oats, 85 cents
per bushel, down from 90 cents; and rye (which has no ARP or target
price), $1.40 per bushel, down from $1.50.
   _No marketing loan program will be implemented for feed grains
in 1989, unchanged from 1988.
   _Malting barley will not be exempt from acreage limitation
requirements established for the 1989 program.
   _There will be no paid land diversion, a feature that would pay
farmers for taking additional acres from production.
   In another report, the department said U.S. grain inventories as
of Sept. 1 included an estimated 4.26 billion bushels of corn from
previous years' harvests, down 13 percent from 4.88 billion bushels
a year earlier.
   Sorghum stocks were at 663 million bushels, down 11 percent from
743 million bushels a year earlier.
   Barley stocks were estimated at 441 million bushels, but there
was no comparison with a year earlier. No oats figures were
reported for Sept. 1.
   The Sept. 1 soybean inventory, at 302 million bushels, was down
31 percent from a year ago's 436 million bushels.
   Wheat stockpiles were reported at 2.24 billion bushels, down 25
percent from Sept. 1, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Shuttle-ComfortStation Bjt   10-01 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Comfort Station, Bjt,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Era For Shuttle, Same Old Problem For Astronauts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's launch may start a new
era for NASA, but the astronauts still face one problem that's
always bothered space travelers _ an uncomfortable comfort station.
   During the 32 months the shuttle was grounded after Challenger,
NASA made more than 200 changes aboard the craft, but improving the
space potty was not one of them. Astronauts still must contend with
an orbiting john that has been known to turn a simple call of
nature into a complex maneuver.
   When the shuttle toilet was first installed, it was said to be
the final solution to a problem that has bothered astronauts since
space travel began.
   Early astronauts learned that responding to a simple human need
in space required a lot more effort than back home. On Earth, there
is gravity and something deposited somewhere tends to stay there.
But in space there is no gravity and anything not tied down or
contained tends to float around.
   During the Gemini and Apollo programs, engineers designed
systems that used flowing air to collect liquid wastes. For solid
wastes, there were blue plastic bags that sealed after use.
Astronauts hated the bags. Some resisted using the bags so strongly
that they required medical attention upon return to Earth.
   For the shuttle, engineers designed a space toilet filled with
machinery and valves that promised the final solution for both
genders. The problem was to be solved with whirling blades,
freeze-drying and collection by vacuum.
   It was an almost immediate failure.
   The system was so complicated that it required some fundamental
toilet training on the ground. And once in space, astronauts found
that equipment designed to remain pristine and fresh often became
clogged and cranky. After some missions, the shuttle returned to
Earth smelling like an overused portable toilet.
   The system was modified time after time, but the complaints
continued.
   Searching for answers, Johnson Space Center officials held
closed door meetings with each returning astronaut, hoping that the
intrepid space fliers would recount personal anecdotes that would
solve the problem. But the terrors of the space toilet continued.
   Now an engineer at aerospace contractor Hamilton Standard Co. in
Windsor Locks, Conn., has proposed a system that officials hope
will silence complaints.
   Don W. Rethke, nicknamed ``Dr. Flush'' by his co-workers,
designed a toilet that he says is simple, sanitary and odor-free.
   Rethke said he originally designed the system for the space
station, the proposed orbiting laboratory where astronauts will
live for months.
   The Hamilton Standard design uses collection bags that are
mounted in a device that resembles the commode back home. The bags
are automatically sealed, compressed and stored in canisters. And
it's simple. Astronauts merely push a button and wait for the
machine to cycle. They then insert a new bag for the next user and
go on their way.
   Rethke said the space station system will collect and purify
liquid waste and even recycle it for hygienic use.
   NASA officials were so impressed with the concept they asked Dr.
Flush to submit a proposed design for the space shuttle. Other
aerospace contractors also may submit designs, but it was Rethke's
ideas that got the plan started.
   ``They (NASA engineers) are tired of trying to solve the old
problem,'' he said. ``This is a very simple system that may be the
solution.''
   America's astronaut corps hopes so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-S&LRescues     10-01 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Rescues,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Arrange Six More Bailouts In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulators have
wrapped up a six-week, $16 billion spending spree by pledging $2.5
billion to the rescue of six ailing thrifts in Texas.
   The acquiring companies have agreed to put up $153 million in
two separate deals and in return will acquire control of S&Ls with
assets worth $4.4 billion.
   Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, who has
been criticized by members of Congress for agreeing to ``thin
deals'' bringing little private money to S&L rescues, said, ``The
millions of dollars ... being invested ... proves again the Texas
thrift market is ... an excellent business opportunity.''
   However, a review of nine packages rescuing 42 Texas
institutions this year shows that regulators have committed $22
billion in aid, while bringing in capital of only about $300
million.
   In the biggest deal announced Friday, a joint venture headed by
Temple-Inland Inc. of Dibold, Texas, is getting $1.49 billion in
assistance from the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. to
acquire three institutions with combined assets of $3.19 billion.
   Temple-Inland, a forestry company, will get 80 percent of the
new institution's stock, while Trammel Crow Co., a Dallas-based
real estate development and management company, and Mason Best Co.,
a private merchant banking firm also based in Dallas, will get 10
percent each.
   Together, the three firms are investing $128 million.
   In the second transaction, Club Corporation International of
Dallas, one of the nation's largest operators of private dining and
country clubs, has received a commitment from the FSLIC worth
$999.5 million. For an investment of $25 million, Club is getting
control of three institutions with combined assets of $1.2 billion.
   In six weeks beginning Aug. 18, the FSLIC, which guarantees S&L
deposits up to $100,000, has committed more than $16 billion to
shut down or merge more than 60 institutions, including 32 in Texas
and 14 in Oklahoma, states hard hit by problems in the oil industry
and by lax S&L regulation.
   The recent spate of transactions represent about half the 124
S&L cases resolved by regulators so far this year.
   Wall, the nation's top S&L regulator, had announced he was
spending as much federal assistance as possible before the 1988
fiscal year ended Friday so that much of it would not count toward
the budget deficit. However, he conceded this week that he had been
mistaken and that there were only a few minor advantages to rushing.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has said the recent string of
transactions are a ``political shell game'' by Republicans intended
postpone any crisis until after the election.
   The bank board's spree has intensified debate over whether a
taxpayer bailout of the S&L insurance fund will be needed next
year. So far, the FSLIC has received all of its money through an
assessment on the industry.
   Congress' General Accounting Office has estimated it will cost
$45 billion to $50 billion to clean up the industry. Of 3,000
institutions nationwide, 500 are considered insolvent and another
400 close to insolvent.
   Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch, is estimating
that if the GAO pricetag proves correct, the federal budget deficit
over the next three years will be nearly $15 billion a year higher.
   The S&L crisis emerged as an issue in the presidential campaign
on Thursday when Democrat Michael S. Dukakis blamed the mess on the
deregulation policies of the Reagan administration. The campaign of
Republican George Bush, in turn, has attributed the problem to
foot-dragging by the Democratic Congress.
   The three institutions being acquired by Temple-Inland and its
partners are: Guaranty Federal Savings and Loan Association,
headquartered in Dallas with 33 branches; First Federal Savings and
Loan of Austin, with 22 branches, and Delta Savings of Texas, with
eight branches in and around Alvin, Texas.
   Among the reasons listed by the bank board for the failure of
the three are: high-risk lending to avoid recognizing losses,
conflicts of interest, unauthorized securities trading, speculative
commercial loans, poor underwriting practices and deficient real
estate appraisals.
   Club International, through a wholly owned subsidiary, First
Federal Financial Corp., is taking control of three Austin-based
S&Ls: CreditBanc Savings Association, Franklin Savings Association
and Great West Savings Bank.
   In two small deals in Indiana on Friday, the bank board provided
$16.7 million in assistance to rescue Citizens Federal Savings and
Loan Association of New Castle and United Savings Association of
Central Indiana, Tipton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
