<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Say Sandinistas Planning Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels accused the leftist
government of amassing troops and artillery for a major offensive
as another government extension to a six-month cease-fire went into
effect today.
   Radio Liberacion, the rebels' clandestine radio, also said
Friday the government provoked ``incidents with the Honduran army''
along Nicaragua's northern border.
   On Thursday, Nicaragua's Sandinista government announced its
fifth unilateral extension of the cease-fire that began March 23,
though peace talks stalled June 9. The ban on offensive operations
runs until Oct. 31.
   The U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have said the truce is
indefinite. Their Radio Liberacion broadcast said the Sandinistas
were taking advantage of the cease-fire to prepare the offensive.
   After U.S. military aid to the Contras ended in February, the
bulk of the rebel force retreated to camps on Honduran territory
near the frontier. Both rebels and Sandinistas allege frequent
truce violations.
   Nicaragua's acting foreign minister, Javier Chamorro Mora, sent
a formal protest to Honduras Thursday in which he accused the
Honduran armed forces of six border incursions and three violations
of Nicaraguan airspace in September.
   A report Thursday in the official Sandinista newspaper Barricada
said Nicaraguan troops fired on the intruding aircraft in one
recent incident.
   Honduras denied the reports.
