<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SeaRescue     10-01 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sea Rescue,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishermen Survive 32 Days Adrift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAURANGA, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two fishermen survived 32 days
adrift in a small boat by catching fish and drinking their blood,
they said today after being admitted to a hospital in New Zealand.
   Iaira Mauerere, 32, and Sera Toaea, 28, both Kiribati islanders,
were picked up by a South Korean refrigerated cargo ship on
September 21 after drifting 1,500 miles.
   They were transported to the New Zealand port of Tauranga after
being discovered by the cargo vessel Kohufu. They were expected to
be released from the hospital this afternoon. Neither was seriously
hurt.
   ``Fish was the only way we survived,'' Mauerere said from
Tauranga Hospital.
   The pair's ordeal began on August 20 when Mauerere, an assistant
fisheries officer for the Kiribati Governments Fisheries Division,
invited Toaea, a fisherman, to join him on a six-hour trip to
deliver three men to an island in the Kiribati group.
   They set off from Tarawa, the island capital, in a Fisheries
Division 28-foot fibreglass open boat with an outboard motor.
   On the return trip, the motor broke down.
   The men had only a basket of babai, a vegetable similar to a
potato, some coconuts and some drinking water.
   To protect themselves from the sun and cool winds at night, they
pulled up some of the interior boards in the base of the boat and
erected a shelter, tied together by trawler line.
   After nine days the food ran out. On the 18th day the water ran
out.
   During the ordeal they slept, fished and swam. They ate the fish
raw.
   Mauerere said they had dried fish on board but once their water
was used up they had to survive on raw fresh fish to keep up their
moisture intake.
   He said the duo recalled reading about others who had survived
at sea by sucking blood from the tails of fish.
   ``We were a bit scared about drinking this but thought, `Let's
try. This is the only way we have to survive,''' he said.
   Both men said they vomited, but managed to glean sufficient
moisture from the fish blood.
   ``We were lucky to be saved,'' Mauerere said. ``Sera was upset
because he thought we could have died. I said, `No, get rid of
those bad memories. We have to start a new life on this beautiful
boat.'''
   The men, both married, spent an additional eight days on the
South Korean vessel before sighting land.
</TEXT>
