<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     10-01 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kabul Echoes Soviet Criticism Of Alleged Pakistani Violations Of
Afghan Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan officials have reiterated Soviet
claims that Pakistan is sheltering, training and arming Islamic
rebels who launch raids across the border into Afghanistan.
   The provision of ``modern weapons, including Stingers,
long-range artillery and mortars and ground-to-ground rockets to
the extremist opposition groups and their transfer to Afghanistan
is continuing,'' said Abdul Wakil, Kabul's foreign minister, on
Friday.
   The United States ``is still continuing the dispatch of weapons
and equipment to armed extremist groups,'' he continued, accusing
Pakistani militias of joining attacks in the Afghan regions of Spin
Boldak, Kandahar and the Kunars.
   Pakistan's ``centers of of training, arming and equiping of
armed extremist groups on its territory have not been dismantled,''
Wakil said in his speech to the 43rd General Assembly.
   He contended that ``Afghanistan has never resorted to small- or
large-scale border violations either from land or air and has
nothing to do with the internal incidents occurring in its
neighboring countries.''
   Pakistan says Afghan warplanes have mounted numerous air raids
on Pakistan's border villages and Afghan refugee camps to punish
the rebels, and also accuses Kabul of sponsoring terrorist bombings
in Pakistan.
   Wakil said that Kabul has brought 547 cases of violations of the
Geneva Accords on Afghanistan to the attention of Pakistan and the
U.N. Good Office Mission to Afghanistan and Pakistan (UNGOMAP).
   He accused Pakistan of delaying UNGOMAP's investigation of the
alleged shipment and transfer of weapons across the border ``on the
pretext of the existence of tribal conflicts and lack of security.''
   Soviet Foreign Ministry Gennady Gerasimov said Thursday that
UNGOMAP officials are ``not doing their job properly'' and should
be investigated by the secretary-general if future peacekeeping
forces are to be approved.
   The Afghan Accords, signed April 14 in Geneva by Pakistan and
Afghanistan, with the Soviets and Americans as guarantors, call for
the Soviets to withdraw more than 100,000 Red Army troops from
Afghanistan, and for Afghanistan and Pakistan to respect each
other's territorial integrity.
   On Tuesday, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnaze said
the Soviets had finished the first part of their troop withdrawal,
but had not yet begun the second phase, and said it depended on
whether the violations of the accord cease.
   U.N. observers have agreed that half the Soviet troops withdrew
by Aug. 15, so Shevardnadze's statement meant the Red Army retreat
has stopped for the last six weeks. The withdrawal began May 15,
and is to be complete by Feb. 15, 1989.
   Diego Cordovez, who mediated the Afghan Accord when he was a
U.N. undersecretary, said Thursday: ``I am surprised that Mr.
Gerasimov has been complaining about the monitoring mechanism
(UNGOMAP), because I had a one-and-a-half-hour meeting with Mr.
Shevardnadze and he said nothing to me about it.''
   Cordovez recently left his U.N. post to become foreign minister
of Ecuador.
</TEXT>
