<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FBI-Hispanics Bjt   10-01 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Hispanics, Bjt,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hispanics Hopeful About Change After FBI Found Guilty In Racial
Bias Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for the 311 Hispanic FBI agents
who successfully sued the agency for ethnic discrimination say they
hope the ruling will have a ``domino effect'' in rectifying bias.
   ``It's a landmark decision because discrimination against
Hispanics in this society is pervasive,'' said Antonio Silva,
co-counsel for the agents in the class action suit.
   The other co-counsel, Hugo Rodriguez, said Friday's decision
determined that the Department of Justice, of which the FBI is a
part, discriminates.
   ``If they do, it exists in other institutions in this country,''
he said.
   ``We're hoping that it'll have a domino effect, that people will
look at themselves and say, `Let's anticipate the problem before we
have it.'''
   The attorneys spoke at a news conference hours after U.S.
District Judge Lucius Bunton issued a 95-page opinion Friday that
said the FBI was guilty of ``a pattern and practice of
discrimination relating to conditions of employment and
promotions.''
   Bunton said the question of damages will be dealt with later.
   FBI Director William Sessions said he was disappointed by the
ruling, but added, ``discrimination has no place in the FBI.'' He
said the agency will decide later whether to appeal.
   In the meantime, he said, the FBI will continue to strengthen
its discrimination-complaint process and management-assessment
program.
   ``The FBI and I, as the director, are committed to increasing
the number of minority and female agents within the FBI's ranks
while ensuring promotional opportunities for these agents,''
Sessions said.
   The FBI's 437 Hispanic agents comprise 4.5 percent of the 9,574
agents; Hispanics make up about 8 percent of the U.S. population.
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh said he plans to meet with
Sessions to discuss the decision.
   ``It obviously raises some concern, and we'll follow through on
it,'' he said.
   The plaintiffs argued during a two-week, non-jury trial in
August that the FBI promotes Hispanic agents slower and assigns
them less-desirable jobs than other agents.
   The same could be said of other employers, Rodriguez said,
adding that Hispanic employees from several government agencies and
private corporations have called him to seek advice about what to
do about alleged discrimination.
   ``If I was a CEO of a major corporation, I think I would take a
long, hard look, not only at my product line as to whether we
address the Hispanic audience, but whether we are doing what is
just to Hispanic employees,'' Rodriguez said.
   Bunton agreed with the Hispanic agents' claims that they were
usually assigned to Spanish-language wiretaps, even if non-Hispanic
agents who were more fluent in Spanish were available.
   Working wiretaps is boring, lonely, uncomfortable work, agents
testified, and the low-glamour job goes unrecognized and unrewarded
when promotions are handed out.
   Bunton agreed with that, too, as well as with agents' assertions
that Hispanics are more likely to be called on to do dangerous
undercover work, even when non-Hispanics could do the job as well.
   The judge also accepted the plaintiffs' arguments that the
agency's discrimination-complaint process is weak, and that
Hispanics are rated unfairly low in the management-assessment
program, which they must complete with high scores to be considered
for higher management positions.
   ``Justice has been done,'' said FBI agent Bernardo ``Matt''
Perez, who was the highest-ranked Hispanic in the FBI when he filed
the original lawsuit five years ago. ``We now feel that we are
complete, first-rate American citizens and we have complete rights.
   ``This is going to better the FBI, and I hope that Sessions will
read this very closely.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Lobbying     10-01 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lobbying,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House To Vote On New Lobbying Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House vote is expected next week on
legislation that would impose the first-ever restrictions on
lobbying by ex-members of Congress and former presidents and vice
presidents.
   The House Judiciary Committee, by voice vote Friday, cleared the
measure for floor action late next week. In addition to its new
restrictions, the bill would expand existing lobbying prohibitions
on former executive branch employees.
   Senior Vice President Ann McBride, of the self-styled citizens'
lobby Common Cause, called the committee vote ``a major step
forward in the battle to enact this important ethics legislation.''
   The Senate already has approved its own set of lobbying
restrictions for those who quit the executive branch or leave
Congress. Both measures are aimed at those who leave the government
and then immediately lobby their former colleagues _ usually on
issues with which they were involved.
   The American Civil Liberties Union has sounded a cautionary
note, writing lawmakers that ``wholesale reform of the ethics laws
is neither necessary nor desirable. That is so because lobbying
activity is political speech that is at the core of the First
Amendment.''
   Indeed, during committee debate, several panel members who voted
for the legislation argued the new restrictions could violate the
constitutional right to free speech. And they said there was no
evidence of wrongdoing by ex-lawmakers-turned-lobbyists.
   Congress wrote the current set of anti-lobbying laws in the
post-Watergate 1978 Ethics in Government Act. Lawmakers did not
include themselves in the restrictions because they believed all
the abuses were in the executive branch.
   The Judiciary Committee added an amendment this week to include
former presidents and vice presidents in the restrictions, but it
defeated a proposal to restrict former federal judges from
appearing before their ex-colleagues for a year after leaving the
bench.
   Under the House bill, members of Congress would be banned for a
year from representing someone before any current member, officer
or employee of the house where they served. The restriction would
not apply to speeches or personal advice.
   Members' former personal office staffers and ex-committee
staffers would be prohibited from contacting their ex-bosses and
colleagues for the year-long period.
   The bill also would prevent former executive branch officers
from even ``aiding and advising'' someone on particular matters
they worked on in government. The language is aimed at
behind-the-scenes strategists who might direct lobbying efforts
without actually making government contacts themselves.
   In cases where the former officials had a policy or program
under their ``official responsibility,'' the bill also would
prevent them from ``aiding or advising'' for two years after
leaving government.
   The former executive branch officials already are banned from
``representing'' clients directly before the government for that
period.
   The measure also would impose a one-year ban on representing,
aiding and advising someone on a trade matter which was under the
ex-employee's official responsibility _ or in which he participated
personally in the last year of government service.
   There also would be changes in restrictions and coverage for
senior executive branch personnel, who generally would face a
one-year cooling-off period before lobbying former colleagues and
agencies.
   The House bill also would add civil penalties for violating the
lobbying law, thus giving the Justice Department a new option
against violators in cases where criminal penalties would not be
pursued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
