<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Thornburgh     10-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blame Congress For Drug Agent Shortages, Thornburgh Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blame for shortages of drug agents rests with
Congress, not the Reagan administration, says Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, who also pressed the Senate to act on a backlog of
nominees for federal judgeships.
   ``We are hearing these days on the campaign trail dramatic calls
for beefed-up anti-drug personnel _ more Drug Enforcement
Administation agents, more FBI agents, more prosecutors and so
on,'' Thornburgh told judges and lawyers Friday at the Philadelphia
Bar Association's annual conference.
   ``I hope those who are speaking this way in public will also
communicate the message directly to the Congress. For this
administration has gone to the Hill year after year with requests
for funds for more employees in our anti-drug efforts,'' he said.
   Thornburgh also pressed the Senate to confirm 29 pending
judicial nominations before the November elections. He said there
was ``no assurance that these highly qualified men and women will
be confirmed and positioned to fill crucial vacancies in our
federal courts before the Senate adjourns.''
   Among the nominees waiting for a hearing and a vote is
Philadelphia attorney Jay Waldman, a friend of Thornburgh's and one
of his former top advisers when Thornburgh was governor of
Pennsylvania.
   On another matter, Thornburgh told reporters he would meet with
FBI Director William Sessions to review a federal court ruling
Friday that the FBI discriminated against Hispanic agents in
promotions and working conditions.
   ``It obviously raises some concern, and we'll follow through on
it,'' Thornburgh said.
   In his speech, Thornburgh did not mention Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis, who has made the war on
drugs a central part of his campaign. Dukakis has pledged to double
the 2,800 DEA agents over five years, beginning with an addition of
600 next year, and to add 800 new federal prosecutors in an effort
to speed up handling of drug cases.
   Thornburgh will chair his first drug policy board Monday since
becoming attorney general and said Reagan would attend for a review
of the anti-drug bills currently in Congress.
   The policy board is a Cabinet-level group which sets the course
for the Reagan administration's efforts against drugs.
</TEXT>
