<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Prop65Lawsuit     10-01 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prop 65 Lawsuit,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Sues Over Tobacco Product Warnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has filed a lawsuit against
stores and manufacturers for allegedly failing to inform California
consumers about cancer-causing substances in tobacco products.
   State Attorney General John Van de Kamp said at a news
conference Friday that the lawsuit was filed in San Francisco
Superior Court against eight major retail chains, 25 manufacturers
of 200 brand named tobacco products and the Ingredient
Communication Council, a manufacturers and retailers group.
   The lawsuit, filed in the first major enforcement under a state
toxics warning law, seeks civil penalties up to $2,500 a day per
violation and could reach ``millions if not hundreds of millions of
dollars,'' Van de Kamp said.
   Resolution of this ``landmark'' case should set standards and
``send out a warning'' for other products containing chemicals
identified by state health authorities as known to cause cancer or
birth defects, Van de Kamp said.
   The U.S. Surgeon General requires warnings about cancer-causing
risks on packages of cigarettes, smokeless tobacco and chewing
tobacco. But cigars, pipe tobacco and roll-your-own tobacco require
no federal warnings.
   Deputy Attorney General Edward Weil said most stores named in
the lawsuit recently began some form of warnings, but investigators
have to determine if they are adequate.
   Van de Kamp said warnings on individual products probably would
be easiest and most effective, but many manufacturers don't want
warnings on goods shipped outside California and can't control
distribution to prevent that.
   Some tobacco manufacturers sent retailers warning signs after
the Safe Drinking Water and Toxic Enforcement Act of 1986 was
approved by voters, Weil said, but stores didn't post them. The law
is commonly known as Proposition 65.
   Most of the warning effort until recently was an 8{-by-11-inch
flyer from the manufacturers group, ICC, that is posted in stores.
   The ICC, which includes 60 manufacturers, retailers and
agricultural producers, provides the signs and maintains the 800
number. It was sued for allegedly misleading consumers and others
into believing that the phone service provides a legally adequate
warning.
   The ICC said that since February it has run newspaper
advertisements and has 62,000 signs in stores.
   Stores named in the lawsuit are Safeway, Ralph's, Lucky's, Alpha
Beta, Vons, Albertson's, Raley's and Thrifty.
   Manufacturers include: Culbro Corp., General Cigar, Consolidated
Cigar, American Tobacco, Brown & Williamson Tobacco, Royal
Factories, Sutliff Tobacco, Pinkerton Tobaccco, M&N Cigar, United
States Tobacco, Swedish Tobacco, Douwe Egberts, Lane Ltd., Larus &
Bros., Lorillard Inc., Havatampa, Phillies Cigar, Avanti Cigar,
Benson Int., John Middleton Inc., JNO H. Swisher & Son, House of
Windsor Inc. and Republic Tobacco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Homeless-Housing     10-01 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless-Housing,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Administration Violated Homeless Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has defied a
congressional mandate by failing to make available surplus federal
property to the homeless, a federal judge has ruled.
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch said the
administration's interpretation of the 1987 McKinney Act
``arbitrarily restricts the scope of the statute.''
   Gasch said the law, named after the late Rep. Stewart B.
McKinney, R-Conn., who died a few months after it was enacted in
1987, ``is designed to make surplus federal property available to
assist the homeless.''
   Agreeing with the National Coalition for the Homeless, he said
only 12 facilities have been identified as underused by federal
agencies and only two have been made available to the homeless.
   Department of Housing and Urban Development spokesman Bob Nipp
said the decision will require the agency to review federal surveys
of surplus buildings to determine which are suitable for housing.
   HUD general counsel J. Michael Dorsey said he did not know how
many properties would be involved. He said the order, however, does
not apply to single-unit dwellings taken over by HUD or the
Veterans Administration because of defaults on government-backed
housing loans.
   Sales of HUD houses will continue, said Dorsey who described the
decision as generally positive because it could help identify
additional buildings that might be used for the homeless.
   ``The order directs us to do more in more detail than we thought
we had done in substantial compliance with the law,'' he said.
   The decision said: ``It's unreasonable to suggest that Congress
chose to lease to the homeless half-empty properties and properties
which are used part of the time, but not properties which are
wholly unoccupied.''
   Gasch said, ``The court is persuaded that the defendants are not
properly implementing the (law). Pitifully few of the numerous
unused federal properties are being evaluated for their suitability
to assist the homeless. Those that are found to be suitable are not
being made available to homeless providers.''
   Ms. Maria Foscarinis, who represented the homeless coalition,
called the ruling a ``terrific decision.''
   ``The judge clearly and strongly holds that the administration
has been violating the law in not making available underused
federal property to the homeless,'' she said.
   Ms. Foscarinis said in a telephone interview from New York that
the significance of the ruling is that ``tens of thousands of
properties across the country can now be used to save lives.''
   She said the buildings, now standing vacant or partially used,
include barracks on military bases, Veteran Administration
hospitals and Post Office buildings.
   Nine days ago, Gasch refused to bar the Department of Housing
and Urban Development from selling single-family homes it had
acquired through mortgage foreclosures to the highest bidder.
   He issued an order denying a preliminary injunction requested by
a coalition of advocates for the homeless who had sought to block
HUD from selling 47,000 foreclosed houses in its inventory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
