<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Papandreou     10-01 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Papandreou,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Prime Minister `Satisfactory' After Heart Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAREFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou was reported in satisfactory condition today after
successfully undergoing a six-hour heart operation.
   Egyptian-born Magdi Yacoub, one of Britain's top heart surgeons
who lead the medical team that performed the operation, said in a
statement that the 69-year-old Papandreou was progressing
satisfactorily in the intensive care unit of Harefield Hospital.
   The operation at the hospital 17 miles northwest of central
London took place Friday.
   Papandreou regained consciousness Friday night after the
operation and was visited by his daughter and three sons, said
Vasilis Kapetanyannis, a Greek Embassy press officer at the
hospital.
   Kapetanyannis made no mention of the prime minister's friend
Dimitra Liani, a former stewardess with the Greek national airline
Olympic Airways who was shown in news pictures earlier this month
strolling with Papandreou in the hospital grounds.
   But state-run Greek television said 34-year-old Ms. Liani was
among a small group allowed into the operating room Friday.
   Papandreou, currently president of the 12-nation European
Economic Community under its rotating presidency system, flew to
London Aug. 25 after his heart condition suddenly worsened.
   He underwent pre-surgical treatment for a narrowing of the
aorta, the main blood vessel carrying blood from the heart. Greek
officials said the main operation was delayed until Friday to clear
a liver disorder linked to the heart problem.
   After Papandreou arrived in Britain, his government announced he
would divorce Margaret, his American-born wife of 37 years. Ms.
Liani is divorcing her husband, architect Alexis Kapopoulous, 43, a
former prominent member of the pro-Maoist Revolutionary Communist
Party. Papandreou has said he plans to marry her.
   Embassy staff said Mrs. Papandreou, the former Margaret Chant of
Elmhurst, Ill., was not in London. Papandreou married her in 1951
when he was teaching economics at the University of Minnesota.
   On Friday, before the operation, Ms. Liani told a reporter: ``I
am praying for a good result.''
   Embassy press attache Dr. Nicholas Papadakis said Friday night:
``Everything is fine. The operation was successful.''
   Shortly after the operation was completed, hospital general
manager David Thomson told a news conference: ``The prime minister
of Greece today (Friday) underwent an operation for replacement of
his aortic valve using a human valve. This was combined with
insertion of three bypass grafts and the clearing of the diseased
coronary artery, to improve the heart function.''
   After reading the statement in English, Thomson left the room
irritably as Giannis Floris, the Greek minister for health, welfare
and social insurance, began explaining the medical terms in Greek
to the 50 Greek press, radio and TV representatives present.
   Papandreou, who will be 70 next Feb. 5, was first elected prime
minister in October 1981 when his Panhellenic Socialist Movement
(PASOK) won a landslide victoy. He won a second term in June 1985.
</TEXT>
