<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pilots-Drugs     10-01 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilots-Drugs,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictments Charge Pilots With Lying About Drug, Alcohol
Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indictments charging 27 pilots with
concealing drug and alcohol-related convictions are the first of
hundreds expected from a nationwide investigation, officials said.
   Twenty-seven commercial, private and student pilots were
indicted Friday, accused of failing to reveal the convictions on
medical certificates submitted to the Federal Aviation
Administration for their pilot's license.
   The indictments were the first in a nationwide crackdown on drug
and alcohol abuse in the transportation industry, federal
authorities said.
   ``The inspector general's office currently has investigations
under way in all 50 states, and hundreds of further such
indictments are expected,'' Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley
said in Washington.
   Twelve current or former commercial pilots were among those
charged, including a pilot with Delta Air Lines who works as a
second officer aboard an L-1011. That pilot and a former Pan
American pilot were the only ones identified as employees of major
passenger carriers.
   A Delta spokeswoman in Atlanta said the pilot would be suspended
once the airline is formally notified of the indictment.
   All but three of the 27 are from Florida.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Genzman said authorities knew of no mishaps
involving the individuals charged.
   The pilot-applicants stated on their medical certificates they
had no record of traffic or other convictions when in fact they had
been convicted of drug or alcohol-related offenses, according to
the indictment.
   The convictions included drunken driving, possession of
marijuana and trafficking in cocaine.
   Investigators tracked down the pilots by matching computer files
of the FAA with those of motor vehicle departments and the FBI.
   A conviction would not necessarily preclude a pilot from getting
a medical certificate and pilot's license, said FAA spokesman Fred
Farrar.
   But he said a past conviction would cause an FAA medical
examiner to ``look long and hard at the circumstances. He may have
concluded (the pilot) should not have a medical certificate.''
   Burnley said the charges were ``indicative of the serious
problem of drug and alcohol abuse, which has permeated all walks of
life and all professions in our society.''
   The charges grew out of a two-year investigation that began with
an audit of the national driver's registry to uncover alcohol or
drug-related traffic violations, said Ben Lorigo of the
Transportation Department's inspector general's office in
Washington.
   The Transportation Department has proposed a broad range of drug
tests, including random tests, of commercial airline pilots and
other flight crew personnel.
   If convicted, the pilots could face at least five years in
prison and fines ranging from $5,000 to $250,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
