<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReedTrial     10-01 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reed Trial,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Lawmaker Who Tried To Lower Rebel Flag Guilty Of Extortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Reed, a longtime state lawmaker and
Alabama NAACP president, says he won't give up his legislative seat
despite his conviction for accepting $10,000 to try to obtain early
parole for a convicted murderer.
   But Attorney General Don Siegelman, citing the Alabama
Constitution and state law, said Reed's conviction disqualified him
as a state representative and he must resign immediately.
   ``I'm not necessarily shocked, but I am disappointed,'' Reed
said of the jury's verdict Friday.
   At a news conference, the Tuskegee Democrat continued to blame
his prosecution on his attempt to remove the Confederate flag from
atop the Alabama Capitol _ a move that drew national attention. His
trial was moved to Mobile because of publicity about the case in
Montgomery.
   ``You know and I know were it not for the Confederate battle
flag I probably would not be here today,'' he said.
   Reed and 13 other black legislators await trial in state court
in Montgomery on misdemeanor trespassing charges stemming from
their mostly symbolic bid to remove the flag from the Capitol Feb.
2.
   That trial was postponed Friday by District Judge Craig Miller.
No new date was set.
   The jury Friday found Reed guilty of extortion and of inducing a
Columbus, Ga., businessman to travel to Tuskegee, Ala., to commit
the crime.
   Reed, 60, the Alabama head of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People as well as the senior black in the
state Legislature, was found innocent on three remaining charges,
including accepting restaurant equipment from the businessman,
Bobby Gene Chesser, as a bribe in the 1986 bid to free Chesser's
nephew.
   The nephew, Anthony Dennis Chesser, is serving a 40-year
sentence for killing his wife four years ago. His bid to seek early
parole failed.
   U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina did not immediately set a
sentencing date.
   Reed, who shook hands with the judge before leaving, could
receive a maximum of 20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine on the
extortion count, and a five-year term and a $250,000 fine on the
lesser charge.
   NAACP Executive Director Benjamin L. Hooks declined to comment
on the verdict. But he described Reed as a ``positive force in the
area of civil rights for a number of years and we respect his
service.''
   Reed, who in 1970 became one of the first two blacks elected to
the Alabama Legislature this century, said ``by no means'' would he
vacate his seat in the state House of Representatives.
   Vowing to appeal, defense attorney Bill Baxley, a former state
attorney general and ex-lieutenant governor, said his opinion was
that Reed's removal would be up to the House.
   But in a letter dated Friday to Reed, Siegelman wrote that Reed
must leave office immediately or Siegelman would take legal action
to have him removed.
   Siegelman said Reed would be restored to office if his
conviction was reversed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
