<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eastern     10-01 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Unions Say Fight Against Job Cuts Not Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' unions say their fight to save
3,000 jobs isn't over even though a federal appeals panel ruled the
financially troubled carrier had ``ample reason for these
reductions.''
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Washington approved the job cuts Friday and rejected union
contentions that Eastern management was illegally undercutting the
bargaining power of its pilots, flight attendants and machinists'
unions.
   The court said the layoffs resulting from service cuts to 14
cities were a legitimate effort to staunch losses, which Eastern
estimated at $1 million a day during this year's second quarter.
Since 1980, the Miami-based carrier has lost $1 billion and blames
much of its troubles on its unions.
   The unions ``have directed our attention to nothing that would
undermine Eastern's claim that legitimate business concerns provide
an ample reason for these reductions,'' Judge Stephen Williams
wrote for the unanimous panel.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker erred in granting the
unions an injunction last month to halt the layoffs because the
dispute between the Texas Air Corp. subsidiary and its unions was
minor under federal labor law, Williams wrote.
   ``It was certainly disappointing, it didn't come as a shock. We
knew, or I had the impression, this was a conservative panel, but
we had faith in Judge Parker's ruling,'' said Charles Bryan, head
of Miami's machinists' union local, which represents about 9,500
mechanics and ground workers.
   ``What our options are right now is to ask for a full review by
the 11-member panel (of the appeals court). We can do that or have
remanded it back to Judge Parker for full trial,'' Bryan said.
   The Air Line Pilots Association will ask for a hearing by the
full appeals court, said union spokesman Ron Cole in Florida.
   The Transport Workers Union, representing about 6,700 flight
attendants, was unsure what action it would take, said Nancy
Currier, vice president of the Miami local.
   Eastern lawyer Michael Madigan in Washington said, ``We regard
this as an enormously significant ruling for Eastern and for the
airline industry as a whole.''
   Eastern in July announced plans to sell planes, cut unprofitable
routes, close its Kansas City hub and lay off 4,000 workers on Aug.
31. Job cuts included management, union and non-union workers.
Because some workers quit, retired or took unpaid leaves, about
3,000 were laid off.
   The carrier is banking on savings of up to $120 million from
service cuts and of slicing $7 million monthly from its payroll.
   The unions quickly challenged the plan, which they viewed as a
ploy by Eastern's parent to dismantle the company and hurt
organized labor. Since Texas Air bought Eastern in 1986, Eastern's
work force has shrunk from about 42,000 to 30,000.
   Meanwhile, in Cambridge, Mass., Eastern workers gathered Friday
on the banks of the Charles River to protest what they characterize
as the union-busting tactics of Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo,
whose Harvard Business School class was holding its 25th
anniversary this weekend.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson canceled a speech at Memphis State
University to address the rally, which was within earshot of the
building where Lorenzo's classmates were gathering. A Harvard
official said, however, that Lorenzo was not present.
</TEXT>
