<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   10-01 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Campaigns In Illinois; Dukakis Heads West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan stumped in Illinois for his vice president,
courting conservative Democrats and independents, while Democrat
Michael Dukakis went west to score the Reagan administration on its
farm and environmental records.
   George Bush responded to Dukakis in kind, making his third trip
into Dukakis' home state of Massachusetts to pick up another
endorsement from police unions. Bush also visited New Jersey and
Connecticut.
   Both vice presidential nominees _ Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and
Republican Dan Quayle _ began a weekend of intensive preparation
for their debate Wednesday in Omaha, Neb.
   Reagan took the campaign to Chicago, a Democratic stronghold
that Bush bypassed earlier in the week during a bus tour of small
towns in central and northern Illinois.
   Besides attending fund-raisers, Reagan courted
conservative-minded Democrats and independent voters in ethnic
communities, many of whose votes helped Reagan and Bush carry the
state in the last two elections.
   ``The liberals may try to mouth some of our words, but when they
talk about `values' and `family' they mean something very
different,'' he told an audience of 1,500 in a Polish social hall.
   Dukakis' California sojourn included a trip to the Stringfellow
Acid Pits, one of the most notorious toxic waste sites in the
country.
   Dukakis, who has been criticized for being too slow to attack
the pollution problem in Boston Harbor, called a recently initiated
cleanup ``one of the finer achievements'' of his administration and
``the largest single water cleanup project in America.''
   He said his state's toxic waste cleanup program has cleaned up
nearly 300 sites and is working on another 400. ``The current
administration has completed about 25 or 30,'' he said.
   In Idalou, Texas, Dukakis pledged to set aside a $100 million
``Fund to Rebuild America'' for business financing in rural
communities. He also pointed to his proposals for improving rural
health care and increasing education aid.
   ``The Republicans put America on the auction block,'' Dukakis
said. ``They've been selling off our farms and businesses and banks
and real estate'' to foreign investors.
   Campaigning in Massachusetts, New Jersey and Connecticut, Bush
found police organizations ready to take up his cause. His attacks
on the American Civil Liberties Union were echoed by Passaic
County, N.J., Sheriff Edwin Englehardt.
   Police ``don't want a man in that White House who is a
sympathizer and a card-carrying member of the ACLU, that great
organization that's against everything that's right for America,''
Englehardt said.
   In Springfield, Mass., where he collected the endorsement of
police unions, Bush suggested Dukakis was trying to conceal his own
record: ``I am running as myself, and my opponent is running from
himself.''
   Quayle, who campaigned briefly in Philadelphia on Friday, was
going to conduct a formal mock debate today with Sen. Bob Packwod,
R-Ore., who is standing in for Bentsen.
   Bentsen, accepting the National Education Association's
endorsement of the Democratic ticket, said the vice president's
talk of balancing the federal budget and serving as the education
president is ``as empty as Dan Quayle's resume.''
   In other political news:
   _ Panelists were chosen for Wednesday's vice presidential
debate. Judy Woodruff of the MacNeil@Lehrer NewsHour will be
moderator. The panelists are Jon Margolis of the Chicago Tribune,
Britt Hume of ABC and Tom Brokaw of NBC.
   _ A Gallup survey of 1,020 registered voters indicated Bush was
the choice of 47 percent, Dukakis 42 percent. The survey, conducted
Tuesday and Wednesday, had a 3 point margin of error. A Los Angeles
Times poll conducted by calling back voters who had been
interviewed just before and then just after the Sunday's
presidential debate found the race still a tie, at 45-45. The new
callback poll, conducted Thursday, had 622 respondents and a
5-point margin of error.
   _ The Seattle Times, which has endorsed only Republican
presidential candidates since 1920, endorsed Michael Dukakis. The
endorsement will appear in an editorial Sunday.
   _ Bush spokesman Steve Hart disputed as ``absolutely untrue'' a
contention by former Central Intelligence Agency director
Stansfield Turner that Bush had rehired Panamanian military leader
Manual Antonio Noriega as a CIA source. Turner said Friday in
interviews with several news organizations that he dismissed
Noriega in 1976 because he was an ``unscrupulous character.''
   Dukakis has criticized the administration for its support of
Noriega until just recently. Bush said in Sunday's debate that
``seven administrations'' had dealt with the military leader who is
under a drug indictment in the United States.
   _ The Dukakis campaign began airing a 30-second advertising spot
during Friday night's Olympic coverage. Called ``The packaging of
George Bush,'' the ad carries the message that Bush is using the
patriotism issue because he has no programs or proposals for
middle-class Americans.
</TEXT>
