<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSAds     10-01 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Ads,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ad Campaign Urges Condom Use To Block AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's three major TV networks say they
will join an advertising campaign urging sexually active Americans
to use condoms to prevent the spread of AIDS.
   The commercials, direct and fraught with emotion, were released
Friday by the nation's leading producer of public-service
announcements, The Advertising Council.
   Several national publications also said they would run print
versions.
   ``The public service campaign of The Advertising Council may
offend some people. I'm truly sorry about that,'' said U.S. Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop, who endorsed the campaign at a Manhattan
news conference. ``You cannot ignore people who might not have your
own morality.''
   Critics of the ads called them misleading because condoms are
not foolproof.
   ``People will use condoms, feel protected, and still get AIDS
and die,'' said Dr. Elizabeth Whelan, executive director of the
American Council on Science and Health.
   ``There is no such thing as safe sex when it comes to AIDS,''
said Monsignor John Woolsey, director of the Office of Christian
and Family Development for the Archdiocese of New York. ``Recent
studies indicate that the failure rate for condoms is overwhelming,
perhaps as high as 40 percent. ... There is only one sure way to
prevent AIDS: abstinence.''
   But Koop called abstinence ``not a viable option for most
people.'' He said many people also are not monogamous.
   Though AIDS has not spread among heterosexuals nearly as rapidly
as it swept the homosexual population, he said, it can be spread
through heterosexual sex.
   The television spots include one in which a youth standing in a
rainstorm says: ``My brother wouldn't listen to me. I told him,
`You have sex, you use condoms so you don't get AIDS.' He laughed
and said condoms weren't macho.''
   The youth then crumples to a sitting position, and the camera
shows that he is in a cemetery. ``My brother,'' he says. ``He was
so macho.''
   The print ads are equally direct. One simply carries a photo of
a rolled condom. The legend says: ``Using it won't kill you. Not
using it might.''
   ABC and NBC ran similar messages last year, although CBS did not.
   ``A lot has happened since that time. There's a national
awareness and we want to be part of the awareness program,'' said
CBS spokesman George Schweitzer.
   He said CBS would air two of the spots, only after 9 p.m. ABC
did not set a time restriction. NBC had no formal restriction but
said the spots were unlikely to appear before 9 p.m.
   Although ad campaigns have urged the use of condoms before, the
new effort carries added clout through the participation of The
Advertising Council, which has produced several highly successful
public service campaigns, such as the ``Take a Bite Out of Crime''
promotion.
   The council, sponsored by the advertising and communications
industries, distributes its public-service ads to media outlets for
use at their discretion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0524EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Labor-McLaughlin     10-01 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Labor-McLaughlin,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McLaughlin Says Affirmative Action `Business Necessity'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The swelling ranks of minorities in the work place
and an aging work force will make affirmative action a ``business
necessity'' in the next decade, Labor Secretary Anne McLaughlin
says.
   ``Affirmative action is no longer just a matter of social
responsibility. It's not just a matter of legal compulsion,'' she
said Friday. ``In the future, the market will make it a fact of
life.''
   In a speech to a conference of industrial human services
specialists, she said:
   ``I take seriously our responsibility at the department to
assure that equal opportunity has real meaning _ and that we as a
nation and more particularly as a government lead by example.''
   Labor Department studies point to a challenge for business in
the decade ahead, she said.
   The rate of new workers entering the labor market is expected to
be the lowest since World War II, and the average age of workers is
expected to rise from 36 to 39.
   Nearly two-thirds of those entering the job market between now
and the year 2000 will be women, she said, and more immigrants will
be in the work force than any time since World War II.
   ``The next challenge for business will be the quiet revolution
ushered in by a new work force'' increasingly composed of women,
minorities, the disabled and older workers, she said.
   Affirmative action will play a central role, she said. ``Not
merely the traditional social or altruistic perspective of
affirmative action,'' she said, ``but affirmative action as it has
evolved _ as a business necessity.''
   McLaughlin said those efforts must be aimed at preparing the
work force for the jobs now being created, investing in public
education and adjusting to the child care and other demands of the
new work force.
   The onus is on the private sector, she said, adding ``federal
solutions to local problems are in nobody's best interest.''
   ``If corporate America doesn't take the lead in developing
talent now,'' she said, ``it will pay more for talent later.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
