<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gibraltar-IRA     10-01 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar-IRA,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coroner's Jury Decides IRA Guerrilla Shootings Were Lawful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury at an inquest ruled that the killings of
three unarmed IRA members by British commandos in March were legal.
   Foreman Daniel Gabay said the 11-member panel voted 9-2 on
Friday for the lawful killing verdicts.
   Commandos of the British Special Air Service, or SAS, regiment
shot the three on March 6 as they walked in this British colony
toward the Spanish border. The victims were Daniel McCann, 30; Sean
Savage, 24; and Mairead Farrell, 31.
   The commandos testified they believed the Irish Republican Army
members were prepared to detonate a car bomb by remote control and
made threatening moves when confronted.
   The outlawed IRA has acknowledged the three were group members
on ``active service,'' meaning they were on a mission to strike
against a British target at the time of their deaths.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
have claimed the killings were part of an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy against members of the IRA, which seeks
independence for Northern Ireland and union with the Republic of
Ireland.
   ``This is a Pyrrhic victory for the Crown Counsel. There was a
split decision,'' said Niall Farrell, brother of Ms. Farrell, in
Gibraltar after announcement of the jury's verdict.
   ``We've seen the evidence. Sean was shot on the ground. Mairead
and Dan were shot in the back while lying on the ground.''
   The inquest, headed by Coroner Felix Pizzarello, had no power of
prosecution. Its sole aim was to determine whether the shootings
were lawful. A verdict of unlawful killing could have led to
criminal indictments.
   Britain welcomed the decision.
   ``To fight terrorism and to protect innocent lives, the use of
force by the security forces is, regrettably, sometimes
unavoidable,'' said a Defense Ministry official in London, speaking
anonymously in keeping with British practice.
   ``Such action must at all times be within the law. This
principle was fully upheld,'' the official added.
   In Dublin, a government statement said Irish Prime Minister
Charles Haughey and his Cabinet would review the verdicts in detail
before commenting.
   Niall Farrell, calling the commandos ``a bunch of murderers''
and the verdict a ``travesty of justice,'' asked Haughey to pursue
the case in the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg,
France.
   In his summation, Pizzarello asked the jury to reach a unanimous
verdict either for justifiable homicide or unlawful killing. He
later said a split decision was acceptable.
   ``I don't see it as a victory or anything else,'' Crown Counsel
John Laws told reporters. ``We've had a good judicial inquiry
according to British law applied to Gibraltar and that's all there
is to it.''
   After the three were killed, they were found to be unarmed, and
the car Savage had parked was found not to contain any explosives
or timing devices.
   Two days later, Spanish police found a car packed with
explosives in Marbella, 48 miles away. The car had been rented to
one of the dead.
</TEXT>
