<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BloodPressure     10-01 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blood Pressure,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidney Recovery and New Coronary Disease Detection Efforts
Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients with kidneys impaired by high
blood pressure may halt kidney deterioration and even see
improvements with stricter control of blood pressure levels,
research suggests.
   The discovery, which contradicts some research on animals that
indicated kidney disease is unstoppable once damage has occurred,
was announced Friday by William Pettinger, professor of internal
medicine and director of the Midwest Hypertension Research
Institute at Creighton University School of Medicine.
   The finding suggests that conventional drugs could be used more
aggressively to control blood pressure and protect kidneys.
   Nearly 60 million Americans face a much higher risk of stroke or
heart attack because they suffer from high blood pressure. Kidney
damage is a direct result of the affliction, Pettinger said,
although not all hypertension patients suffer impaired kidney
functioning.
   Joseph Izzo, associate professor of medicine and pharmacology at
the State University of New York at Buffalo, said Pettinger's
research underscores previous findings.
   ``You have to consider it significant and it's in light of a
longstanding body of information ... that pressure accelerates
damage to the kidneys,'' said Izzo. ``Since we can control
pressure, we ought to.''
   Damaged kidneys are less able to filter impurities from the
blood, allowing substances that are normally excreted to build up,
including urea.
   Aggressive control of blood pressure ``not only protects kidney
function, but you actually get some return of function,'' said
Pettinger, who reported his findings at a conference of the
American Heart Association's Council for High Blood Pressure
Research.
   ``We've been able to conserve (kidney) function in the vast
majority of patients, even those who started with 50 to 75 percent
(kidney) damage,'' he said.
   Pettinger said he will continue to research an apparent
correlation between improved kidney function and reduced intake of
drugs to treat high blood pressure.
   ``With constant good control of blood pressure, the mechanisms
which sustain high blood pressure appear to be reduced and a
smaller amount of drugs are required to control the blood
pressure,'' he said.
   Pettinger's study involved 18 patients who were treated with
conventional drugs for high blood pressure.
   In a second announcement Friday, researchers at the University
of California at San Francisco revealed that two tests may help
detect coronary artery disease in patients with mild high blood
pressure before symptoms develop.
   Coronary artery disease is caused by fat that builds up in the
walls of blood vessels in the three main arteries of the heart. It
often goes undetected until a patient suffers a heart attack, pain
or sudden death. One-third of sufferers die suddenly, without any
warning of the condition.
   Brian O'Kelly, a cardiology research fellow at UCSF and a
clinical fellow at the Albert Heritage Foundation for Medical
Research in Alberta, Canada, reported preliminary findings that
suggest two tests used to diagnose heart disease may prove useful
in early detection of ``silent'' coronary artery disease.
   Patients with mild high blood pressure are more likely to suffer
from arterial blockage than those with normal blood pressure,
although researchers are not sure what the relationship is, said
O'Kelly.
   Until now, treatment of high blood pressure has successfully
reduced the incidence of strokes, kidney failure and heart failure,
he said, but it has failed to reduce the incidence of fatal heart
attacks and hardening of the arteries.
   Researchers theorize the reason is that the disease is present
before treatment begins.
   O'Kelly hopes the tests will help identify people at high risk
of developing symptomatic heart disease in time to begin aggressive
treatment. Successful early detection could also help develop more
effective ways to avoid heart attacks, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
