<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmptyRaft     10-01 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Empty Raft,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Empty Raft All That Remains of Four Cubans' Freedom Float</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An empty inner-tube raft, a knapsack and
water-soaked notes are all that remain of a doomed effort by four
young Cubans who tried to flee their homeland, immigration
officials said.
   The apparent deaths of the four youths who left Cuba on Sept. 6
_ just as Hurricane Gilbert was about to strike _ spotlights the
dangers of such freedom floats, said Perry Rivkind, district
director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``Well over 50 percent of them never make it to the United
States,'' Rivkind said Friday. ``But they keep on coming. It's an
indication of how desperate the situation is.''
   Rivkind said 26 people have successfully negotiated the Florida
Straits on inner-tube rafts in the past year. It is 90 miles from
the Cuban coast to Key West, but ocean currents generally carry
rafts much farther. It is about 200 miles to Miami, and survivors
have been picked up farther north.
   Rivkind is certain many others did not make it, but this is one
of the few times a raft has been found and relatives could confirm
who was aboard. In most cases relatives are afraid to report the
disappearances to Cuban authorities, Rivkind said.
   The canvas-covered raft of lashed-together inner tubes was found
Monday by a U.S. Coast Guard patrol 60 miles southeast of Miami.
   On board were the records of Luis Mourelo-Coll, 19, a lovesick
Cuban soldier who deserted the military to try to rejoin his
girlfriend, who had arrived in Miami in August. Mourelo-Coll also
had relatives in Florida.
   At first it was thought he might have been alone on the raft,
but on Friday tearful relatives of three others aboard contacted
the INS. Rivkind said he could not release names but that they were
14, 16 and 25 years old.
   Mourelo-Coll's flight had been carefully planned. Inside a
knapsack found with the raft were his Cuban identification,
military and junior high school records and five passport-size
photos.
   Also in the bag were unlabeled food cans, a tire pump,
antihistamine, a Cuban cigar, coins, a comb and a membership card
for a resort in Spain. There was also a list of names and addresses
in Florida, along with some notes that became illegible in the
water.
   The Coast Guard estimates Hurricane Gilbert must have struck the
raft with 40- to 50-mph winds after the four had been floating for
six to seven days.
   ``You can just picture this thing bouncing upside down in the
storm,'' Rivkind said. ``There is no way they could have survived
it.''
   Carmen Rodriguez, a cousin raised with Mourelo-Coll's mother,
had readied a spare room here after hearing in a Sept. 8 phone call
that her cousin had left Cuba. But she spoke to Mourelo-Coll's
grandmother in Cuba on Wednesday and learned that no one has heard
from him since he left.
   Rivkind said he will ask Radio Marti, the Florida-based radio
station beamed to Cuba, to issue more warnings about freedom floats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
