<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-Massacre 2ndLd-Writethru a0497 10-01 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Massacre, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0497,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Troops Move to Put Down Ethnic Rioting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army troops in full combat gear moved
into two southern cities today to quell ethnic gun battles that
killed about 175 people and wounded at least 170 others, officials
said.
   The violence started Friday night in Hyderabad, 100 miles
northeast of Karachi, when marauding bands of native Sindhis
sprayed gunfire in about 30 neighborhoods of Mohajirs, Indian
Moslems who migrated to Pakistan after partition in 1947, witnesses
said.
   On hearing the news, Mohajirs in Karachi retaliated by setting
up roadblocks and firing on vehicles traveling from Sindhi
neighborhoods.
   In one case, Mohajir gunmen sprayed gunfire through the windows
and doors of a bus carrying Sindhi fish merchants, killing 12 of
about 20 on board, a witness said.
   Hospitals in Hyderabad said about 149 people, mostly Mohajirs,
were killed and 170 were wounded. Karachi hospitals confirmed a
total of 26 dead, mostly Sindhis.
   Ali Hassan, a local resident of Hyderabad, who saw the violence,
told The Associated Press by telephone, ``It was hell.''
   ``The markets were full of people ... when bullets were sprayed
from a moving car. There was panic and people started running for
shelter,'' he said.
   He said 10 to 15 cars and jeeps opened fire in about 30
different parts of the city at the same time.
   Hassan said the targets included public gatherings, a wedding,
movie houses and bus stops.
   He said sirens wailed as ambulances raced through the streets
ferrying the dead and wounded to hospitals.
   ``It was a very well-planned attack and executed with
perfection,'' Hassan said.
   Ismail Baloch, a 50-year fish merchant and wounded survivor of
the Karachi bus attack, said he and about 19 other Sindhis were
riding from their village east of the city to the main harbor when
armed Mohajirs stopped their bus near Karachi airport.
   ``They just started firing through windows and doors,'' he said
from his bed at the city's Jinnah Hospital.
   Authorities responded in both cities by calling in army troops
with machine-gun mounted jeeps and armored personnel carriers.
   Police clamped an indefinite curfew on Hyderabad, and calm was
reported restored by this morning as military patrolled the streets.
   In Karachi, officials put a curfew on six neighborhoods today,
but sporadic gunfire and rockthrowing were still being reported.
   Both Hyderabad and Karachi have been the scene of bloody ethnic
clashes in the past between Mojajirs and separaists who want Sind
province to be independent of Pakistan.
   Most of the dead in Hyderabad were Mohajirs, and casualties in
Karachi were Sindhi.
   The Hyderabad massacre was the worst in history for the city of
one million.
   The highest death toll ever reported in Hyderabad was 18 in
riots last July that followed an unsuccessful attempt by Sindhi
student radicals to assassinate Mohajir Mayor Aftab Sheikh.
   Mohajirs later published a list of alleged suspects, including
the president and six office bearers of the Jeay (Long Live) Sind
Students' Federation. All seven eventually were arrested and face
trial on murder and related charges.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Friday night's
attacks appeared to be the Sindhis' answer to those arrests.
   The most militant Sindhis are members of the Jeay Sindhi
Movement, which is campaigning for an independent state of
``Sindhudesh.''
   The Mohajirs, who dominate the province's cities, have formed
the Mohajir Quami Movement to press for official recognition as a
fifth nationality in addition to the Sindhis, Punjabis, Baluchis
and Pathans.
   Karachi, a hot, dusty metropolis of eight million, has a long
history of ethnic unrest which peaked with Sindhi-Pathan clashes in
late 1986 that killed more than 200.
</TEXT>
