<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Two-ClerkOrdinance     10-01 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Two-Clerk Ordinance,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robberies Drop With Test Ordinance Requiring Two Clerks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have decided to make
permanent a law requiring 24-hour convenience stores to have at
least two clerks at night after police found the measure reduced
robberies.
   City commissioners voted 3-1 Thursday night to draft a permanent
ordinance that will be virtually identical to the 2-year-old
experimental ordinance that expires Nov. 11.
   The measure requires all-night convenience stores to have at
least two clerks on duty between 8 p.m. and 4 a.m. It also requires
stores to install security cameras and to keep windows clear of
advertisements.
   Police Chief Wayland Clifton claimed the two-clerk requirement
was a major reason why convenience store robberies in the city
dropped from 61 in 1986 to 23 last year and eight so far this year.
   ``There's a lot less danger out there for people who work at
them and who go there to buy bread and milk,'' he said.
   But Gerald Felder, a lawyer representing the Retail Grocers
Association, argued that the two-clerk law was too expensive,
costing stores $18,000 to $25,000 a year. That expense may have
been a factor in the closing of five convenience stores, he said.
   ``The problem is the economic burden and the reasonableness of
the two-clerk requirement,'' Felder said. The idea is to make the
stores safer, but ``what you're doing is doubling the number of
potential victims,'' he said.
   Felder said robberies dropped after 1986 largely because of the
arrest of one or two active thieves and the effectiveness of other
requirements in the ordinance.
</TEXT>
