<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StormIsaac     10-01 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Storm Isaac,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warnings In Caribbean As Tropical Storm Approaches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm warnings have been issued throughout
the eastern Caribbean as Tropical Storm Isaac continued its
westward course from the Atlantic, forecasters say.
   But Isaac's top winds of 45 mph may not strengthen today as the
storm spins toward warm Caribbean waters, the National Hurricane
Center reported.
   At 6 a.m. EDT Saturday, Isaac was centered near latitude 12.0
north and longitude 58.8 west, or about 95 miles southeast of
Barbados, moving west-northwest at 14 mph.
   Tropical storm warnings were issued for the islands of Barbados,
the Grenadines, St. Vincent, St. Lucia, Dominica and Martinique.
Trinidad, Tobago, Grenada and its dependencies are under a tropical
storm watch.
   Isaac, which reached storm status Friday, was expected to drench
the Windward Islands today. Small craft in the warning areas were
advised to stay in port.
   Meanwhile, the former hurricane known as Helene evolved as
expected into a 600-mile-wide storm in the far North Atlantic.
   In its final advisory on Helene, the hurricane center reported
Friday that the storm was southwest of Reykjavik, Iceland with top
sustained winds near 70 mph.
   Tropical depressions become named storms when winds hit 39 mph
and hurricanes when winds reach 74 mph. Isaac is the ninth Atlantic
storm to reach named status this year.
   The six-month hurricane season started June 1 and ends Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
