<2ND_LINE>PM-Caterpillar-Deere-UAW, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0525,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere and UAW Remain Talking As Picket Signs Go Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with union confirming agreement,
but one plant on strike because of local issues; changes time that
agreement was reached to Central time to conform with style. Picks
up 10th graf pvs, `The 5,377...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for Deere & Co. and the United
Auto Workers reached a tentative agreement today on a three-year
contract affecting more than 13,400 workers, company and union
spokesmen said.
   Robert Combs, spokesman for the farm equipment manufacturer,
announced the settlement shortly after 5 a.m. CDT, when pickets had
already been posted in front of some plants. No details of the pact
were immediately released.
   Talks between the two sides had continued in Moline, Ill., past
the union's midnight Friday strike deadline.
   The agreement covers employees at plants in Atlanta,
Minneapolis, Denver and smaller towns in Illinois and Iowa, Combs
said.
   UAW spokesman Karl Mantyla confirmed that the agreement had been
reached, but said he could not comment on details.
   ``It's subject to some ironing out of language,'' said Mantyla
after approximately 20 hours of talks. He said a schedule for a
ratification vote likely would be decided on during the weekend.
   Although pickets were reported after midnight at some Deere
plants, Mantyla said no strike had been called.
   ``No instructions were issued from here to walk out, but we have
not advised them not to, either. We don't know what the local
unions are doing,'' he said.
   Bruce Davis, a spokesman for UAW Local 94, said a strike over
local issues continues this morning at the Dubuque Deere plant,
despite the tentative agreement on a companywide contract. He would
not elaborate on the issues.
   The 5,377 workers at Deere's largest plant in Waterloo, Iowa,
delayed any strike action, said Jerry Niedert, first vice president
of the union local in Waterloo.
   The tentative agreement apparently averts a full-scale walkout
like the bitter strike in 1986-87 that ended after 163 days with
employees' acceptance of a wage freeze and other concessions.
   In Bridgeton, Mo., negotiators for Caterpillar Inc. and the UAW
agreed earlier Friday to extend their contract indefinitely,
averting a midnight strike deadline and allowing the union to focus
its attention on Deere.
   The extension agreement between Peoria-based Caterpillar and the
UAW came just 12 hours before the current contract would have
expired and avoided a possible walkout by 17,500 Caterpillar
workers in five states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
