<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Takes a Turn for the Worse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 2nd pvs, ``The monarch...'' to UPDATE
with 2nd transfusion, emperor resting. Subs 3rd graf to conform.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, `It was...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health of ailing Emperor Hirohito took a turn
for the worse today when he lost a large amount of blood and
suffered a sharp drop in blood pressure, officials said.
   The monarch's blood pressure stayed down for 30 minutes, but
doctors gave him a large blood transfusion and his vital signs
stabilized, imperial officials said.
   Kenji Maeda, Imperial Household Agency spokesman, said the
emperor received a second transfusion later and was ``resting
peacefully'' in the evening.
   It was not possible to measure how much blood discharged from
the emperor's bowels, but it was ``a considerable amount'' and more
than in past days, said Maeda.
   News reports said a Red Cross vehicle with blood again entered
the Imperial Palace later today, but palace officials did not
immediately confirm that Hirohito had still another transfusion.
   Hirohito has been bedridden with intestinal hemorrhaging since
Sept. 19, when he vomited blood. News reports have said he has
intestinal cancer, but palace officials have neither confirmed nor
denied the reports.
   Earlier today, The Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest newspaper,
said the emperor's overall condition was worsening and doctors
feared his internal bleeding had spread from the upper intestine to
other organs.
   The 87-year-old emperor, the world's longest reigning monarch,
is a symbol of the Japanese state, though he exercises no real
power. He has reigned since 1926.
   Crown Prince Akihito and Crown Princess Michiko were summoned to
the Imperial Palace after the emperor's episode today and stayed
for more than an hour.
   Prince Aya, Hirohito's second grandson, who arrived in Tokyo
today from London, where he is attending Oxford University, also
immediately visited the emperor.
   It was the ninth day in a row that Hirohito has been given
blood. He has been given a total of 9.4 pints of blood since Sept.
19, more than the total amount of blood in his body, news reports
said.
   Earlier today, the emperor ate food for the first time in nearly
two weeks. Hirohito ate five or six spoonfuls of a porridge, an
imperial agency official said.
   Newspapers reported today that palace doctors were worried about
the emperor's worsening jaundice. The reports said his hands and
feet were swollen because of a malfunctioning kidney and vitamin
deficiency.
   Maeda said Hirohito's temperature today was 99.5 Fahrenheit,
compared with his normal reading of about 95.9.
   Many autumn events have been canceled in Japan in deference to
Hirohito's health, including planned visits by overseas leaders.
   Newspapers said the government is considering postponing a visit
by South Korean President Roh Tae-woo scheduled for mid-November.
But a Foreign Ministry official denied the reports and said the
ministry was going ahead with preparations for the visit.
   It would be the first visit to Japan by Roh since he took office
in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Diplomacy 3rdLd-Writethru a0528 10-01 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Diplomacy, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0528,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Extends Diplomatic Offensive With Trip To Zaire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs with details of morning talks, Mobutu to
visit South Africa. Pickup 12th graf pvs, `Reporters and...'
Deletes last 2 grafs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GBADOLITE, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mobutu Sese Seko and South
African President P.W. Botha held a historic summit meeting today
to discuss economic ties and a plan to end the civil war in Angola,
Zaire's southern neighbor.
   After two hours of talks at Mobutu's palace, the presidents told
reporters the Zairean leader had accepted Botha's invitation to
visit South Africa.
   No black African leader has visited South Africa since Botha
took power in 1978. No date was set for Mobutu's visit.
   ``Our relations are on a new path,'' Mobutu said, adding that
they talked ``frankly and in great depth.''Botha said he was
impressed with Mobutu's knowledge of southern Africa affairs and
called it ``a most successful morning.''
   Botha arrived in Mobutu's ancestral village near the Central
African Republic frontier to a red carpet but low-key reception.
The talks began shortly afterward and were to last through the day.
   In Kinshasa, the Zairean capital 700 miles southwest of
Gbadolite, where Botha's plane stopped to refuel, troops opened
fire on about 200 students demonstrating at the University of
Kinshasa against his visit.
   Witnesses said at least two students were injured, one hit in
the neck by a bullet and another hit in the leg. Both were taken to
the university clinic for treatment but their conditions were not
known.
   The meeting was Botha's first with Mobutu and his third summit
in black Africa during his 10 years in power _ all of them in the
past three weeks.
   After the morning meeting, Botha told reporters he and Mobutu
discussed the latest round of U.S.-mediated talks in the Congolese
capital of Brazzaville, aimed at a peace agreement between South
Africa and Angola.
   ``We discussed peace in Africa and in southern Africa
especially. We discussed the Angolan question, which is of vital
importance to all of us, and we discussed the South-West Africa,
Namibia problem which is being dealt with in the near future,''
Botha said.
   Both leaders said they would also discuss economic issues.
   Reporters and photographers, who witnessed the start of the
talks, said Mobutu welcomed Botha in French and Botha thanked
Mobutu for inviting him in a reply spoken in Afrikaans. The remarks
were translated by interpreters.
   Mobutu, in announcing the visit Friday, said South Africa had
asked for the meeting. The Zairean leader follows a firmly
pro-Western foreign policy.
   On Sept. 13, Botha met with President Joaquim Chissano of
Mozambique, a longtime adversary of South Africa. The next day he
visited President Kamuzu Banda of Malawi, the only African country
to maintain full diplomatic relations with Botha's white-controlled
government.
   One of Botha's longstanding foreign policy goals has been to
broaden ties with black Africa without having to make substantive
political concessions to the disenfranchised black majority in his
own country. There has been speculation about possible meetings
between Botha and other African leaders.
   Despite the lack of formal relations, Zaire and many other
African countries trade with South Africa and rely on its ports and
railroad lines for handling imports and exports.
   South African products, ranging from toothpaste to meat, are
sold in Zaire, and more than a third of Zaire's main export _
copper _ is routed through South Africa.
   Peace in Angola might lead to reopening of a rail line linking
southern Zaire to Angola's Atlantic Ocean port of Lobito, providing
a more efficient route for copper exports.
   The Brazzaville talks between South Africa and an Angolan-Cuban
delegation adjourned Thursday without agreement on the key issue of
a timetable for withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in
Angola supporting the government.
   South Africa has offered to begin implementation on Nov. 1 of a
United Nations' plan for independence for South-West Africa, or
Namibia, if a Cuban withdrawal from Angola can be negotiated.
   Angola's Marxist government has accused Zaire of allowing the
UNITA rebel movement to operate from its territory, and there have
been repeated reports that U.S. military aid for UNITA is routed
through Zaire.
</TEXT>
