<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--FalseSatellite     10-01 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--False Satellite,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glittery Carnival Sphere Mistaken For Fallen Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities thought it was a radioactive Soviet
satellite, but the glittering, smoking sphere that closed the
Paris-Lille superhighway for nearly two hours turned out to be
carnival equipment.
   The 6-foot aluminum sphere fell off a carnival truck Friday
night, and the electrical workings inside apparently caught fire
from the impact, officials said.
   The Soviet nuclear-powered Cosmos 1900 satellite remained in
earth orbit, but was expected to fall into the atmosphere sometime
this week. French space specialists say the chances it will fall on
French territory are about one in a thousand.
   At about 9 p.m. Friday, a motorist on the highway near Peronne,
about 85 miles north of Paris, saw the smoking, shiny debris and
alerted police.
   Dozens of gendarmes, firemen and civil defense workers were
called out to divert traffic around the area and establish a
security perimeter.
   The superhighway was reopened before 11 p.m.
</TEXT>
