<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetAmputee     10-01 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadet Amputee,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Secretary Refuses to Intervene on Behalf of Disenrolled
Cadet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cadet who lost part of a leg in
a traffic accident has lost his bid to stay in the Air Force
Academy in spite of his handicap.
   A Pentagon rule calls for ``disenrollment'' of any service
academy cadet who loses all or part of a limb, and Air Force
Secretary Edward C. Aldridge approved that action Friday for Cadet
Third Class Dan Korslund.
   Aldridge had been pressured by two senators, several advocates
for the disabled and an organization of amputee athletes pushing
for Korslund, who would have been in his sophomore year this fall.
   Aldridge announced his decision in a letter to Sen. William
Armstrong, R-Colo., who said he would ask President Reagan to
consider the case.
   Korslund, 20, lost part of his right leg in June while helping a
friend start a stalled car on Interstate 25 near the academy
grounds.
   At the time of the accident Korslund had been confined to the
academy grounds in a disciplinary matter and technically was absent
without leave, The Colorado Springs Gazette Telegraph quoted
sources as saying.
   Armstrong, who had tried to keep Korslund in the academy, called
Aldridge's decision ``a great mistake.''
   In addition to the Pentagon rule, Aldridge said it would be a
waste of taxpayers' money to send Korslund to school when there is
no possibility he would be allowed to serve in the Air Force.
Military officials estimate it costs about $200,000 to send a cadet
through a service academy.
   An Air Force spokesman at the Pentagon said current policy does
allows seniors who become medically disabled in their final
semester to graduate.
   Academy spokesman Will Ketterson said Korslund was advised of
the decision Friday at a Veterans Administration hospital in
Seattle, near his home in Tacoma, where he was transferred earlier
in the week.
   A man answering the telephone at the VA hospital said Korslund
was not available for comment and had in fact left the hospital.
   ``He has been discharged and that's all I'm allowed to say,''
said the man, who refused to give his name.
</TEXT>
