<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Tibet     10-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Tibet,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Profile Police Presence Reported On Anniversary of Tibet
Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rifle-toting police patrolled the streets and
monasteries of Tibet's capital Saturday on the first anniversary of
anti-Chinese protests that left at least 14 people dead.
   Foreign travelers contacted in the remote Himalayan region
reported no incidents as about 200 police guarded Lhasa's holy
Jokhang Temple, the main site of the bloody Oct. 1, 1987 riots.
   Michael Ruh of West Germany said police carrying rifles walked
continuously on the square in front of the temple and on the
Lingkor, the pilgrim's path around the Jokhang.
   ``You can see them on the rooftops with binoculars,'' Ruh added.
   The protests last year on China's Oct. 1 National Day were led
by Buddhist monks loyal to Tibet's exiled spiritual leader, the
Dalai Lama, and seeking an end to Chinese rule over Tibet.
   An Australian traveler said he was detained briefly by Tibetan
police while walking near the Jokhang on Friday night. ``They
pushed us around and were a little hostile at first ... but they
gradually calmed down and became Tibetan again,'' said the man, who
identified himself only as Jeremy.
   Describing police as ``ready and jumpy ... but hoping that
nothing will happen,'' the Australian said he and a friend counted
33 trucks carrying about 40 police each patrolling the city.
   Travelers were told by security officers they would be punished
if they took part in protests and warned them to stay away from the
Jokhang and the nearby Barkhor market.
   Ruh said authorities closed a second-floor cafe overlooking the
Jokhang that is frequented by travelers. An 11:30 p.m. curfew has
been in effect since last Sunday, he said.
   Chinese leaders in recent days have stressed Tibet will never be
given independence or semi-independence and warned that separatists
will be dealt with harshly.
   Asian diplomats say Chinese military forces around Lhasa have
been increased, and travelers to Lhasa report police surveillance
of monasteries has increased.
   China has proposed direct talks with the Dalai Lama, with the
stipulation that he must abandon any claims to Tibetan independence.
   The Dalai Lama fled to exile in India after a failed uprising
against the Chinese military in 1959.
   Lastt June, the Dalai Lama proposed Tibet be given domestic
autonomy while China retain control over the region's military and
foreign affairs. The plan was rejected by Beijing.
</TEXT>
