<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SkyPig     10-01 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sky Pig,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporters Call His Plane ``Sky Pig'' But Dukakis Likes the Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD SKY PIG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has Air Force One. George
Bush has Air Force Two. Michael Dukakis has ``Sky Pig.''
   That inelegant and unofficial name has stuck as the campaign's
handle for the Democratic presidential nominee's chartered campaign
jet. The name has even appeared on a printed campaign schedule.
   The plane is a Presidential Airways Boeing 737 _ an aging,
relatively small jetliner that Dukakis has used since Republican
Bob Dole faded from the presidential race in the early spring and
relinquished it.
   Dukakis, by all accounts, has grown attached to the familiar
plane _ even though to some aboard it no longer seems adequate for
a presidential campaign.
   ``It's our plane of choice,'' said top aide Nick Mitropoulos.
   The question is: Why?
   At this stage of past campaigns, presidential nominees were
traveling in Boeing 727s or their equivalent _ larger, sleeker
aircraft, with more seats and longer range.
   Sky Pig is unable to fly coast-to-coast without a refueling
stop. It has seating for only about 100, compared to 130 or more
for a 727. Sometimes luggage has to be loaded onto a larger, second
plane that follows _ so the 737 can keep within takeoff and landing
limits.
   And Sky Pig has its idiosyncracies, like a tendency to drip
water from the ceiling through condensation on hot days. It has no
facilities for heating food.
   The name was coined by network television crews who have
accompanied the candidate for months. On its lumbering takeoff
rolls they sometimes yell encouragement: ``Up pig, up.'' There's
even a song, to the tune of the 1960s rock song ``Wild Thing.'' It
goes: ``Sky Pig, you make my heart sink.''
   The second plane _ an even older 727 _ follows Sky Pig, carrying
the spillover of staff, reporters, Secret Service agents, and
television crews and producers. But because it's faster, Dukakis
sometimes switches to the American Trans Air plane to save time on
a trip across the continent.
   Still, he always returns to the familiar plane.
   Press Secretary Dayton Duncan said Dukakis simply likes the
plane.
   He is comfortable, sitting in first class seats in the front
row. Behind him it is more crowded.
   Campaign insiders say he also likes the name Presidential
Airways on the side of the aircraft.
   The regular crew of flight attendants sometimes come along to
his campaign events.
   They always have aboard a box of Raisin Bran cereal, Dukakis'
favorite, and they keep a supply of Orange Crush, the candidate's
soda of choice.
   He seems puzzled that anyone would want to dump The Pig.
   ``Well, we've been on this plane for a long time,'' he said. ``A
long time.''
</TEXT>
