<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     10-01 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortionists Prepare Repeat Of Summer Blitz On Atlanta</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Juli is CQ in 14th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters aiming to shut down Atlanta abortion
clinics face a tougher, less hospitable police force in their
planned repeat this week of the summer blitz that landed more than
750 of them in jail.
   Organizers say they expect hundreds of demonstrators for the
planned week-long protest. They say they'll find out where
abortions are being done and try to stop them, and that those
arrested were once again being asked to refuse to give their names
to authorities.
   Police plan to be ready and vow to keep the clinics open.
   ``They're going to see a different Atlanta Police Department
(this) week,'' said liaison officer Richard Hyde. ``We're tired of
getting on our knees and asking grown men and women to get on the
bus.''
   Atlanta police were fairly lenient during the summer
demonstrations, which began during the Democratic National
Convention, carrying protesters gently away from the clinics.
   ``We know how to move a person from point A to point B without
putting him on a stretcher,'' said police Maj. Kenneth Burnette, in
charge of the Atlanta precinct where some of the clinics are
located. He said the demonstrators violate constitutional rights of
women who seek a legally available service.
   ``This time, they're going to go to jail and they're going to be
treated like criminals,'' Burnette said.
   Advocates of legalized abortion are also preparing
counter-demonstrations and vigils and are training escorts to take
women wanting abortions through the lines of demonstrators at the
clinics.
   Protest organizers accused the police of threatening violence as
an intimidation.
   ``We are afraid of what the police are planning to do,''
Operation Rescue official Joseph Foreman said Friday.
   Also Friday, the city asked a Fulton County Superior Court to
declare the demonstrators public nuisances and restrain them from
blocking clinic entrances or coming within 15 feet of anyone
entering or leaving a clinic. The court did not immediately rule on
the request.
   Juli Loesch of Eire, Pa., spokeswoman for Operation Rescue, said
the New York-based anti-abortion group is ``expecting people in the
heavy hundreds to come to Atlanta, and there will be Atlanta
people, too.''
   ``We'll do what we did last time. We will find out (in advance)
which clinics are having abortions on a given day. These are not
symbolic actions. We are trying to stop abortions from happening.''
   Organizers say they plan to end this string of Atlanta sit-ins
Friday.
   The first Operation Rescue protest began on the second day of
the July Democratic convention, and the demonstrations continued
long after the Democrats left. Through the summer, Atlanta police
arrested 765 demonstrators at 17 sit-ins before the protests
slacked off in September.
   Most of those arrested did not carry identification and gave
authorities aliases of ``Baby John Doe'' or ``Baby Jane Doe,''
making it impossible for police to free them on bond. The aliases,
protesters said, were to symbolize their link to what they consider
to be the anonymous victims of abortion.
   Several demonstrators spent a month or more in jail, and three
were still there Saturday, including two men who have spent more
than two months in jail. Ms. Loesch said those who could take the
time to stay in jail would be encouraged to use the same no-name
tactic this week.
   Arrests and jail expenses in the summer protests came to about
$500,000 for the city of Atlanta, which gradually toughened its
stance against the protests. Police started dragging protestors to
jail-bound buses instead of carrying them. Vans of protesters en
route to targeted clinics were given traffic tickets. The
convention expedient of freeing identified demonstrators on
recognizance bonds ended, and the courts began demanding cash or
surety bonds of up to $2,000.
   Nationwide, Ms. Loesch said, 6,364 Operation Rescue protesters
have been arrested in about 30 cities this year. The group
maintains that its actions have persuaded about 370 women not to
have abortions.
</TEXT>
