<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan Bjt   10-01 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan, Bjt,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>172 Killed In Worst Ethnic Violence In Pakistani History</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KAR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army troops and police reported an
uneasy calm in two southern cities Saturday, one day after ethnic
violence left at least 172 people dead.
   Officials said Sindhi nationalists in apparently coordinated
attacks fired Friday from moving cars on Mohajir immigrants in
buses and marketplaces, killing at least 140 in Hyderabad and 32 in
Karachi.
   Area hospitals, however, reported a higher toll _ 217 fatalities
and 400 injuries, including several Sindhis killed in retaliatory
shootings Saturday by Mohajirs who set up roadblocks.
   Army troops eventually drove the rioters from the streets of
Karachi by nightfall.
   ``The situation is returning to normal,'' Chief Minister Akhtar
Ali Kazi, the top executive of Sind province, said in a statement.
   Both Hyderabad and Karachi, Pakistan's largest city with 8
million residents, have been the scene of bloody ethnic clashes
between Mohajirs and Sindhi separatists who want Sind province to
be independent of Pakistan.
   The 107 million people of this Moslem nation, carved out of
predominantly Hindu India at the end of British rule in 1947, form
a patchwork of rival ethnic groups stretching south from the
Himalayas to the Indian Ocean.
   Pakistan officially recognizes nationalities of its four
provinces: the Pathans of the northwest province bordering
Afghanistan, the Baluchis of arid Baluchistan, the Punjabis of
Punjab in the east and the Sindhis of Sind province in the south.
   But the weekend massacre involved a fifth major group: the
Mohajirs, who immigrated mostly from India and, in the last decade,
from Bangladesh.
   The increase in Mohajirs, especially in Sind province, has led
to repeated clashes in recent years with the Sindhis, Pathans and
Punjabis.
   The most militant Sindhis are members of the Jeay Sindhi
Movement, which is campaigning for an independent state of
``Sindhudesh.''
   The Mohajirs, who dominate the province's cities, have formed
the Mohajir Quami Movement to press for official recognition as a
fifth nationality.
   Ali Hassan, a Hyderabad resident who saw the violence, told The
Associated Press by telephone: ``It was hell.
   ``The markets were full of people. ... When bullets were sprayed
from a moving car, there was panic and people started running for
shelter,'' Hassan said.
   Hassan said about 10 cars and jeeps opened fire in several
different parts of the city _ at public gatherings, a wedding,
movie houses and bus stops.
   ``It was a very well-planned attack and executed with
perfection,'' Hassan said.
   Officials said the Hyderabad massacre was the worst in history
for the city of 1 million.
   The highest death toll ever reported previously in that city was
18 in riots last July that followed an unsuccessful attempt by
Sindhi student radicals to assassinate Mohajir Mayor Aftab Sheikh.
   Clashes between Mohajirs and Pathans started in Karachi in 1985
over a fatal traffic accident. Riots continued for nearly six weeks
and left about 60 dead.
   The worst violence in Pakistan's history was in late 1986 when
the two groups battled almost daily for months. Authorities said
about 200 people died but unofficial estimates were much higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
