<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-01 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of hot air balloons of every
color and stripe were launched into clear skies Saturday to kick
off the 17th Annual Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta.
   About 150,000 people turned out shortly after dawn to watch the
mass ascension that traditionally marks the beginning of the
nine-day event, said spokeswoman Jean Jordan.
   The first wave of about 100 balloons drifted aloft shortly after
7:30 a.m., followed by four more waves for a record launch of an
estimated 580 balloons, Jordan said.
   ``It's a astronomical event,'' she said. ``Balloon Fiesta Park
is very jammed and really, really crowded.''
   Old balloon favorites like Tony the Tiger and Mickey Mouse were
joined this year by newcomers such as the Financial Times' balloon,
a cone-shaped affair that depicts a rolled-up newspaper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most people prefer a ride in a
limousine to cap off their wedding day, William Beamish and
Jacqueline Erickson say a Greyhound bus was more their style.
   ``I think this will be etched in our memory banks for many
years,'' Beamish said as the couple and their wedding party walked
off the bus Friday. ``I'm sure everybody on the bus will remember
it. It's not something that happens every day.''
   Family and friends were chauffered to the wedding in the bus,
and after the couple tied the knot, everyone was treated to an
evening ride on the bus.
   Beamish and Erickson met through their jobs. Both are
Minneapolis-based Greyhound drivers.
   They've known each other for six or seven years, but romance
flowered between runs one night in Hibbing.
   ``We went dancing and fell in love. It was a surprise to both of
us,'' Erickson said.
   Since then, they have tried to catch a moment with each other on
all points of their bus runs between Minneapolis, Fargo, N.D., and
Madison, Wis.
   ``I'll think we'll have a perfect marriage. We'll probably see
each other once or twice a week,'' Erickson joked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne County Jail inmates can obliterate
electronic enemies, flail at punching bags and wind up behind the
8-ball with some of the $129,000 of new recreational equipment
installed in two downtown lockups.
   Five new video games were installed Friday in the old jail
building, and pingpong tables, weight machines, pool tables and
other items have been installed in the new jail building next door.
   ``Clearly, we are no longer in an Eighth Amendment situation of
cruel and unusual punishment,'' said Sheriff Robert Ficano.
   The equipment was installed in part to satisfy court orders
giving jail inmates expanded recreational opportunities. County
officials said they also hoped the equipment would defuse tensions
among inmates and make the facility safer for guards.
   Inmates welcomed the new weight equipment. Said one: ``You can
go crazy in here, especially if you've got a case that's kind of
shaky.''
</TEXT>
