<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-CynthiaLennon     10-01 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Cynthia Lennon,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Wife of Late Beatle Also Denounces New Lennon Bio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cynthia Lennon joins the throng denouncing the
new, unauthorized biography of her late former husband, John
Lennon, as written by a money-hungry author capitalizing on
untruths.
   ``People who write books like this, it is for greed, and as far
as I'm concerned, they're gravediggers, no more, no less,'' Mrs.
Lennon says on the CBS show ``60 Minutes'' scheduled for broadcast
Sunday evening.
   ``Grave robbers, body snatchers, you name it, they are it.''
   The biography by Albert Goldman, ``The Lives of John Lennon,''
depicts the former Beatle as an anorexic bisexual addled by drugs
who raged his way from Liverpool to New York. It was released Sept.
14.
   Goldman, who defends his Lennon book and said it is based on
1,200 interviews, also has written controversial biographies of
comedian Lenny Bruce and Elvis Presley.
   Lennon was murdered outside his Upper West Side home on Dec. 8,
1980, by Mark David Chapman.
   ``All I know and all the people that love John know that we had
our years (and) that nobody, no film, no book will ever complete
what went on in our lives. That's our part of our hearts that has
to stay with us, must not be public,'' Mrs. Lennon said.
   ``I love John. I've always loved John because he was my first
love. But, I mean, I've loved him in different ways. I love his
memory. I loved what he did. I understood his madness, his phases.
I just feel that I understood.''
   The couple divorced a few months before Lennon married Yoko Ono
in 1969.
   Ms. Ono already has trashed the book, calling it ``totally
fiction'' in a nationwide broadcast that coincided with the release
of the book. She too was interviewed on the ``60 Minutes'' show,
entitled ``The Two Mrs. Lennons.''
   ``These people in this book are not us. It's not John and me,''
Ono said in the taped radio broadcast.
   Cynthia and John's son, Julian Lennon, also denounced the book
on the radio taping, calling it ``lies, untruths,'' and adding that
``the whole thing is just sickening.''
   Sean Lennon, the son of Yoko and John who is now 12, added his
voice on the CBS broadcast, rebutting charges that his father was
inattentive to parenting.
   ``I think he did a lot of fathering in the five years that I
knew him,'' Sean says. ``He spent so much time with me not just at
home, but everywhere, you know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Reagan-Text     10-01 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan-Text,870</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of President Reagan's weekly
radio address, giving from the White House Oval Office on Saturday:
   My fellow Americans, in the past few weeks you and I and all
Americans have won some major victories here in Washington. These
victories didn't come easily, but each will help shape our nation
in the years ahead.
   One of the most important has to do with the federal budget.
Only once since 1948, has all of the budgeting of the United States
government been approved by Congress and signed by the President on
or before the beginning of the fiscal year, and too often when the
budget process has reached an impasse, appropriations have been
dumped into massive continuing resolutions.
   The worst of these came along last year. Congress poured all the
government's appropriations into a single bill. The bill was 1,057
pages long, weighed 14 pounds, and arrived over two months after
the fiscal year began.
   Not even Congress knew what was in it.
   I said in January that the next time Congress pulled such a
stunt: Well, never again. Well, I'm happy to report that today,
October 1st, marks the beginning of the fiscal year, and at this
hour for the first time in years, all the government's budgetary
work is done.
   The last of the government's 13 appropriations bills have been
delivered to me and I have signed them. It was touch and go for a
while whether we would actually meet the deadline. The
appropriations bill for the District of Columbia provided financing
of abortions long after most other federal abortion financing has
stopped. We said public money should not be used for abortions.
Many liberals said it should be. We won.
   The defense appropriations bill was also a close call. As you
know many liberals are opposed to our Strategic Defense Initiative.
Why they would want to deny America a defense against nuclear
missiles, a defense that the Soviets have been candid enough to say
they're building for themselves, why the liberals would want to do
that, I don't know.
   They have through various devices restricted how we spent money
on SDI research and development.
   These restrictions could have crippled critical parts of the
program, but early this week we got the restrictions removed from
all bills, and research will go forward to find a way to end the
nightmare of nuclear terror. I hope the last 24-hours prove
historic and mark the end of the ``Perils of Pauline'' budget games
Congress played for so long.
   Another recent historic accomplishment is passage of a bill
implementing the US-Canada Free Trade Agreement. When similar
legislation is enacted in Canada, North America will be on its way
to becoming the world's largest open market.
   Thanks in part to our successful policy begun the day George
Bush and I took office of opening markets around the world to
American goods, America is today in the longest peacetime economic
expansion on record. Canada is also growing strongly. Opening our
mutual border to uninhibited commerce will help that unprecedented
expansion continue into the next decade and the next century.
   This week, we won one other major victory in Congress and took a
giant step toward reform in the welfare system that is a trap for
too many of our fellow citizens.
   Now, I've often said that genuine welfare reform must be geared
to making people independent of welfare, and that means, among
other things, that those who receive welfare must be required to
work. Too many liberals have fought this idea every step of the
way. But yesterday, we prevailed, and the welfare reform
legislation that will arrive on my desk shortly includes a work
requirement.
   Even as we can take pride in these great victories, a couple of
other legislative battles continue to rage, over the textile bill,
which I vetoed this week, and the drug bill.
   On the textile bill, the problem is that the bill is
protectionist and would draw foreign retaliation against American
products. With America exporting more than ever, protectionism
means destroying American jobs, and I won't allow it.
   The House-passed drug bill provides for a federal death penalty
for drug-related killings. Liberals in Congress oppose the death
penalty and other necessary improvements in the law and plan to
kill the bill in the Senate. They've also recently cut funding for
the federal agencies that enforce our drug laws.
   It's time the liberals realized that the fight against drugs is
not ``Pee-wee's Big Adventure,'' but a serious and dangerous
business. And our law enforcement officers should have all the
tools they need to do their job.
   I urge the Senate to follow the House's lead and give America a
strong drug bill. I urge Congress to act swiftly this week to
restore full funding to drug law enforcement.
   With your help, in the end, what is best for the nation will win
out. It has in many ways in the past few days. Let's hope Congress
will do what's right on the textile and the drug bills.
   Until next week, thanks for listening, and God bless you.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatalCoverup     10-01 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Coverup,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father, Son Jailed For Coverup In Fatal Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who falsely claimed
responsibility for a fatal traffic accident because his son had
been driving without insurance has been sentenced to jail along
with the son.
   Ronald Haw, 49, a Culver City engineer, was sentenced to one
year in county jail Friday and three years' probation by Orange
County Superior Court Judge James K. Turner.
   Haw was convicted of conspiracy and a misdemeanor charge of
filing false information with a police officer concerning the
accident, which killed a 17-year-old bicyclist.
   Haw's 25-year-old son, Gary, was sentenced to two years in state
prison for his role in the Sept. 8, 1987, accident. He was
convicted in August of felony hit-and-run driving and conspiracy.
   Gary Haw was not insured to drive his father's turbocharged
Porsche. He admitted at trial that he lied to authorities about who
was driving at the time so the insurance would cover the damage.
   The younger Haw testified that he had not seen the bicyclist.
   He said that after the accident he called his father and asked
him to come to the scene. He told police his father was driving but
had gone for help after the crash and probably had become
disoriented and lost.
   The judge ordered Gary Haw taken into custody upon sentencing,
expressing concern that he might flee, said Deputy District
Attorney Pat Donahue.
   The prosecutor said the younger Haw deserved prison because,
among other things, ``He lied about the death of a boy, and also he
encouraged others to participate in this charade he planned.''
   Donahue said he also sought jail time for the father ``because
of the callous attitude he showed during the trial, the nature of
the lie and the fact that he was lying about the death of a boy for
insurance reasons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Georgetown     10-01 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Georgetown,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Superpower Policies A Success</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 2:35 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, saying ``I am the same man I
was when I came to Washington,'' contended Saturday that his
beliefs have been vindicated by the success of his superpower
policies.
   In an address at Georgetown University, Reagan said his policies
have brought about ``the receding tide of totalitarianism'' during
his two terms as president.
   The president said he's been ``steadfast and unapologetic,'' and
unwilling to accept Soviet nuclear superiority, the Soviet
occupation of Afghanistan or the presence of Soviet and Cuban
proxies in Angola and Nicaragua.
   Reagan said his principles hadn't swerved at all, even though
some conservatives had been leery about the administration's move
to ease relations with the Soviet Union in order to achieve the
first treaty banning an entire class of nuclear weapons.
   ``Contrary to some of the things you've heard, I am the same man
I was when I came to Washington. I believe the same things I
believed when I came to Washington. And I think those beliefs have
been vindicated by the success of the policies to which we held
fast,'' Reagan said.
   ``Yes, at every point on the map that the Soviets have applied
pressure, we've done all we can to apply pressure against them,''
Reagan said. ``And now, we are seeing a sight many believed they
would never see in our lifetime: the receding tide of
totalitarianism.''
   Reagan made the unusual weekend appearance at a school to help
celebrate the bicentennial of the nation's oldest Catholic
university. Accepting an honorary doctorate of humane letters,
Reagan spoke on the celebration's theme, ``Learning, Faith and
Freedom.''
   ``America is what she is because she is guided by all three,''
the president said. ``Americans know the truth of those words. We
still believe in our creator, we still believe in knowledge, we
still believe in freedom.''
   The president contended that rulers ``who enslave and victimize
the people of the Earth'' are coming to envy America's freedom.
   ``We prosper economically only because people are free _ free
not only to speak and read and think but also to create and build
and barter and sell,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w andacongressmanfromthestateofWashington.     10-01 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>nd a congressman from the state of Washington.</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Congress heads into its final days before adjournment in
October, it seems a good time to reflect on these last two years.
The 100th Congress has been a landmark Congress. Guided by the
historic bipartisan budget summit of November last year, Congress
moved constructively and effectively to bring about a signficant
reduction in the national deficit that so threatens the country's
future and the economic security of every individual American.
   The Congress is determined to continue on this path of reducing
the federal deficit and moving further toward a balanced budget.
This year, we fully complied with the requirements of the
Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit reduction act. But, American society,
like the individual American, is compassionate. And Congress, as
the representatives of a compassionate people, moved to address a
series of longstanding needs that our nation could be better poised
to meet the challenges it faces.
   The congressional leadership set a goal last January to pass all
13 appropriation bills in time for the new fiscal year. This will
avoid the necessity of having to lump all federal spending together
in one major bill called the continuing resolution. We are well on
our way toward completing action on these bills and sending them to
the president for signature.
   The spending cuts contained in these bills will enable Congress
to meet the goals of last year's budget summit. They also enable
the 100th Congress to cut the budget deficit by some $70 billion
over the last two years. The deficit for fiscal year 1989 will be
about 20 percent less than it would have been without the
congressional budget actions, and this early legislative action on
the budget has established a discipline that we haven't seen in
perhaps 40 years.
   At the beginning of the 100th Congress, Speaker Jim Wright
announced an ambitious legislative agenda to deal affirmatively and
constructively with problems the public identified as being the
most serious. In terms of passing important new legislation, this
has been the most productive Congress in decades.
   Here are just a few of the landmark bills we passed: a clean
water bill to combat the pollution that has endangered our water
supply; a highway bill to mprove safety and mobility for the
traveling public; a trade bill to help reverse the crippling trade
deficit that has robbed our nation of so many good jobs; a
plant-closing bill to give American workers the same right to
notice before a lay-off that workers in most other industrial
countries enjoy; an education bill to increase the government's
commitment to quality schools; a housing bill to ease the
difficulties that young people face in purchasing their first home;
a Medicare improvement bill to protect beneficiaries from the
impact of financially catastrophic hospital and physician expenses;
a homeless aid bill to provide help to the most unfortunate
citizens among us; and a drought relief bill to help the thousands
of family farmers hurt by the crippling effects of drought.
   And before we adjourn, we hope to complete action on two other
major American priorities _ anti-drug legislation to give the
government new tools to carry out the war against drug abuse; and a
welfare reform bill to give welfare recipients the training and
supportive assistance they need to obtain and keep a job.
   As holders of the public trust, I think most of us in Congress
feel that these last two years have set a record the 100th Congress
can be proud of. But, let's be fair, Congress probably shouldn't
write its own report card. I'm confident, however, that in the
months ahead, the American public will look at the record and
conclude that these last two years have been a story of promises
made and promises kept _ that our major legislative goals have been
achieved and that we have built a firmer foundation for America's
future.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0109 </DOCNO>
