<DOCNO> AP881001-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-ExitGromyko     10-01 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Exit Gromyko,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold War's `Mr. Nyet' Ends Half Century Of Public Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Kremlin Shake-up, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drizzle was falling on the Kremlin, wreathing
the thick red walls of the ancient fortress in mist, as the last
seconds in nearly a half-century of public life ticked off for
Andrei Andreyevich Gromyko, the Cold War's ``Mr. Nyet.''
   The chimes in the Spassky Tower tolled noon Saturday as a
glum-faced Gromyko and the 12 members of the ruling Politburo filed
into the cream-colored hall of the Grand Kremlin Palace to open a
special meeting of the Soviet parliament.
   Fifteen minutes later, the 79-year-old Gromyko retired from his
job as president, ostensibly at his own request, at any rate with
fulsome public praise from the man who succeeded him, Communist
Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gromyko's exit was the end of an era in Soviet political life,
one that began with wartime U.S.-Soviet collaboration and then
turned into the superpower brinksmanship epitomized by the Berlin
Wall and the Cuban missile crisis.
   Gromyko entered his country's diplomatic corps in 1939 and later
served as Soviet foreign minister for 28 years. His poker-faced
countenance became a symbol of Soviet intransigence worldwide, and
he was around for the East-West honeymoons as well as the quarrels.
   He served under Stalin and under all of the men who succeeded
Stalin as Communist Party chief: Nikita Khrushchev, Leonid
Brezhnev, Yuri Andropov, Konstantin Chernenko and Gorbachev.
   In his three years as a permanent representative on the U.N.
Security Council, Gromyko cast 26 vetoes, sounding out his ``nyet''
_ no _ when it came his turn to vote.
   But four months after taking power in March 1985, Gorbachev
replaced Gromyko as foreign minister and relegated him to the
mostly ceremonial job of president. Gromyko retired Friday from the
Politburo.
   ``Thank you, comrade deputies, for the trust you have granted
me,'' Gromyko said Saturday from the Supreme Soviet rostrum. ``I
appreciated, and appreciate, this trust.''
   A loud ovation tore through the high-ceiling hall. Gorbachev
helped Gromyko back to his seat. Then the 1,500-member parliament
voted to retire him. There were no opposing votes.
   Gromyko sat in silence beside Gorbachev at the dais, facing the
deputies, as the Supreme Soviet members raised their right hands en
masse to send him into retirement.
   He did not take part in the vote that ended his political
career, but slouched in his green-upholstered seat, wearing an
inscrutable look.
   It could have been a smile. But it also could have been a
grimace. With Gromyko, it never was easy to tell the difference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
