<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-Edwards     10-01 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Edwards,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Preparing for Shuttle Landing with Simulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA briefed members of
the shuttle recovery convoy Saturday and planned for a simulated
shuttle landing to prepare for Discovery's return to Earth on
Monday.
   The NASA-Air Force convoy of more than 200 people in an
assortment of vehicles will rush onto the hard, unpaved surface of
Rogers Dry Lake when the shuttle touches down.
   The convoy will spend about an hour ``safing'' the orbiter to
make sure hazardous vapor levels are below dangerous levels and
attaching lines to cool the orbiter and purge it of fumes.
   When the procedure is complete, Vice President George Bush will
be whisked out to greet the five astronauts at the bottom of a
stairway outside the shuttle.
   ``We're going to take him out to meet the crew,'' National
Aeronautics and Space Administration spokesman Ralph Jackson said.
``Once we determine it is safe, we will take him out.''
   The shuttle was scheduled to end its four-day, 55-minute mission
_ America's first manned space flight since the explosion of
Challenger killed seven crew members 32 months ago _ with a 9:33
a.m. PDT landing.
   Bush staff members, who arrived in a large motorhome bearing a
photocopied sign displaying the presidential seal and marked
``Official White House Vehicle,'' met with NASA officials Saturday
to work out details of the visit. Bush said last week he would
attend in his official capacity as vice president, not as the
Republican presidential contender.
   NASA planned to conduct a full-scale drill Sunday by simulating
a shuttle landing.
   Other NASA crews will ``do a runway walkdown, looking for debris
that might be on the runway _ wood or nails or whatever,'' said
Charlie Baker, shuttle area manager for NASA's Dryden Flight
Research Facility at this Mojave Desert military base.
   Asked how he felt about Discovery's landing, Baker replied:
``Let's get her down and get on with it!''
   On Friday, the orbiter will be lifted atop a modified Boeing 747
jet for its return flight to Cape Canaveral, Fla.
</TEXT>
