<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev-Text 1stAdd a0625 10-01 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Text, 1st Add, a0625,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: already today.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The soviets will be able to tackle the new tasks only if they,
first and foremost, restructure themselves, the style and methods
of work.
   Each session, a meeting of the permanent commision, the
executive council and every day of deputy's work is to be filled in
with substantial work. The solution of the issues, put by the life
itself, should be brought under control.
   A great amount of work is in store for the soviets at all
levels, which is connected with the development of our state as a
rule-of-law one and a qualitative leap in society's legal
consciousness.
   It is precisely this way, through the extension and development
of the role of the soviets, that we will reach a rational
separation of rights and duties among the party and soviet bodies,
economic and public organizations.
   It is my conviction that under the current state of affairs,
this decision is the optimum way to promote perestroika, raise the
efficiency of the soviets and form a rule-of-law socialist state
basing on the unity of goals and everyone's responsibility for
one's work.
   It is precisely these criteria and the progress of perestroika
that we will apply to appraise all our future activities.
   Comrade deputies, it is an imperative of life, that the
remaining term of the current USSR Supreme Soviet be used to the
greatest advantage. A new impulse is needed to improve performance
of the Supreme Soviet, its Presidium, commissions and deputies.
   In accordance with the decisions of the 19th party conference,
the drafting of laws on changes and amendments to the constitution
and on the election of people's deputies is nearing completion. The
draft laws will soon be published for a nationwide discussion and
in November they are to be submitted for consideration to the
Supreme Soviet.
   Preparation for elections to the supreme body of power will
begin after the adoption of those laws. The newly elected congress
of people's deputies will form a new structure of central bodies of
power, with similar work to be carried out later at the republican
and local levels.
   This is a crucial task demanding thorough consideration by the
whole of our party. We will have to face many new problems and
adopt new approaches and methods of work, particularly in the light
of the separation of duties between the party and state bodies.
   The party will be most active in promoting the role of the
soviets, their self-dependence, initiative and responsibility in
attaining various economic, social and cultural goals.
   The soviets will take on their shoulders the major burden of
state work and energetically execute the party's economic, social
and nationalities policies at all levels.
   As we are beginning our effort to enhance the role of the
soviets, we should, of course, rely on the vast experience of the
Supreme Soviet and all soviets nationwide.
   At the same time, new forms required by perestroika should be
introduced boldly, as the old arsenal will not suffice here. The
new time we are living through today, the new conditions are posing
new objectives of greater scope.
   While tackling major domestic issues, the Supreme Soviet will
equally increase efforts in conducting the USSR foreign policy
which has in recent years acquired a dynamic and vigorous nature.
   Our international course is clear. It is the course of averting
the danger of a nuclear catastrophe, normalizing international
relations, establishing relations of equality and mutual benefit
between the world's countries and peoples, broad cooperation in
various spheres and securing every nation's right to freely choose
its destiny.
   This policy is fervently approved by the Soviet people,
supported by our socialist friends, meets with ever growing
understanding among large sections of the international public, and
is already bearing fruit.
   We will continue to unswervingly pursue this policy.
   The role of the Supreme Soviet, its Presidium and standing
commissions, and the parliamentary group is exceptionally great in
the pursuance of Soviet foreign policies.
   I count on your support for my work.
</TEXT>
