<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Estonia     10-01 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Estonia,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalist Group Gets Greeting from Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Shake-Up, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLINN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a boost from Kremlin chief Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, Estonians on Saturday opened a congress of a popular
movement pushing for economic, cultural and political autonomy for
their tiny republic.
   Gorbachev sent his endorsement to the more than 3,000 delegates
of the People's Front through his protege, Vajno Vyalyas, leader of
Estonia's Communist Party.
   The opening session in the Town Hall of Estonia's capital,
Tallinn, occured as Gorbachev was elected president by the Supreme
Soviet in Moscow. He replaced Andrei Gromyko, who resigned.
   Vyalyas expressed Gorbachev's ``greetings and wishes for
success'' and was greeted by the delegates with applause.
   The main demands of the nationalist People's Front are to make
Estonian the republic's official language; give it the right to
trade with foreign countries; allow the republic to conduct
business within the Soviet Union independent of Moscow's control;
and limit migration of Russians into Estonia.
   Officials say 28 percent of the front's members also are members
of the Communist Party. The front claims membership of 60,000 of
Estonia's 1.5 million people.
   Leaders of the People's Front, formed in April, said they
recognize the primacy of the Communist Party in Soviet society and
do not seek to break out of the Soviet Union.
   ``The People's Front is not a party. It is a movement and it
will remain a movement,'' Edgar Savisaar, one of the group's
founders, said in a speech Saturday.
   But many members say privately that their ultimate goal is full
independence from the Soviet Union.
   The two-day session was called to adopt a political platform and
formally elect leaders. Similar groups have sprung up in the other
two Baltic republics, Lithuania and Latvia.
   The People's Front organized a demonstration by hundreds of
people Saturday night. They linked arms in a human chain along the
cobblestone streets of Tallinn and chanted ``Estonia is in our
hands.''
   The chain stretched across the old town to the castle-like
government building.
   There, demonstrators were asked to look toward the building in a
symbolic gesture in support of demands that the flag of the
formerly independent republic be flown together with the Soviet
Estonian flag.
   The congress got under way with the sounds of two horns played
by an elderly man and boy wearing Estonian national costumes on
Town Hall's huge stage.
   ``The country and its children are waiting for action,''
declared the opening speaker, Estonian stage actor and director
Mikk Mikiver. ``The future of Estonia is in our hands.''
   Vyalyas, whose ties to Gorbachev go back to the 1950s when they
were leaders of the Young Communist League, met with Gorbachev in
Moscow on Wednesday to discuss the republic's reforms.
   Vyalyas, a native Estonian, on June 16 replaced the unpopular
and non-Estonian party chief Karl Vaino. He said the Moscow
leadership has firmly backed movements like the People's Front, as
long as they in turn support Gorbachev's ``perestroika,'' or
restructuring program.
   The Baltic people, the most westward-looking of Soviet
nationalities, have seized upon Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness, to assert demands for preservation of their culture and
economic independence.
   Estonia has surged into Gorbachev's drive to revive the economy
and to address grievances of the country's more than 100
nationalities.
   The Baltic republics were independent countries from shortly
after the Bolshevik revolution of 1917 until 1940, when they were
absorbed into the Soviet Union.
   Under Gorbachev's more tolerant policies, Baltic residents have
taken to the streets to protest the secret pact between Nazi
Germany and the Soviet Union that divided Eastern Europe and led to
the Soviet takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
