<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Earthquake     10-01 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earthquake,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tremor Shakes Part of LA County on Anniversary of Destructive 1987
Temblor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake beneath the San Gabriel
Mountains shook parts of the San Fernando Valley on Saturday, the
first anniversary of a deadly temblor that caused millions of
dollars in damage in Los Angeles County.
   The 10:56 a.m. earthquake measured 3.5 on the Richter scale,
said Robert Finn, spokesman for the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   The earthquake occurred on a different fault than the
destructive Oct. 1, 1987, Whittier quake and was unrelated, Finn
said.
   Seismologists pinpointed the quake's epicenter at 19 miles north
of downtown, about five miles northwest of the Sunland district.
The location is in Angeles National Forest under the south slope of
the San Gabriels.
   The 1987 earthquake was centered in Whittier Narrows, southeast
of Los Angeles. It measured 5.9 on the scale and was followed by a
5.3-magnitude Oct. 4 aftershock. The two quakes caused eight
deaths, 200 injuries and $358 million in damage.
   An earthquake measuring 3.5 can cause slight damage in the local
area. Quakes measuring 5 and 6 can cause considerable to severe
damage.
   Residents and workers in the vicinity of Saturday's quake did
not report any damage.
   ``I'd almost describe it as if someone was just jumping up and
down on the roof a couple of times. We had a slight jar,'' said
Betty Smith, who works in the golf shop at the course in the Hansen
Dam recreation area. The dam is unused.
   Three Burbank residents called police to ask about the quake,
but nobody at the police station felt it, said said Sgt. Rick
Madrid.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
</TEXT>
