<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Delvalle     10-01 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Delvalle,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Begins Seizing Deposed President's Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has begun seizing the
assets of deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle, an affluent
businessman, the judge in charge of the confiscation said Saturday.
   Judge Lorenzo Parker Dupuy said the Treasury Department issued
the order after Delvalle was formally accused of acts ``harmful to
the people of Panama,'' including asking the United States to
freeze $54 million the National Bank of Panama had on deposit in
U.S. banks.
   The freeze, which helped bring the Panamanian economy to a near
standstill this spring, coincided with an unsuccessful opposition
drive to force Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the nation's de facto
ruler, to resign.
   Parker said he began confiscating Delvalle's assets on Thursday.
He said the government seized 18 racehorses stabled at the
Hipodromo President Remon in the capital.
   The judge said he did not know the value of the horses or the
rest of Delvalle's assets.
   The Santa Rosa sugar firm, one of Delvalle's main businesses,
will be confiscated Monday, Parker told The Associated Press.
   Parker said Treasury Secretary Orville Goodin has ordered every
bank in Panama to freeze Delvalle accounts and turn over his
records by Oct. 7. Goodin also ordered all public registries and
notaries to turn over any information they have on Delvalle's
business interests, he said.
   Delvalle, 50, served as president from Sept. 27, 1985, to Feb.
26, 1988.
   Noriega had the National Assembly replace him in February after
Delvalle tried to remove Noriega as head of the Defense Forces.
   Delvalle tried to get rid of Noriega after a U.S. grand jury
indicted Noriega on charges of drug trafficking and money
laundering. Noriega has denied the charges.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle, who has been in
hiding since his ouster, as Panama's president.
   Parker said the sugar firm, which includes a mill in Aguadulce,
110 miles from the capital, will continue to operate. Parker said
he will ``protect the interests of investors and workers.''
   Parker said seizure orders were also issued against the assets
of two Delvalle associates: Juan B. Sosa, a former ambassador to
the United States, and Alberto Garcia de Paredes, consul general in
New York. Both are still recognized by the United States.
   The judge said the assets of Gabriel Lewis Galindo, another
former ambassador to the United States, will also be seized.
Galindo is a key opposition leader.
</TEXT>
