<HEAD>Seventeen Reported Dead In Rocket Attack On Jalalabad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen people were killed when
eight rockets slammed into Afghanistan's eastern city of Jalalabad
on Saturday, Radio Kabul said.
   The state-run radio gave few details of the rocket attack. A
military correspondent with Afghanistan's official Bakhtar news
agency reported ``old men, women and children'' were among the
dead, said Radio Kabul.
   The report, monitored in Islamabad, said 34 people were injured.
   No one claimed responsibility, but Radio Kabul blamed ``criminal
extremist opposition,'' apparently referring to U.S.-backed Moslem
guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed government of Afghanistan.
   Radio Kabul also reported the deaths of two high-ranking Afghan
army officers. The two, General Abdul Rehman and Colonel Ghulam
Mustafa, were killed last month in the eastern province of Paktia,
the report said.
   The report did not give an exact date of the deaths or any other
details.
