<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Activist     10-01 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Activist,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escaped Activist Leaves U.S. Consulate For Medical Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black activist who escaped
to the U.S. Consulate after police allegedly tortured him left his
refuge Saturday to get medical treatment, his lawyers said.
   Activist Clifford Ngcobo holed up in the consulate on Sept. 21
after spending five months in detention without being charged. He
filed a civil court action alleging that police assaulted him and
tortured him with electric shocks while he was in custody.
   The government said Ngcobo will not be redetained under
emergency regulations, but he faces possible prosecution on a
charge of illegal weapons possession.
   Ngcobo had joined three prominent anti-apartheid leaders who
took refuge at the consulate after escaping on Sept. 13. The three,
all held without charge for more than a year, say they will not
come out until all political detainees are released.
   The law firm, Cheadle, Thompson and Haysom, said doctors who
examined the activist at the consulate determined that he required
long-term therapy for anorexia and anxiety.
   The law firm said the decision for Ngcobo to leave the consulate
was based partly on the Law and Order Ministry's assertion that he
would not be redetained.
   ``The immediate and most pressing reason for his departure from
the consulate, however, was to ensure that he received proper
medical care and to interact with people in a normal environment to
facilitate his recovery,'' the lawyers' statement said.
   ``He is very fearful of redetention after his experience at the
hands of the security police.''
</TEXT>
