<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite-WrongInfo     10-01 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite-Wrong Info,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Book's `InfoPages' Seem More Like `MisInfoPages'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The information section in a new Yellow
Pages directory mislabels a couple of interstates, describes a
thousand-foot tower visible ``from miles away'' that in fact was
never built, and in general contains so many goofs that the
red-faced publishers are just going to start all over.
   ``We're not sure just what form it will take, but we will
reprint it in some way, shape or form,'' said Charles O. Yokum, a
spokesman for the Ameritech Publishing Co.
   ``We're in the community to stay, so we have to make it right
and fix it so these kinds of errors don't happen again,'' Yokum
said.
   The 56-page InfoPages section is in the front of the 900,000
newly printed Indianapolis Yellow Pages directories. Yokum figures
the cost of reprinting the section will be at least $100,000.
   The ``Things to See and Do'' section of the ``InfoPages''
contains the biggest error, or, at least, the tallest. It directs
visitors to Indiana Tower, and describes it in great detail.
   ``Rising to a height of 1,000 feet, it is the centerpiece of
White River State Park, a landmark attraction,'' the description
reads. The only problem is the tower was deleted from the original
plans for the park.
   The section also has mislabeled interstate highways and an
alphabetized directory of city and county streets with
corresponding maps that don't have grid letters and numbers.
   It defines the Indiana University Natatorium, the indoor
swimming and diving complex, as ``a track and field stadium with
numerous tennis courts and a bicycle racing track.''
   ``There are too many mistakes for us to live with,'' Yokum said.
``So we will do it no matter how much it costs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
