<DOCNO> AP881001-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1844EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     10-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Attacks Bush's Comments on ACLU, Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson urged his supporters to vote for
fellow Democrat Michael Dukakis on Saturday, calling Republican
George Bush ``dangerous and mean-spirited'' and condemning Bush's
remarks about the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``You see, Mr. Bush, you call people who fight for liberty
subversive,'' Jackson said in remarks to about 1,000 people at a
voter registration rally at Operation PUSH headquarters. He said
the Republican presidential nominee was on an ``ugly and mean side
of history.''
   He said Bush's attacks on the organization are ``a back-handed
swipe at the entire civil rights community, not just the ACLU. ...
He was taking a back-handed swipe at the entire civil liberties
community.''
   ``There is something dangerous and mean-spirited about Bush,''
Jackson said.
   He also took Bush to task for the vice president's comments
during last Sunday's debate that many of the nation's homeless
people ``are mentally sick.''
   ``Bush assumes the homeless are homeless because something is
wrong with them emotionally,'' Jackson said, calling that ``a
contemptuous way the rich look down at the poor.
   ``I would remind Mr. Bush that Christmas, which we celebrate not
far from now, is not about big gifts for rich friends, it is not
about Santa Claus and reindeer. Christmas, Mr. Bush, is about a
homeless couple,'' Jackson said.
   Homeless people are simply poor and unemployed and need help,
the former Democratic candidate said.
   ``Mr. Bush turns his back on the homeless, following a tradition
of abandoning the homeless,'' Jackson said. ``The homeless are not
helpless and they must not be hopeless because they can hope. Hope
is on the way.''
   He said he supports Dukakis because there is a need to ``choose
a new direction'' in next month's presidential election.
   Jackson praised Dukakis' call for a national health insurance
program and criticized Bush for opposing it.
   ``When the president or vice president or the Supreme Court
justices or members of Congress get sick, the government takes them
to Walter Reed (Army hospital) and takes care of their medical
bills,'' he said.
   ``If it's good enough for the president, it's good enough for
all the people,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
