<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Scattered Over Southeastern Quarter Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms developed Saturday along a weak
weather disturbance moving slowly across the Mississippi Valley,
and over the Southeast and the southern Plains.
   The showers and thunderstorms associated with the weak
disturbance extended from the central Gulf Coast to Indiana,
western Ohio and eastern Wisconsin.
   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain and a flash flood
watch was issued for southwestern Alabama.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered along the southern
Atlantic Coast, and across central Oklahoma and north-central
Texas. A thunderstorm in central Oklahoma produced hail the
diameter of nickels southwest of the town of Minco.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 96 at Palm Springs,
Calif. Saturday morning's low was 17 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
ahead of a cold front from the Gulf Coast region to the northern
Atlantic Coast states and the Great Lakes region.
   Highs only in the 50s were predicted from North Dakota to Upper
Michigan; below 70 from Montana through the northern and central
Plains to northern New England; in the 80s across much of the
nation west of the Rockies, and across southern Texas, the central
Gulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast states; and in the 90s
in the desert Southwest and the valleys of southern California,
with readings above 100 degrees at some locations.
</TEXT>
