<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru   10-01 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0633,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haitian Colonel Charged In U.S. Forced to Retire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with state department comment,
captured men on television; picks up 8th graf: Paul, very ...;
edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haitians and Western diplomats
Saturday praised the military government's unexpected ouster of a
powerful colonel who faces drug charges in the United States.
   The removal of Col. Jean-Claude Paul as commander of the feared
Dessalines Barracks could prompt Washington to resume $60 million
in annual aid. The funds were cut off after last year's
election-day massacre in which thugs believed to be supported by
Paul's soldiers killed 34 people at the polls.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Susan Clyde said she was told Paul was
replaced by his second-in-command, Lt. Col. Guy Francois.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Sondra McCarty said
``recent developments, including the retirement of Col. Paul, are
steps in the right direction. The departure of Col. Paul in
particular will improve prospects for cooperation in anti-narcotics
efforts.
   ``Our objectives in Haiti remain the same: transition to a
freely elected government, respect for human rights, economic
justice and cooperation in anti-narcotics activities. Reinstatement
of aid continues to depend on concrete progress in all of these
areas,'' she said.
   Paul has been linked to the Tonton Macoutes, the hated personal
forces of the Duvalier dictatorship.
   In March, he was indicted by a federal grand jury in Miami on
charges of conspiring to import cocaine into the United States.
   Bursts of gunfire were heard late Friday night when the
government television announced Paul's forced retirement, but
Port-au-Prince was calm Saturday and it was quiet at the 700-man
Dessalines Barracks.
   ``A fine maneuver, a masterstroke,'' a Western diplomat said of
Paul's ouster. The diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he was told Paul was no longer in the barracks, but his
whereabouts were not known.
   Also Saturday, members of the Presidential Guard appeared on
state television with four handcuffed men, accused by the soldiers
of being Tonton Macoutes
   The soldiers said the men participated in the Nov. 29 election
massacre with weapons personally supplied by Paul. All denied
participation in the massacre.
   Paul, very popular among his troops, was the only major unit
commander to remain in power following the Sept. 17 enlisted men's
coup that overthrew Haitian ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and placed
Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril in power.
   Last week, the rank-and-file soldiers removed nearly 60
unpopular officers with ties to the Duvalier family regime.
   The television announcement said Paul's dismissal was signed by
Avril and Col. Carl Dorsainvil, minister of defense and interior.
   ``Perhaps his retirement is in response to the demands of the
Americans, but at the same time, there is a general cleanup in the
army,'' Communist Party leader Rene Theodore said Saturday.
   As head of the most brutal unit in Haiti's 7,000-member army,
Paul had been considered one of the most powerful figures in the
military. Soldiers who staged the coup against Namphy said they
wanted to name Paul armed forces chief, but decided not to because
of the drug charges.
   Haitian and diplomatic sources said Paul's ouster would likely
lead to renewed U.S. aid to Haiti. But the State Department has
conditioned a resumption of aid on democratic reforms and has said
Paul should answer the drug charges in court.
   Namphy reassigned Paul to an administrative position in June,
but Paul refused and was backed by President Leslie Manigat. Namphy
ousted Manigat, accusing him of meddling in army affairs, and Paul
remained head of his battalion. Paul did not intervene when
soldiers ousted Namphy on Sept. 17.
   Haitian politicians hailed the forced retirement after it was
announced Friday. They said it showed the 2-week-old government was
moving in the right direction.
   Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier ruled from 1957 until his death
in 1971, when his son, Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier, assumed
the presidency. On Feb. 7, 1986, after months of civil disorder,
Jean-Claude fled to exile in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
