<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShreveportShooting     10-01 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shreveport Shooting,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Youth Shot By Blacks In Shreveport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white teen-ager was shot and seriously
injured by a black early Saturday in this city scarred by recent
race riots but police said they didn't think it was a racial
incident.
   Todd Spillers, 17, a sophomore at Woodlawn High School, was on a
respirator but improving in the intensive care unit at
Willis-Knighton Hospital, where he underwent surgery, said his
mother, Kathy Ellerd.
   Mrs. Ellerd said she was told that Spillers was shot by one of a
group of blacks who shouted ``This is for Hot Biscuit!'' as they
drove off.
   The Hot Biscuit Restaurant was the site of what police said was
an unprovoked racial shooting in August of a black teen-ager by a
young white man. One man has been charged with second-degree murder.
   Police said they did not believe race was the main reason
Spillers was shot, but would give little other information about
the case. No arrests had been made Saturday.
   ``I don't feel it was a racial incident at this point,'' Police
Sgt. Milton McGrew said early Saturday. ``It was just bad words
that had passed between them.''
   Mrs. Ellerd said her son and two other white youths were walking
to a store when a group of blacks drove by in a car, firing a shot
out of the window.
   ``Todd and his friends thought it was a blank or a capgun. They
didn't think anything about it,'' she said. ``The black boys
hollered something. I think Todd hollered something at them when
they were passing by. They went three blocks, turned around and
came back.''
   Mrs. Ellerd said the youths told her that blacks got out of the
back seat and the front passenger seat.
   ``There was talking or words or whatever. Someone hit Todd. From
what I understand, the next thing is that he was shot,'' she said
in a telephone interview from the hospital.
   Police said no additional information would be available until
public information officer Cindy Butts went on duty Monday. Her
telephone number could not be found through directory assistance,
and Chief Charles Gruber's number is unlisted.
   The neighborhood was at least 10 miles from the Cedar Grove
neighborhood where blacks rioted Sept. 20-21 after a white
teen-ager killed a black in what police said was a drug deal gone
sour. The young girl has been charged with second-degree murder in
that killing.
</TEXT>
