<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MormonConference 1stLd-Writethru a0621 10-01 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mormon Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leader Says Time Is Now For Book of Mormon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs after 9th, `His keynote ...' to UPDATE with
appointments; picks up 10th graf pvs, `Other members.'
^By VERN ANDERSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying ``the time is now,'' Mormon Church
President Ezra Taft Benson on Saturday challenged members to flood
the world with the message of the faith's most cherished scripture.
   Addressing the opening session of the church's 158th Semiannual
General Conference in halting phrases, the 89-year-old ``prophet,
seer and revelator'' of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints sounded what has been the theme of his three-year presidency.
   ``Now my good saints, we have a very great work to perform in a
very short time. We must flood the earth with the Book of Mormon _
and get out from under God's condemnation for having treated it
lightly,'' Benson said.
   Considered the ``keystone'' of the Mormon faith, the 531-page
volume was published by church founder Joseph Smith in 1830. Smith
said he translated the work from gold plates given him by an angel
named Moroni.
   The church's 6.5 million members believe the book is a history
of ancient peoples who came to the Americas from the Middle East
and were visited by a resurrected Jesus Christ shortly after his
crucifixion.
   ``I do not know fully why God has preserved my life to this age,
but I do know this: that for the present hour he has revealed to me
the absolute need for us to move the Book of Mormon forward now in
a marvelous manner,'' said Benson, who was U.S. secretary of
agriculture in the Cabinet of President Dwight D. Eisenhower.
   ``We have the Book of Mormon, we have the members, we have the
missionaries, we have the resources and the world has the need,''
he said. ``The time is now.''
   Benson acknowledged he was ``getting older and less vigorous,''
but expressed gratitude for the prayers and support of the
membership.
   His keynote address for the two-day conference in the 6,000-seat
Tabernacle on Temple Square was beamed by satellite to more than
2,000 chapels in the United States, Canada and Puerto Rico.
   During the afternoon session, Richard G. Scott was appointed a
member of the Council of the Twelve, an advisory body to the
governing First Presidency. He fills a vacancy created by the death
of Marion G. Romney, 90, president of the Twelve.
   Scott, 59, was a member of the presidency of the First Quorum of
the Seventy and executive director of the church's vast Family
History Department. J. Richard Clarke, a member of the Seventy, was
named to replace Scott.
   The First Presidency also added four members to the Seventy,
which assists the Twelve and supervises 35,700 full-time
missionaries. The five-year appointments of Monte J. Brough, Albert
Choules, Lloyd P. George and Gerald E. Melchin brought Seventy
membership to 66.
   Other members of the church's all-male hierarchy condemned drug
abuse, gambling, government-run lotteries and television
advertising for beer and wine coolers.
   Elder Russell M. Nelson said the worldwide plague of drug
addiction won't be eradicated by government or law, but by personal
commitment.
   ``The solution to this problem ultimately is neither
governmental nor institutional. Nor is it a question of legality.
It is a matter of individual choice and commitment,'' Nelson said.
   Mormons in good standing do not smoke or drink alcohol, tea or
coffee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
