<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlaneChase     10-01 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Chase,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Stealing Plane, Landing On Turnpike, And Taking Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old student pilot took a small
airplane from an airport, landed it on a turnpike, then stole a car
in his attempts to flee police early Saturday morning, authorities
said.
   ``He didn't even solo yet,'' said Scott Buchanan of the novice
who took the two-seat Cessna from the flight school where Buchanan
is employed.
   The student, Douglas Ellison, of Lee, faces numerous charges,
including illegal use of an airplane, auto theft and resisting
arrest. He was released on bail on Saturday, police said.
   Police Officer Timothy Morgan, who arrested Ellison after
chasing him back to the airport, said the incident capped off a
three-week investigation at Allen Flying Service, which owned the
plane.
   The service had complained that someone was using its planes
after hours, he said.
   Morgan said he spotted the plane flying erratically during a
nighttime check at Skyhaven Airport in southeastern New Hampshire.
   He said Ellison landed at the airport, but apparently noticed
the police cruiser and started to take off again.
   Morgan said he chased the plane down the runway, driving
parallel to the plane and flashing his blue lights, but didn't
manage to prevent the escape.
   ``He must have at least read the (flight training) book,''
Buchanan said. ``That's not easy.''
   Police said they had to close part of the highway for half an
hour because of the incident. Ellison allegedly stole the car after
fleeing through a woods.
</TEXT>
