<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Defectors     10-01 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defectors,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Says Her Son Will Return To Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose son and daughter-in-law returned
from the Soviet Union last week said Saturday the couple plans to
move back to Moscow because they believe U.S. officials have
mistreated them.
   ``They are going back because of the lies that have been told,''
said Lavera Branch.
   Theodore and Cheryle Branch, after suffering financial setbacks
in Pennsylvania and Florida, moved to Moscow 10 months ago. They
said Soviet officials gave them a furnished apartment, jobs and
medical benefits.
   They said they were enticed to return to the United States by
U.S. Embassy officials in Moscow who promised to give them a place
to live, find jobs for them and reimburse $3,000 in travel
expenses. They also said the embassy offered help enforcing a court
judgment awarding them eight weeks' back wages from a Florida
broadcaster.
   But the State Department said no such promises were made.
   They plan to talk with Soviet officials in Washington, D.C., to
discuss entering the Soviet Union again, Lavera Branch said.
   Theodore and Cheryle Branch could not be reached Saturday at the
motel where they have been staying. Last week, Branch said the
couple might return to the Soviet Union but they were ``tired of
moving back and forth across the ocean at somebody's whim.''
   Branch's mother said the couple has been harassed by neighbors
about their decision to live in the Soviet Union.
   ``I'm afraid some people turned against them,'' she said. ``They
just take for granted that people who go to Russians are no good.
It's like we've all been brainwashed to believe that all the
Russians are terrible. But they're nice people just like
Americans.''
</TEXT>
