<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Zaire 4thLd-Writethru   10-01 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Zaire, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0692,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobutu Agrees To Visit South Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with later Botha comment; picks
up 10th pvs: The South...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GBADOLITE, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire met
Saturday with South African President P.W. Botha in Mobutu's
ancestral village and agreed to visit South Africa soon.
   After two hours of talks at Mobutu's palace near the border of
the Central African Republic, the Zairean leader told reporters he
accepted Botha's invitation to visit South Africa.
   ``Our relations are on a new path,'' Mobutu said, adding they
talked ``frankly and in great depth.''
   No black African leader has gone to South Africa since Botha
took power of the white-controlled government in 1978. No date was
set for the visit.
   Botha said he was ``most impressed'' with Mobutu's knowledge of
southern Africa affairs, calling the get-together ``a most
successful morning.''
   On his return flight to South Africa, Botha told reporters he
planned more diplomatic initiatives in Africa this year.
   ``Africa is talking to South Africa,'' said Botha.
   A joint statement released after the meeting said the two also
discussed jailed black South African activist Nelson Mandela and
the fate of six black South Africans facing the death penalty in
the 1984 mob killing of a black township official.
   Roland Darroll, a South African Foreign Affairs Department
spokesman, denied a report that Mandela was about to be released.
The report, from the French news agency Agence France-Presse,
quoted Mobutu Saturday as saying he had obtained Mandela's
``liberation, soon and without conditions.''
   Mandela, 70, leader of the anti-apartheid African National
Congress, was sentenced to life in prison in June 1964. Botha has
said he would release Mandela if he renounces violence, and Mandela
has refused.
   The statement also said Botha reiterated to Mobutu that he would
consider granting clemency to the six jailed South Africans, who
critics say have been wrongly implicated in the slaying, but only
after the appeals process is completed.
   The South African Broadcasting Corp., meanwhile, reported Mobutu
and the leaders of Gabon, Congo, Angola and Zambia planned to meet
in the Zambian capital of Lusaka on Thursday, apparently to discuss
developments in the Angolan war.
   In Kinshasa, the Zairean capital700 miles to the southwest,
where Botha's plane stopped to refuel, troops opened fire on about
200 students demonstrating at the University of Kinshasa against
his visit.
   Witnesses said at least two students were injured, one struck in
the neck by a bullet and another hit in the leg. Both were taken to
the university clinic for treatment but their conditions were not
known.
   The meeting was Botha's first with Mobutu and his third summit
in black Africa during his 10 years in power _ all of them the past
three weeks.
   On Sept. 13, Botha met with President Joaquim Chissano of
Mozambique, a longtime adversary of South Africa. The next day he
visited President Kamuzu Banda of Malawi, the only African country
to maintain full diplomatic relations with Pretoria.
   One of Botha's foreign policy goals has been to broaden ties
with black Africa without having to make substantive political
concessions to the disenfranchised black majority in his own
country.
   Botha told reporters he and Mobutu spoke about the latest round
of U.S.-mediated talks in the Congolese capital of Brazzaville,
aimed at a peace agreement between South Africa and Angola.
   ``We discussed peace in Africa and in southern Africa
especially. We discussed the Angolan question, which is of vital
importance to all of us, and we discussed the South-West Africa,
Namibia problem which is being dealt with in the near future,''
Botha said.
   Despite the lack of formal relations, Zaire and many other
African countries trade with South Africa and rely on its ports and
railroad lines for handling imports and exports.
   South African products are sold in Zaire, and more than a third
of Zaire's main export, copper, is routed through South Africa.
   The Brazzaville talks between South Africa and an Angolan-Cuban
delegation adjourned Thursday without agreement on a timetable for
withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola
supporting the government.
   South Africa has offered to begin implementation on Nov. 1 of a
United Nations plan for independence for South-West Africa, or
Namibia, if a Cuban withdrawal from Angola can be negotiated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
