<DOCNO> AP881001-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 2220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Unrest     10-01 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Unrest,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resigns from Yugoslavia's Presidium Membership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former president of the Yugoslav
communist party resigned from the party Presidium on Saturday and
said he was unhappy with the simmering ethnic unrest over a
disputed province.
   The resignation of Bosko Krunic was reported by the official
Tanjug news agency. It is the second time a top Yugoslav official
has stepped down recent days.
   The changes appear to boost the chances of Serbia's hard-line
party chief Slobodan Milosevic in his bid to gain tighter control
over the republic's two autonomous provinces, Vojvodina and Kosovo.
   Krunic, 59, was known to have opposed Milosevic's centralist
plans.
   Franc Setinc, a member of the 23-man top party body, resigned
Monday after warning against ``the destructive avalanche engulfing
the country.''
   Tens of thousands of Serbs have demonstrated in recent weeks in
support of Milosevic's drive. More rallies were reported Saturday.
   Krunic, who held the rotating one-year post as president of the
ruling League of Communists until July, told a Presidium session on
Saturday that in recent months he was ``exposed to many
unprincipled hecklings and unsubstantiated charges, including
slanders in some (Yugoslav) media and at public rallies,'' Tanjug
said.
   As a former party leader, he felt responsible for the
``unsuccessful settlement of acute problems in (Yugoslav) society
and for inadequate results in the work of the Presidium,'' Tanjug
quoted Krunic as saying.
   Krunic said he was displeased with the daily rallies held in
Serbia, where Slavs were protesting alleged ethnic Albanian
harassment in the restive province of Kosovo, which borders Albania.
   Most of the Slavs are Christian while most Kosovo Albanians, who
make up 90 percent of the population in that province, are Moslem.
   
   Milosevic' opponents claim he is using the rallies to further
his plans for control over the autonomous provinces.
   The split in the top Yugoslav leadership over possible solutions
to end ethnic strife in Kosovo is expected to dominate a meeting of
the party's Central Committee set for Oct. 17.
</TEXT>
