<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smuggler-AIDS     10-01 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smuggler-AIDS,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Smuggler To Open AIDS Hospice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge with a tough reputation
has tentatively agreed to let a man who helped import 11 tons of
marijuana to run a hospice for AIDS patients in lieu of a maximum
15-year prison sentence.
   U.S. District Judge Gene Carter said he would agree to the
alternative sentence for Harvey Prager pending submission of
additional papers from attorneys. He set sentencing for Oct. 7.
   Carter has a reputation for imposing severe sentences in drug
cases. And Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph H. Groff III said the
judge had accepted alternative sentencing only a few times and
``never to this magnitude.''
   But then, ``no one has ever volunteered to live in an AIDS
hospice, either,'' said Groff, who recommended a prison term.
   Carter tentatively accepted Prager's proposal to open an AIDS
hospice and act as resident manager, with his wife, for five years,
after hearing several witnesses who work on AIDS projects in Maine.
   The judge said he had thought more about Prager than he had
about any other defendant during his years on the bench. He called
his decision ``supremely difficult.''
   Prager, 41, of Yarmouth, helped smuggle marijuana into Maine at
Little Deer Isle during the summers of 1979, 1980 and 1981. He was
arrested in London last fall and was returned to Maine, where he
pleaded guilty in January to charges of conspiracy, possession and
importation of marijuana.
   Prager's involvement in smuggling was a ``very serious offense
against basic human decency,'' Carter said.
   No one could answer the question of whether it is ``an
acceptable trade-off'' to permit someone to do something good for
society, rather than go to prison, the judge said.
   Carter questioned several people who appeared in court on
Prager's behalf.
   ``If I have anything to do with it, he will not fail,'' said Dr.
Michael Bach, an AIDS specialist at Maine Medical Center. ``We are
in desperate need of a hospice, and we will have one within six
months'' if Prager were allowed to proceed.
   Prager has been working with Bach to help terminally ill AIDS
patients.
   Carter said he was concerned about how the public would view
Prager's atonement for such a serious crime. But Dr. Owen B.
Pickus, also an AIDS specialist in Portland, said the public
``would not view this is an easy-out option.''
   The judge also asked Prager why he should not go to jail.
   ``I have been given enormous gifts,'' Prager said. Although he
``squandered those gifts inexcusably'' he was confident he could
``make so much more of a contribution by going forward with this
alternative sentencing proposal.''
   More than 20 other people connected with the smuggling operation
have been sentenced to prison terms of up to 10 years. Groff said
he talked with several of them and none objected to Prager's
alternative sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
