<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DogAttack     10-01 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dog Attack,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Child Attacked by Dog from Same Shelter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WALTON BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dogs adopted from the same animal
shelter have attacked two children, killing one and seriously
injuring the second in separate incidents a week apart.
   Bobby Ivy, 5, needed 25 stitches to close facial wounds suffered
when he was bitten Thursday by an old English sheepdog named
Tinkerbell, who was adopted a day earlier, said the boy's mother,
Hope Ivy of Fort Walton Beach.
   Nathan Carpenter, 4, was killed Sept. 23 by a large mixed-breed
at nearby Wynnhaven Beach. A neighbor had adopted the dog named
Chief about two hours earlier.
   Both dogs were from the Panhandle Animal Welfare Society, known
as PAWS.
   ``I'm going to have the (PAWS) board review our adoption
policy,'' said the shelter's executive director, Mike Zoller. ``At
this point, if someone tells us a dog has any history of any
aggression, we're not going to put it in the (adoption) program.''
   Zoller described Chief as a lovable dog, and said when Chief's
owners dropped him off Sept. 12, they didn't mention any aggressive
tendencies.
   In the first attack, Chief escaped from his new owner's yard and
was found by the victim's mother, Sharon Kay Carpenter. She noticed
the PAWS tag, put the animal in her yard where her son was playing
and phoned the shelter to find out who owned the dog. The attack
began while she was on the telephone.
   Tests found Chief was not rabid after a sheriff's deputy shot
the dog.
   Tinkerbell was back at PAWS Friday under a 10-day quarantine,
although she is up-to-date on rabies shots, Zoller said. She
probably will be destroyed after the quarantine, he said.
   A record number of bite cases have been reported to the shelter
since the fatal attack last week, Zoller said.
   ``We must have eight or nine dogs in quarantine now,'' he said.
``I think it must be because people are acting strange around the
dogs now and the dogs can sense it.''
</TEXT>
