<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSAds     10-01 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Ads,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ad Campaign Urges Condom Use To Block AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's leading producer of public-service
announcements released a national advertising campaign Friday
urging sexually active Americans to use condoms to prevent the
spread of AIDS.
   U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop endorsed the campaign at a
news conference, noting that it may be controversial but calling on
the media to carry it. The three major television networks said
they would.
   ``The public service campaign of The Advertising Council may
offend some people. I'm truly sorry about that,'' Koop said. ``You
cannot ignore people who might not have your own morality.'
   Critics of such advertising in the past have said it was
preferable to stress abstinence and monogamy, rather than the use
of condoms, to halt the sexual transmission of the AIDS virus.
   Koop, however, called abstinence ``not a viable option for most
people'' and said many people also are not monogamous.
   The Ad Council, a not-for-profit organization that has been
producing public service promotions since 1942, has produced
several highly successful public service campaigns, such as the
``Take a Bite Out of Crime'' promotion.
   At least two other national advertising campaigns have urged the
use of condoms against AIDS, one sponsored by the federal Centers
for Disease Control and another from the American Medical
Association. Some of those ads were broadcast on network television.
   The council, sponsored by the advertising and communications
industries, distributes its ads to media outlets for use at their
discretion.
   ``This is not the first time we will be airing PSAs that deal
with that subject directly,'' said Dom Giofre, NBC's spokesman.
``What is significant here is that The Ad Council, which is a
major, very thorough group, is getting into this thing.''
   Spokesmen for ABC and CBS said they, too, would broadcast the
announcements. ABC and NBC ran spots with a similar message last
year, but CBS did not. Cable News Network spokesmen said they had
not seen the spots yet.
   The project includes three spots in English and Spanish for
television, radio, print and outdoor transit display.
   In one TV ad, a youth standing in the rain says: ``My brother
wouldn't listen to me. I told him: `You have sex, you use condoms
so you don't get AIDS.' He laughed and said condoms weren't macho.''
   The youth then crumples to a sitting position, his back against
a tombstone. ``My brother,'' he says. ``He was so macho.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
