<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     10-01 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed, 10 Wounded In Latest Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One Palestinian was killed and
three wounded Friday in violence triggered by a confrontation
between a Jewish settler and Arabs who stoned his car, officials
and witnesses said.
   In addition, the army said an 18-year-old boy was killed in
Hebron when soldiers opened fire after they were stoned by a group
of masked Arab youths. Hospital officials said Zain Hafez Karaki
died of bullet wounds to the chest and arm.
   There were conflicting reports about what caused the death of
the other Arab.
   Palestinian witnesses said the man was shot by one of about 15
Jewish settlers who gathered in downtown Hebron at the site where
settler leader Rabbi Moshe Levinger's car was stoned.
   But police spokesman Mordechai Barakat said an investigation
showed Levinger only fired a single shot in the air.
   An army spokesman said an autopsy would be performed to
determine the cause of death. She said one report indicated the
Arab died when he fell from a roof while fleeing gunshots.
   The army declared Hebron a closed military area and blocked
reporters from entering the city.
   Mukassad Hospital officials identified the dead man as Kayed
Hassan Salah, 38, who owned a shop near site of the shooting. They
said he died of bullet wounds to the back and left shoulder.
   The three wounded were a 14-year-old boy shot in the pelvis and
left thigh, a 20-year-old man shot in the right thigh and a
23-year-old man shot in the left shoulder, officials at Hebron's
Alia Hospital said.
   Seven other Palestinians were wounded Friday in clashes around
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, reports said.
   Levinger opened fire after about 30 Palestinians stoned his car,
Arab witnesses said. They said about 15 Israeli settlers joined
Levinger in firing their weapons.
   The city, where about 60 Jewish settlers live alongside 70,000
Arabs, has been the site of frequent clashes between Jews and Arabs
since the Palestinian uprising began in December.
   Levinger's wife Miriam told The Associated Press her husband
fired in the air when his car was stoned but said he was not
responsible for the Arab fatality and three other casualties.
   Mrs. Levinger, who emigrated to Israel from Brooklyn, N.Y., said
three of her children and a grandchild were in the car with her
husband but that she did not witness the incident herself.
   Abdul Rahman Abu Shekhadem, a Palestinian college student who
suffered a broken arm in the confrontation, said one of the Jewish
settlers sprayed the area with gunfire.
   ``He started shooting. He didn't know where he was shooting or
who he was shooting,'' Abu Shekhedem, 21, said from his bed at
Jerusalem's Mukassad Hospital.
   The deaths raised to 280 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising against Israel's 21-year occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip began Dec. 8. Six Israelis have also died in the
violence during the same period.
   Also Friday, Israel extended the closing of West Bank schools
and universities to Nov. 15 to try to prevent an expected rise in
violence by student activists, said Olivier Rafowicz, a spokesman
for the military administration.
   The 1,198 schools and universities attended by about 300,000
students were to have opened Sept. 1.
   The army also extended the closing of the Arab-run Palestine
Press Service for another year, the defense ministry said. The
service, closed in March for allegedly inciting violence, monitored
events in the occupied lands and was a key source for foreign
reporters.
</TEXT>
