<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Hijacking     10-01 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Hijacking,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacker Recovering From Wounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a hijacked Brazilian
jetliner said Friday that he took his plane into a dive before
landing in an effort to dislodge the hijacker's gun.
   The hijacker, who killed a co-pilot and wounded three others
before he was shot and captured Thursday, wanted to crash the VASP
Airlines Boeing 737 a government building in the Brazilian capital,
officials said. He was hospitalized in stable condition Friday,
authorities said.
   Raimundo Conceicao, 28, wounded three other crew members. He
held 98 passengers and another three crew members hostage for eight
hours before police shot him as he walked toward a getaway plane
with the pilot.
   The pilot, Fernando Murillo Silva, told TV Globo on Friday that
before landing in the central city of Goiania ``with only five
minutes worth of fuel left, I took the plane into a dive, hoping
the hijacker would fall on his head and release the gun.''
   Conceicao stumbled but held on to the gun and pointed it at the
pilot's head.
   As the plane landed at Goiania's Santa Genoveva airport,
Conceicao shot and killed co-pilot Salvador Evangelista and wounded
a flight engineer and a steward.
   Using his fingers to simulate the weapon, Silva described how
the hijacker put the gun to the co-pilot's head and pulled the
trigger.
   ``It was horrible,'' he said.
   A federal police spokesman, Paulo Marro, said the gunman
probably will stand trial for homicide and for endangering the
lives of those aboard.
   Marra said police did not have details on Conceicao's
background. Air Force Minister Octavio Moreira Lima earlier called
the hijacker ``a psychopath.''
   ``The hijacker told negotiators he wanted to settle accounts
with the president over the country's economic policies,'' Moreira
Lima said.
   Federal Police Chief Romeu Tuma said the hijacker told the
control tower he wanted ``to slam the Boeing 737 into a ministry
building in Brasilia.''
   Inflation for this year is forecast at 800 percent under
President Jose Sarney.
   Alcir Pereira, spokesman for the Santa Genoveva Hospital in
Goiania, said Conceicao had been successfully operated on and was
recovering. ``He is out of danger,'' he said.
   TV Globo showed Conceicao handcuffed to his hospital bed.
   Conceicao hijacked the twin-engine jet minutes after it left the
southeastern city of Belo Horizonte for Rio de Janeiro. He barged
into the cockpit and demanded that the pilot fly to Brasilia.
   After circling Brasilia, the pilot was told that because of
security reasons he could not land there, and the plane headed for
Goiania, 125 miles away.
   Air Force spokesman Col. Eden Avolinsque said Sarney gave orders
not to negotiate with the hijacker nor refuel the plane.
   As hundreds of heavily-armed police and army troops sealed off
the Goiania airport, Conceicao agreed to get off the airliner,
release the passengers and fly to Brasilia on a small turboprop
plane _ taking only the pilot as a hostage.
   As the hijacker was walking toward the smaller plane, special
police agents fired and wounded him. Conceicao then spun around and
shot Silva, wounding him in the leg.
</TEXT>
