<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-Press     10-01 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Press,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lower-Than-Expected Press Turnout For Discovery Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer than half the journalists who
requested credentials for the Discovery launch actually showed up,
and NASA on Friday blamed new restrictions on access for the lower
turnout.
   ``There were many who told us they were not coming when they
learned of the creation of a new press site on the causeway,'' said
a statement from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   The new site provided a view more than 6 miles from the shuttle,
whereas the Launch Complex 39 press site is just over 4 miles away.
   NASA said 2,318 news people picked up their accreditation
badges, compared to the 5,200 who requested credentials.
   The final number on hand for the launch _ the first U.S. manned
spaceflight since the 1986 Challenger disaster _ fell short of the
record 2,700 journalists who covered the Apollo 11 and Apollo 17
moon missions and the first space shuttle flight.
   Because of Air Force studies following Challenger that warned of
casualties that could be caused by falling debris from another
post-launch accident, Air Force officials responsible for range
safety at Kennedy Space Center recommended that only essential
personnel be allowed at the main press complex.
   Veteran space journalists were angered by the restrictions,
which they feared could lead to future tightening of coverage
allowed, especially for secret military missions.
   NASA and the Air Force finally compromised to allow 1,800 news
media representatives at the near site, giving larger allotments to
the news media with the tightest deadline pressures and need for
staff. The others had to watch from the causeway, without telephone
lines or computers at hand.
   However, Jay Barbree, who has covered the space program for
three decades for NBC News radio, said he thought the Discovery was
one of the most extensively reported launches. He said the amount
of time its coverage was carried on the national networks was the
most he could recall.
   ``A lot of the people who get accredited are really coming here
to watch. So the tourists didn't come because of the restrictions,
but the working press covered it comprehensively,'' Barbree said.
   Reporters at the secondary site said their view was excellent,
but that their separation from communications equipment was a
handicap.
</TEXT>
