<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleExperiments     10-01 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Experiments,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Float Inside Orbiter, Conduct Experiments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experiment similar to shaking up
oil and vinegar turned out to be more like mixing an ``egg white in
an egg yolk'' when astronaut David C. Hilmers and fellow Discovery
crew members performed the test Friday.
   Hilmers and George D. ``Pinky'' Nelson spent part of the morning
working on the experiment known as phase partitioning, and some of
their activities were broadcast on NASA's satellite television
channel.
   ``It's a little experiment that tries to look at the fluid
dynamics of separating two different phases of materials,'' Hilmers
said.
   Researchers hope the experiment will help them better understand
the role gravity and other physical forces play in separating
unmixable liquids. During the experiment, two polymers are
dissolved in a saline solution and they then separate.
   on Earth, the heavier material floats on top of the other, but
the outcome is much different in space where there is no gravity.
   ``Pinky and I have been shaking up this phase partitioning
experiment. It's a lot like shaking up vinegar and oil _ in 0 g
(gravity) it has a somewhat different mixing. It's more like an egg
white in an egg yolk,'' Hilmers added, and laughter followed from
another astronaut.
   In all, there are 11 experiments the astronauts will conduct
during their four-day mission, including two student projects.
   The first post-Challenger flight's main purpose _ to deploy a
communications satellite _ was completed early Friday when a
two-stage booster rocket pushed the satellite into its final orbit.
   NASA grounded shuttles missions after the Challenger exploded
Jan. 28, 1986, and the disaster also halted researchers' efforts to
test their theories in space for more than 2{ years.
   Hilmers said the phase partitioning experiment was a good
example of the need for manned spaceflights.
   ``I guess one of the things this (experiment) can show is the
use of people in space. We can look at the experiment, see if there
are any unique changes and observe them. We can take pictures as we
see unique changes, and possibly modify the experiment,'' he said.
   An experiment completed earlier Friday was the aggregation of
red blood cells, which consists of blood samples donated by people
with various illnesses such as cancer and diabetes.
   During the experiment, a pump flushes each blood sample through
a system in an effort to study how red blood cells collect in 0
gravity. Two 35mm cameras photograph the experiment, and Nelson
said the device seemed to be working.
   ``We could hear it whirling and taking pictures all night
long,'' he said.
</TEXT>
