<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hogs-Pork     10-01 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hogs-Pork,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swine Inventories at Five-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hog farmers continue to expand production,
with inventories in the major pork states this fall the largest in
five years, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   As of Sept. 1, the inventory of hogs and pigs in the 10 major
pork states totaled an estimated 45.1 million head, up 5 percent a
year ago and 14 percent more than two years ago, the report said.
That was the biggest 10-state inventory on Sept. 1 since 1983.
   The report also included for the first time a total U.S.
inventory figure for Sept. 1 _ 58.3 million head.
   In the 10 biggest states, which account for about 77 percent of
the U.S. total inventory, the number of breeding hogs was up 3
percent and 12 percent from Sept. 1, 1987 and 1986, respectively,
to 5.47 million head. That indicated further production increases
in the coming months.
   Officials said the 10-state Sept. 1 inventory of market hogs _
animals headed for slaughter and the consumer market _ totaled 39.6
million head, up 5 percent and 14 percent from the previous two
years, respectively.
   The 10-state pig crop during the summer months of June, July and
August was 17.9 million head, up 2 percent from the same period a
year ago and 11 percent more than in the summer of two years ago.
   Looking a future prospects, the report said hog farmers surveyed
in the 10 states intend to have 2.35 million sows give birth in
September, October and November, up 4 percent from farrowings a
year ago and 11 percent more than in 1986.
   The following list shows the Sept. 1 inventory. The first
number, in thousands, is the total number of hogs in the state, the
second is the Sept. 1 figure's percentage of a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Georgia         1,300  113
Illinois        6,100  111
Indiana         4,600  101
Iowa           14,500  101
Kansas          1,540  112
Minnesota       4,930  108
Missouri        3,150 105
Nebraska        4,000  103
North Carolina  2,650  104
Ohio            2,300  105
