<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pilots-Drugs     10-01 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pilots-Drugs,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 Pilots Charged With Concealing Drug, Alcohol Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven pilots accused of lying about
drug and drinking convictions on license applications were indicted
Friday in a government crackdown on unreported abuses among the
nation's pilots.
   Among those charged are 12 current or former commercial pilots,
including a pilot for Delta Air Lines. That pilot and a former Pan
American World Airways pilot were the only ones identified as
employees of major passenger airlines.
   The indictments issued Friday also named two student pilots, 10
private pilots and three others. All but three are from Florida.
   ``These indictments are the first in a special nationwide
project ... to vigorously pursue this abuse in a critical sector of
the nation's transportation system,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert
Genzman.
   Genzman said authorities knew of no mishaps involving those
charged.
   In Washington, Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said
hundreds of indictments were expected as a result of the nationwide
investigation. He said the charges were ``indicative of the serious
problem of drug and alcohol abuse which has permeated all walks of
life and all professions in our society.''
   The Transportation Department has proposed a broad range of drug
tests, including random tests, of commercial airline pilots and
other flight crew personnel.
   A spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration said the
past convictions would not have necessarily precluded the pilots
from obtaining a medical certificate and pilot's license.
   But, said spokesman Fred Farrar, the fact that the applicants
had past convictions for drug- or alcohol-related offenses would
have caused an FAA medical examiner to ``look long and hard at the
circumstances.''
   Friday's indictments were the result of a two-year investigation
that began with an audit of the national driver's registry to
uncover alcohol or drug-related traffic violations, said Ben Lorigo
of the Department of Transportation inspector general's office in
Washington.
   Painstaking computer checks of 711,000 pilots around the country
revealed 10,200 had had driving privileges revoked in the previous
seven years and 750 of them had failed to report it on the required
FAA medical forms, he said at a news conference in Tampa.
   The 27 indicted Friday, if convicted on all charges, could each
face at least five years in prison and fines ranging from $5,000 to
$250,000 for making false statements to the FAA on medical
certificates.
   The concealed convictions included drunken driving, trafficking
in cocaine and possession of marijuana.
   Genzman said there was an amnesty program within the last
several years to allow those who had withheld information on their
forms to come forward. Some did, but the number was very low,
Genzman said, indicating to federal authorities the problem was
widespread.
   Of the former and current commercial pilots charged, Lorigo said
some may be retired or fly as a sideline, and not as a career pilot.
   The Delta pilot, Fred Kopec, 27, of Orlando, was charged with
failing to reveal a drunken driving arrest in Lee County, Ala., in
January 1984.
   Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate in Atlanta confirmed Kopec worked
for the airline, but said Delta had not yet been formally notified
of his indictment.
   When Delta is informed, ``we will take the appropriate action,
which would be to suspend the pilot,'' Ms. Pate said.
   Another Delta spokesman, Jim Lundy, said Kopec has worked for
Delta for two years and is a second officer for L-1011 jetliners.
   Kopec could not be reached for comment Friday. A telephone
number in Orlando for Kopec could not be located.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
