<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DoE-Nuclear     10-01 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DoE-Nuclear,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Question Safety Of DoE Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The safety of Department of Energy nuclear
reactors came under heavy criticism at a congressional hearing
Friday, with one department official comparing the situation to the
ill-fated space shuttle Challenger.
   ``There are currently some senior managers within the department
with an attitude toward production reactor safety which on the face
seems to be similar to that which existed in the space program
prior to the Challenger accident,'' said an internal memo released
at the hearing.
   The Sept. 16 memo was written by Richard Starostecki, a deputy
assistant secretary, to his boss, Ernest Baynard III, the assistant
energy secretary for environment, safety and health.
   Starostecki said the safety office staff is often challenged to
prove that the department's reactors, which produce nuclear
materials for the Department of Defense, are unsafe before
officials will act on the office's concerns.
   His memo did not identify the senior managers, but it did say
that Secretary John Herrington and Deputy Secretary Joseph Salgado
had taken ``steps to overcome this attitude and lack of technical
inquisitiveness.''
   This and other memos critical of the operations of department
facilities were distributed at a joint hearing by the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee and the House Government Operations
subcommittee on environment, energy and natural resources.
   The focus of the hearing was an incident in August when there
was an unexpected power surge during the restarting of one of the
reactors at the Savannah River Plant in South Carolina.
   Witnesses said employees of the plant's operator, the du Pont
Co., ignored the surge _ caused by some partially activated tritium
left in the reactor vessel _ and continued to power the reactor,
which eventually shut itself down.
   The department's safety office and outside consultants later
concluded that no procedures for such a situation had been
established during the 30 years the plant has been operating.
   Dexter Peach of the congressional General Accounting Office said
there was no danger of the reactor going out of control, ``but
nobody knew it at the time.''
   ``This could have been another Chernobyl if they had guessed
wrong,'' said Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio. ``If I didn't know what was
going on in a nuclear reactor, I would shut it down.''
   Asked to characterize the overall safety ethic at the Savannah
River Plant, Robert Keller, a senior nuclear engineer with the
safety office, replied: ``I would use the term seat-of-the-pants,
or cavalier.''
   Added Robert Smith, the safety office's representative at the
plant: ``They do not have the technical understanding of basic
principles to allow them to make a good decision, to put the
reactor in a safe condition if it was in an unsafe condition. These
operators do not have the knowledge.''
   The officials said that although Westinghouse Corp. is taking
over for du Pont next year, many of the control room people will be
remaining on the job.
   Starostecki, who said he lacked confidence in the control room
personnel, testified that had the power surge occurred at a
commercial nuclear power plant, federal rules would have required
an immediate shutdown.
   He said that in the last 17 years, problems at Savannah River
reactors have forced about 9 to 12 shutdowns a year. ``A commercial
reactor would have difficulty with three or four a year,'' he said.
   He said inspections have turned up ``several hundred
deficiencies'' at the plant's P reactor and that ``portions of the
plant have been operating in a very poor condition for years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
