<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     10-01 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Begings Weekend Of Debate Preparations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle took time out from staff briefings Friday to raise money and
tour a fire equipment exhibition before a weekend of mock debates
leading up to his confrontation next week with Democratic
countrpart Lloyd Bentsen.
   The Indiana senator boarded his campaign plane clutching some
briefing notebooks after a day in which he underwent questions and
answers from his aides in what a spokesman said was a preliminary
run-through of the format for debate Wednesday in Omaha, Neb.
   ``We're ready,'' Quayle told reporters at the exhibition of fire
engines, fire boats and hooks and ladders.
   In a reference to the media scrutiny he has faced since becoming
George Bush's running mate, Quayle told the audience of several
hundred firefighters: ``I want you all to know I'm very accustomed
to putting out fires. I've learned that in my trade.''
   ``We look forward to the competition of ideas in the debate
ahead of us because we're going to debate the future,'' he said.
   Spokesman David Prosperi said that on Saturday, Quayle would
conduct a formal mock debate with Sen. Bob Packwod, R-Ore., who is
standing in for Bentsen in the debate preparations. The sessions
will be videotaped and Quayle will review them over the weekened.
   He is getting advice from Roger Ailes, George Bush's media guru,
who sat in on Friday's sessions. The sessions are being held at an
undisclosed office building in the Washington area.
   Aides say the strategy for the debate will be to concentrate on
Michael Dukakis, not on his running mate.
   ``I think Bentsen has to try and explain the positions of his
running mate and convince the viewing audience and others that
Dukakis is in the mainstream,'' Prosperi said. ``Bentsen is not the
issue. The issue is the qualifications of his running mate.''
   The circle of aides that participated in Friday's briefings
included Stuart Spencer, Quayle's campaign manager; Ken Khachigian,
his speechwriter; Jim Cicconi, his research director; Mitch
Daniels, former White House political director; Prosperi and Ailes.
Packwood also sat in on the session, Prosperi said.
   ``We are just trying to familiarize him with the format, the way
the debate is set up, and discuss how to deal with probable and
possible attacks by Sen. Bentsen ,'' @e cav.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
