<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   10-01 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0624</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday Sept. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Diamonds in Copper and Iron Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on assignment. Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies are trying to add some glitter to the drab copper
and iron-ore mining scene of far northern Michigan.
   It started as a glint in a Dow Chemical Co. metallurgist's eye.
First Dow, and now a Colorado company, Crystal Exploration Inc.,
entered the search for diamonds in the state's Upper Peninsula.
   Seven Kimberlite pipes _ volcanic rock shafts that can yield the
earth's hardest mineral _ have been discovered.
   Core drilling has unearthed a scattering of sand-grain sized
diamonds, too few and too small for commercial production. But the
explorers say the search is young.
   The pipe formations are in a 40-mile area around Iron Mountain
and Crystal Falls, at the western end of the Upper Peninsula along
the Wisconsin border.
   In the few places on earth they are found, Kimberlite pipes
occur in clusters of up to several dozen, said James Huml, a Dow
research associate.
   Huml, a metallurgist by trade and geologist by avocation, said
he thinks there are more than a dozen Kimberlite pipes in the Upper
Peninsula.
   Dow has searched for six years. Now more exploration and mining
expertise is needed, Huml said. ``Dow is not a hard-rock mining
company.''
   Dow recently sold its mineral leases and geological data, for an
undisclosed amount, to Crystal Exploration Inc., a Colorado
subsidiary of Sydney, Australia's Restech International Ltd.
Restech has mineral exploration and gold mining operations in
western Australia.
   It will carry on the search, while Dow holds onto an option to
take part in the exploration and development, and to share in any
profits.
   Occasional diamond finds in Ohio farm fields in the late 1800s
and early 1900s long had geologists looking to te north, said
Crystal Exploration's president, Sigfried Muessig.
   Muessig said a Kimberlite pipe, named for Kimberly in the
diamond-mining region of South Africa, is the only formation known
to produce the gems.
   ``It is a cylindrical formation where volcanic rock has come up
120 miles from the bowels of the earth, and the heat and pressure
have formed the diamonds,'' he said.
   ``It's a very rare occurrence,'' Huml said. Other Kimberlite
pipes have been found in Arkansas, Kansas, Wyoming and Colorado.
None commercially produce diamonds.
   There were no volcanic remnants in Ohio, so geologists thought
glaciers carried the diamonds there from Canada, Muessig said.
   But he said the focus shifted in 1981 when the U.S. Geological
Survey found a Kimberlite formation _ the Lake Ellen Pipe _ about
10 miles northeast of Crystal Falls.
   It was evidence that volcanoes smoked and spewed nearly 200
million years ago in the Upper Peninsula, and possibly generated
the heat and compression forces to leave a diamond treasure behind.
   The glaciers flattened the volcanoes, but since 1981 Dow has
found six more Kimberlite pipes _ several hundred feet across at
the surface and covered by volcanic debris, Huml said.
   In Dow's explorations, he said, ``We have found microdiamonds,
generally small, less than a millimeter in diameter. They are
grain-sized.''
   But the explorers still think the western Upper Peninsula was
the source of the gems found in farm fields to the south. ``We
think there is good potential, because of the historical finds,''
Muessig said.
   Crystal Exploration will do more sampling in the already
discovered pipes in the next year, Muessig said, and will continue
exploring for more Kimberlite formations, ``in hopes the next pipe
we discover will have gem-quality stones.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday Sept. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Childs ADV07   10-01 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Childs, ADV 07,0792</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Oct 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Toni Childs: Singing Words From Within</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Toni Childs leafs through
a stack of press clippings comparing her favorably to Joan
Armatrading, Phoebe Snow, Janis Ian, Tracy Chapman, Suzanne Vega,
Miriam Makeba and Laura Nyro.
   She's been seeing a lot of stories like that since her first
album, ``Union,'' was released by A&M Records in the spring.
   ``I can give you more,'' she says with a sublime smile and a
hint of frustration. ``Grace Slick, Bette Midler, Annie Lennox,
Janis Joplin _ every female that anybody's ever liked, I think.''
   The smile reflects her unswaying confidence that new singers
will one day be compared with Toni Childs. The frustration suggests
the comparisons are flattering but imprecise.
   Using images that flow _ sometimes subconsciously _ from her own
extraordinary experiences, and a songwriting style that relies more
on intuition than technique, Childs has set herself apart from the
current crowd of women singers.
   For one thing, she says she often writes and performs in a
trance.
   Half a lifetime ago, the 30-year-old singer left an unhappy home
for a journey that took her through a Northern California commune,
federal prison, Europe and the arms of musician David Ricketts. She
moved in with Ricketts in 1985, on the day she signed her contract
with A&M and shortly before Ricketts and David Baerwald hit it big
with David & David's highly successful ``Boomtown'' album.
   The love affair failed but the painful break-up inspired several
of the songs of self-discovery on ``Union,'' and she and Ricketts
remain close friends. They worked together on Childs' first album,
and she said he will play a big role in her second.
   Childs is planning to travel with Ricketts to Africa, Bali and
India in search of ``tones'' that will shape her second LP. They
have already begun work on some new songs, but she said the themes
and most melodies will be a product of her upcoming trek.
   ``All I know is that there are certain places I want to go
because of the tones, that I'm being drawn there because of the
tones. The tones always dictate to me what's really going on. So
I'm going to be true to that for whereever it's going to take me,''
she said in an interview.
   ``Maybe that's a really cosmic way of doing it. But the tones
hit parts of me that make me release things, or make me see things,
or maybe make me ask the questions that I wouldn't ordinarily ask.
And then I get answers that I find out for me.''
   She not only instinctively selects her destinations, but relies
on instinct when writing her songs, a process which has as much to
do with solving private mysteries as with making music.
   ``Your subconcious speaks to you really strongly, and when
you're doing something like music ... it's like dream time ... and
it's good to kind of pay attention to it,'' she said.
   Although her songs often sound like poems set to music, only one
song from the first album _ ``Zimbabwe'' _ actually started out
that way. The others extended from improvising with Ricketts on a
combination of ``groove and melody and mood.''
   ``You just kind of get in this trance with it and then these
words start coming out and, for me, the challenge is to find out
what ... I'm telling myself,'' she said. ``It unlocks some sort of
side of you that sometimes you might not have the courage to take a
look at.''
   That sort of spontaneity doesn't always translate well to a
stage performance, but Childs drew ovations at San Francisco's
famed Fillmore auditorium as she rocked through powerful versions
of songs that sounded more gentle on the album. No wonder the
comparisons to Joplin, Slick and Lennox.
   ``My sort of thing is to get in my trance,'' she said of her
live shows. ``(To) go back to the same place that the song
actually, originally came from _ that's my goal.''
   Although her introspective lyrics often ``haunt'' her, Childs
said her music has been most important to her as a way of looking
at her life.
   ``You know, on a pressure cooker it has that little place where
the steam escapes,'' she said. ``Well that's been my out, (a way)
to take a look at my life and the mistakes I've made, the choices
I've made or what choices I want to make.
   ``That's really what the music's about.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Oct. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
