<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Eliot ADV03   10-01 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Eliot, ADV 03,1010</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Centenary of T.S. Eliot Celebrated</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``All our knowledge brings us nearer to our ignorance, All our
ignorance brings us nearer to death, But nearness to death no
nearer to God,'' T.S. Eliot, ``The Rock.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His poetry reflected the anguish of life, and his
pessimism was viewed archly by some. Still, T.S. Eliot was embraced
by the world as one of the major 20th century poets in the English
language.
   This year, his centenary year, has witnessed an outpouring of
celebrations for the late Nobelist, who himself considered William
Butler Yeats the greatest poet of our time.
   Thomas Stearns Eliot was born in St. Louis on Sept. 26, 1888. He
lived in London from 1914 and became a British citizen in 1927. He
won the Nobel Prize in literature in 1948 and died in London on
Jan. 4, 1965. His poetic gift was extraordinary, from the
despairing early works _ ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock,''
``The Waste Land'' _ to his later, more hopeful visions, such as
``Ash Wednesday'' and ``Four Quartets.''
   He also was a critic and dramatist, and his plays include
``Murder in the Cathedral,'' ``The Family Reunion'' and ``The
Cocktail Party.''
   On the 100th anniversary of his birth, Westminster Abbey held a
service at which admirers read from his works and his widow,
Valerie, laid a wreath at his memorial tablet.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Let us go then, you and I,
   ``When the evening is spread out against the sky
   ``Like a patient etherised upon a table.''
   _ ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   There have been other readings from Eliot's works throughout
England, two sessions filling London's Queen Elizabeth Hall and
Palace Theater with Poet Laureate Ted Hughes and veteran poet
Stephen Spender taking part.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. is airing five radio programs on
Eliot's long poem, ``Four Quartets,'' and performing four of his
plays.
   Eliot's work is the centerpiece of Europe's largest annual
literature festival, Oct. 1-16 at Cheltenham in western England.
Irish poet Seamus Heaney, considered one of the outstanding living
English-language poets, is giving the major festival lecture called
``On Learning From Eliot.''
   ``Quotations from Eliot like `the skull beneath the skin,' and
`in my end is my beginning' are found everywhere in literature and
the arts. You don't realize how much other poets and playwrights
have used him,'' said festival director Tim Sargeant.
   ``Eliot in his centenary year was the obvious choice for the
festival and he appeals to such a wide range of people.
   ``He wrote poems for children as well as the deep and involved
poetry of `The Waste Land.' His `Old Possum's Book of Practical
Cats' is the basis of Andrew Lloyd Webber's musical, `Cats'; Eliot
was affected by music, and composers in their turn have been
affected by him,'' Sargeant said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``April is the cruelest month, breeding
   ``Lilacs out of the dead land, mixing
   ``Memory and desire, stirring
   ``Dull roots with spring rain.''
   _ ``The Waste Land.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   However, centenary celebrations were marred by a protest over
three distinguished Jews, including Oxford philosopher Sir Isaiah
Berlin, lending their names to a trust fund appeal in Eliot's name
by the London Library, of which he was president.
   Critics recalled the anti-Semitic expressions in some of Eliot's
poetry and letters.
   In the 1927 poem ``Burbank With a Baedeker: Bleistein With a
Cigar,'' Eliot wrote: ``The rats are underneath the piles. The jew
is underneath the lot.''
   The poet also said in a lecture in January 1933, as Adolf Hitler
was about to take power in Germany: ``Reasons of race or religion
combine to make any large number of free-thinking Jews undesirable
... and a spirit of excessive tolerance is to be deprecated.''
   
   Some critics say Eliot in time put aside anti-Semitism and that
it had no role in his later life.
   ``Eliot is much in favor these days because his ideas are now
fashionable,'' said poet Harry Gilonis. ``He was a classicist, a
monarchist, an Anglo-Catholic and very conservative, while in his
poetry he was a modernist, attacked in his day for pessimism and
formlessness.
   ``Eliot wasn't appreciated by the public then but he is admired
now, and with paperbacks for a mass market, more and more people
are reading his work.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Love is most nearly itself
   ``When here and now cease to matter
   ``Old men ought to be explorers
   ``Here and there does not matter.''
   _ ``Four Quartets.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The BBC stressed that while Eliot's pessimism has been much
criticized, when he was at the height of his powers Europe was in
political torment, and doubt was cast on the very survival of the
continent's civilization.
   Newspapers have run a steady stream of articles about Eliot's
poetry and what The Times of London called his ``messy, bewildering
and unpredictable'' life: Eliot's first wife, Vivien Haigh-Wood,
constantly complained of being ill and was eventually committed to
a mental institution.
   But The Times said in an editorial that Eliot was ``still an
inspiration'' for justifying and reinforcing European culture,
which was for him ``a congregation of ideas and values.''
   The centenary eve saw a memorial service in St. Michael's
church, East Coker, the Somerset village home of Eliot's ancestors
who went to America and where his ashes are interred. He
immortalized East Coker in ``Four Quartets.'' Eliot joined the
Faber publishing house as an editor when it was started in 1925.
Its first catalog included his poems from 1909-25.
   ``His books have sold in millions around the world and the
numbers are incalculable,'' said Joan Mackle, a publicist at Faber,
which sells all Eliot's works, which annually earn $2.5 million,
according to Forbes magazine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1555EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-WeekendTV ADV07-09   10-01 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV, ADV 07-09,0845</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07-09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 7-9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Actress Researches Role For Half-Century-Old Murder Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Helen Mirren, like thousands of
Britons before her, traveled to the seaside spa of Bournemouth to
inspect the little cottage where the murder took place 53 years ago.
   Mirren's visit to the house beside the English Channel was
different from those of the merely curious. She was researching her
role as accused murderess Alma Rattenbury in ``Cause Celebre,''
which can be seen on PBS' ``Mystery!'' in two parts, Thursday and
Oct. 20.
   Rattenbury, 38, was accused, along with her teen-age lover,
George Bowman, of bludgeoning her elderly husband to death in 1935.
Their trial in London's Old Bailey caused a sensation, and
Rattenbury was widely reviled in England.
   ``I went to the house and I could feel the terrible trauma the
people felt,'' said Mirren. ``The house hasn't changed its
character since the tragedy took place. Bournemouth is a very
middle class, bourgeois, narrow-minded, smug town.''
   Ever since, the little house in Bournemouth has drawn the
curious who still seek out the house and visit the cemetery in
search of the unmarked graves.
   Francis Rattenbury is buried apart from his wife. She was
acquitted of the charge of murder, but within days stabbed herself
four times in the heart. Bowman was sentenced to death, but the
sentence was commuted to life imprisonment. He served seven years.
Bowman, now 72, still lives in Bournemouth.
   ``I think I feel more strongly about `Cause Celebre' than any
other piece of work I've done,'' said Mirren. She has starred in
such movies as ``White Nights,'' ``Excalibur,'' ``Age of Consent,''
``The Mosquito Coast,'' ``2010,'' ``The Fiendish Plot of Dr. Fu
Manchu'' and the new release, ``Pascali's Island.'' She recently
completed an as-yet untitled movie with Paul Scofield.
   She has also acted extensively on the stage in her native
England, where one critic called her the ``sex bomb'' of the Royal
Shakespeare Company.
   ``When you do Shakespeare, as I've done often,'' she said, ``you
work on an epic scale of emotions. But to do all that and know it
actually happened is quite something. Crimes of passion involving
ordinary people are fascinating. You can't identify with
psychopaths, but you get caught up in stories about real people.
You feel a sense of responsibility bringing back to life someone
whose life I feel close to.
   ``I loved Alma. The woman who now lives in her house loves her
in the same way. The only people who reviled her were the people
who didn't know her. People hated Alma because she had an affair
with a man 20 years younger. Women especially were afraid of that
element in her and felt she should be punished.''
   Mirren says her research has convinced her that Alma Rattenbury
did not participate in the murder.
   ``She instigated it because of what she was,'' she said. ``Alma
and George were tried together, but each confessed to the crime and
said the other was innocent. She was tried only because she
confessed in an effort to protect George.''
   The two-hour drama also stars Harry Andrews as Francis
Rattenbury, David Morrissey as George Bowman, David Suchet as the
defense counsel and Norma West as Irene Riggs, Alma's housekeeper
and close friend.
   Mirren lives in the United States, but still visits and works in
England frequently. She grew up in Southend, which she calls
England's Coney Island. Her first job, while still in convent
school, was as a sideshow barker. Her first acting role was Caliban
in ``The Tempest'' at the age of 13.
   ``I still do a lot of theater in England,'' she said. ``I find
it difficult to work on the stage in Los Angeles. They have good
theater, but it's just not a part of the lives of people here. They
think of theater as an audition for television or film. I hate to
see it debased.''
   Mirren also learned to speak with an American accent so that she
could do more films here. She first tried it out in ``The Mosquito
Coast.''
   ``Pascali's Island,'' about the final days of the Ottoman Empire
of Turkey before World War I, was filmed on the Greek island of
Rhodes off the coast of Turkey.
   ``It's an extraordinary part of the world,'' she said. ``You
feel that history so powerfully. Whenever I go on location I like
to take a book that takes place in that part of the world. So I
took some books by Mary Renault. They're set in classical times.
When I did `The Mosquito Coast' in Belize I took along some books
by Joseph Conrad.''
   She spent this past summer in Baton Rouge, La., with a friend
producing a movie. Afterwards, they toured Civil War battlefields
in the South. She didn't say what she took along to read.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 7-9</NOTE>
