<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:FordProbe     10-01 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Ford Probe,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Ford Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>(EDITORS: Also moving on business wire.)
^By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With little advertising and less fanfare, the
Ford Probe is speeding through dealer showrooms, keeping most
buyers waiting at least six weeks for delivery of a car that may be
carving its own market niche.
   Since its formal introduction last May, the Probe, built beside
the Mazda MX-6 at Mazda Motor Manufacturing USA Corp.'s Flat Rock
plant south of Detroit, is being sold three months in advance of
assembly line runs, Ford Motor Co. analyst Ray Windecker said.
   Delivery time can vary depending on what kind and color
automobile a customer wants.
   The American car-buying public got a dose of what Ford had in
mind months before its formal introduction. The news media,
specifically the automotive magazines, sang the car's praises.
   ``By the time the cars were introduced, more than one-third of
the car-buying age populous was aware of the car,'' Windecker said.
   ``I don't think there's been that much excitement about a
domestic car since a Taurus,'' another Ford that was introduced in
December 1985, said Beth Fusco, an auto analyst with Moody's
Investor Services in New York City.
   ``They did a lot of advance promotion for the car in
magazines,'' she said. ``I thought that was a pretty sophisticated
send-off. I think they did a good job promoting it, and I think the
car is selling itself.''
   Probe's base price is $11,490 with a 2.2 liter, four-cylinder
engine. The car, with hidden headlamps and a swept-back rear deck,
can be upgraded with a turbocharged engine and option packages to
$17,292.
   Earlier this summer, scores of Probes reached the end of the
assembly line at Flat Rock needing repairs.
   Mazda quality control manager James G. Bouck said the quality
problems were created when a second shift was added at the plant _
a joint-venture between Ford and Mazda _ and some workers were
retrained and moved from one shift to another.
   Bouck, who moved to Mazda from General Motors Corp., said Mazda
has more stringent quality demands that some other automakers. That
can result in more cars landing in repair lots before being shipped
to dealers.
   ``Our repair inventory is about 300 now,'' he said, calling it
an expected number.
   Probe sales have grown at a steady clip _ about 600 cars more
are sold each month than in the preceding one. No one at Ford would
reveal projected sales figures, but Windecker said demand has
outstripped those projections.
   It's too early to tell exactly where Probe will fit into the
American car market.
   ``They are creating a different niche for themselves,'' Fusco
said. But, she cautioned, ``I think you have to be really careful
when you're creating a niche.
   ``Look what GM did with Fiero,'' she said, referring to the
Pontiac two-seater that sold well in its first few years on the
market before falling off dramatically. GM stopped making the car
earlier this year.
   Analysts said the Probe has capitalized on the No. 2 and most
profitable automaker's strengths _ solid design, careful marketing
and reliability.
   ``They have done many things right,'' said Richard Henderson, an
analyst with the Pershing Division of Donaldson, Lufkin and
Jenrette in New York City. ``It's a combination of many, many
little factors, some borrowed from Europe, some from North America
and some borrowed from Mazda.
   ``Combine that with a nice fit in its product mix ... and you've
got a very successful car,'' Henderson said.
   Like other newly introduced cars, Probe's engineering initially
may take a back seat to its looks.
   ``What is there out there in that price range that looks that
neat?'' asked Fusco. ``I think people buy cars because they look
good, and secondarily because the quality is good and the warranty
is good.''
   Like other Fords, Probe carries a one-year bumper-to-bumper
warranty and a six-year, 60,000-mile powertrain warranty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
