<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:Safety     10-01 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Safety,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Safety will be among the choices new car buyers will have this
year, according to the National Coalition to Reduce Car Crash
Injuries.
   Air bags and anti-lock brakes are two of the major safety
devices that many manufacturers are offering. Three-point rear seat
belts will also be more commonplace this model year, the Coalition
points out.
   Eleven of the world's 17 largest automobile manufacturers will
offer inflatable air restraint systems as either standard or
optional equipment, according to a study conducted by Ralph Nader,
consumer advocate.
   Four other manufacturers have committed to air bags beginning in
1990 and General Motors _ which offers them as options on the Delta
88 _ says it will offer 3 million cars with air bags by 1992.
   Anti-lock brakes were offered as standard or optional equipment
by 17 of 23 auto manufacturers recently surveyed by the Insurance
Institute for Highway Safety.
   Cary Corbin, Coalition coordinator, says most auto manufacturers
are phasing in standard rear seat shoulder harnesses in the 1989
model year and by model year 1990, virtually all cars sold in the
United States will have shoulder belts for the back seat.
</TEXT>
