<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1600EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv03   10-01 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 03,0609</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gold in the Doldrums</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frustrated by the pokey performance of the stock
and bond markets lately? You won't get much sympathy from fans of
another staple investment, gold.
   The price of gold, which was hovering in the range of $450 to
$460 per troy ounce heading into the summer, made news recently
when it slipped below $400 for the first time in more than a year
and a half.
   The timing of this weak showing made it especially hard for
gold's admirers to swallow.
   First of all, it came against a background of widespread
inflation worries, which were given voice by no less an authority
than Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board. Gold is
supposed to thrive on inflation fears.
   Secondly, gold has not benefited from all the shakeup investor
confidence has suffered through in the nearly 12 months since the
stock market crash last October. Gold is supposed to serve as a
haven from shocks in other investment markets.
   ``A combination of forces has recently ganged up on the price of
gold,'' observed Charles Eaton, an analyst at Nikko Securities
International Inc., in a recent report on the subject.
   Among them, he cites rising interest rates around the world; an
upswing for the dollar in foreign exchange; falling oil prices; and
softness in prices of some other commodities, which suggest that
inflationary pressures are not intensifying the way many people
thought they would.
   ``Gold is international money as defined by the free markets,''
Eaton said. ``When gold is strong, the dollar is weak, and when
gold is weak, the dollar is usually strong.''
   At the same time, high ``real'' interest rates _ that is,
nominal interest rates compared to the rate of inflation _ have
been a drag on the gold market.
   When real interest rates stand at generous levels, they offer
investors an attractive alternative to owning gold, which pays no
interest and in fact may carry a ``negative yield'' in the form of
carrying charges, storage fees, insurance and other costs.
   Many Wall Street analysts have watched the recent drop in gold
prices with undisguised delight.
   After all, it suggests that much-ballyhooed fears of an
overheating economy are not warranted and that the Federal Reserve
is apparently succeeding in its campaign to keep inflation at bay.
   John Connolly at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. sees ``a major change
from the recent consensus holding that an inflationary surge is
inevitable.''
   That line of thinking would point to good things for both the
stock and bond markets.
   But there is a darker version of the same picture _ that ``the
weakness in gold may well be forecasting a period of deflation and
debt liquidation in the months ahead,'' as Eaton says.
   That possibility, rather than an immediate revival of inflation,
now seems to be emerging as the bullish case most often advanced by
gold advocates these days.
   ``Given the size of the worldwide debt problem and the potential
for a credit contraction, we would expect the Federal Reserve to
flood the system with liquidity (i.e., loanable funds),'' Eaton
argues.
   In such circumstances, he says, the dollar will naturally be
cheapened and ``gold will soar.''
   That fits with gold's image as a kind of financial insurance
policy. Like most other insurance policies, it is a bet that many
people, even as they make it, hope they are not going to win.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Oct 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv03   10-01 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 03,0666</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Oct. 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Takeover Fever Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest action in the stock market these
days isn't the buying and selling of shares in companies but the
buying and selling of the companies themselves.
   This is takeover fever, and rather than diminishing as forecast
it seems to be intensifying. Involved in the action are corporate
raiders, corporations seeking new assets, leveraged buyout funds
and big financial institutions.
   The reheating of leveraged buyout fever was measured again last
week when Manufacturers Hanover Corp., once a staid old banking
operation, announced formation of a buyout fund that could amount
to as much as $2 billion.
   Large as that figure is, it belies the true buying power. When
used to buy out shareholders of a target company, it can be
leveraged at a ratio of from 5-to-1 to even 10-to-1, or $10 billion
to $20 billion.
   Such an amount is sufficient to frighten the management of all
but the biggest companies in the United States, but it is only a
small part of the pot. An estimated $25 billion to $30 billion is
controlled by buyout specialists.
   The activity itself _ and the potential for more _ is generating
concern not just from business and investment people, but from
other interested parties who fear that the long-term soundness of
the economy is endangered.
   High on the list of concerns is that sound companies, slowly
built over many decades, are falling into the hands of manipulators
rather than managers, and are prone not only to immediate
dissection but also to eventual destruction.
   Enhancing the power _ and perhaps the danger _ of leveraged
buyout money are ``junk bonds,'' which are high-risk debt
securities paying high rates of interest. A major role of such
bonds is to substitute long-term debt for equity.
   Debt does wonderful things for those seeking to buy existing
companies, but it is generally thought to be more dangerous than
equity to deal with. And, the critics say, those dangers may be
worsened by other activities of the buyers.
   One of these activities is to think short term _ to sacrifice
distant strength for immediate financial results _ and that, say
critics, can get any company into trouble. Such buyers also seek to
lessen debt by selling off parts of the company, perhaps weakening
it in the process.
   The debt itself can become the biggest problem of all,
especially in a downturn. Costly to begin with, it can become
destructively so in a recession or period of high interest rates,
when even strong companies may teeter.
   There is another, more positive, view of the scene: Leveraged
buyouts sometimes get rid of poor management, and they provide a
premium over market prices for shareholders of the company taken
over.
   During 1986, for example, 31 percent of all deals were completed
at a 50 percent or better premium. In 1987, 38 percent of all deals
were at prices at least 50 percent higher than those that prevailed
a month earlier.
   Such short-term benefits cannot be denied. The question only
time can answer is whether these immediate benefits provoke distant
problems.
   ``The transformation of billions of dollars of equuity into debt
is eroding the financial footing of U.S. industry,'' says Wright
Investors' Service. It worries about the economic consequences in a
downturn.
   Concern also is expressed by many critics about the market
volatility and instability that have increased as a result of
takeover fever, with some stocks rising or falling 10 percent in a
day on takeover speculation.
   It was, Wright says, one of the underlying causes of the stock
market collapse of last October, and it also seems to be high on
the list of reasons why many individual investors have abandoned
the market, perhaps for good.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon Oct. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881001-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv01-02-2Takes   10-01 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 01-02-2 Takes,0930</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 1-2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Cars and Trucks: Good '88; Softer '89 Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The end of the 1988 model year is producing
surprisingly strong sales results for the nation's biggest
automakers but raising tough questions for the future.
   Sales results due out Tuesday are expected to show around 15.5
million vehicles _ roughly two-thirds cars and the rest light
trucks _ were sold during the model year. That would be up slightly
from last year, and down from the industry record of 16.1 million
vehicles sold in 1986.
   Up ahead _ in 1989 and beyond _ looms a softer market, analysts
said this past week.
   High on the minds of analysts and consumers are how much cars
and trucks will cost and what kind of incentives automakers will
create in the coming months to lure people into dealerships.
   ``Nobody buys cars without incentives,'' said analyst Kathleen
Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   ``It's another way of life _ sort of like frequent-flier
programs in the airlines,'' said Mike Kobayashi of PaineWebber Inc.
He added that incentives would be part of marketing all kinds of
cars and trucks.
   Analysts agreed consumers are expecting to be offered cash
incentives, and there's a chance that cut-rate financing, which
dropped as low as 1.9 percent just over a year ago, may return if
fears of higher interest rates and modest inflation in 1989 later
prove true.
   But Douglas Laughlin of Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc. said consumers
may be offered enticements earlier. ``We could come into the
calendar year with some kind of incentive,'' he said.
   Beyond that, there is some question about how domestic and
foreign car makers can convince consumers that their vehicles are
the best and the most affordable. Warranties may come into play,
leasing may be more attractive and safety could be a big concern.
   Estimates of 1989 sales by more than a dozen analysts ranged
from a high of about 15 million vehicles to a low of about 13
million.
   ``I think 1989 (sales) will be flat, but a relatively good year
for the Big Three,'' said Joshuah Harari of Standard & Poors Corp.
   For the past several years, General Motors Corp. has seen its
share of the American vehicle market slip as buyers turned to Ford
Motor Co., Chrysler Corp. and the imports. The analysts expect to
see GM arrest that slide in the next model year as, among other
things, the world's largest corporation gives each of its divisions
more distinctive personalities.
   ``They've lost the equivalent of a Chrysler-size company (in
sales) in the last three to four years,'' said David Healy of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``GM stopped the hemorrhaging in terms of market share, but
there's still some blood on the Band-Aid,'' said Joseph Phillippi
of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Generally, the No. 1 automaker is aiming Chevrolet at the
economy and modestly priced end of the market; Pontiac is being
tagged as the performance car division; Oldsmobile is getting the
lion's share of GM's high-tech work and Buick and Cadillac are
offering the company's top-of-the-line cars.
   Some experts doubt whether Ford can continue its phenomenal
earnings pace of the first half of the year. The nation's No. 2
automaker has set industry earnings records during the last two
quarters _ each well over $1 billion.
   ``They are awash in liquidity,'' said Beth Fusco of Moody's
Investor Services.
   ``Ford continues to roll on ... but their quality seems to be
slipping a little,'' Phillippi said. ``I've seen dirt in the paint
of cars on showroom floors.''
   Healy agreed. ``One of the things I worry about at Ford is
they've been running full (capacity) for so long ... you wonder if
they're vulnerable to some quality problems,'' he said.
   Quality and customer satisfaction are major concerns at
Chrysler, where Gerald Greenwald, chairman of the corporation's
car-making arm Chrysler Motors Corp., conceded the company would
have to struggle to hold on to its 1988 car sales levels in 1989.
Big benefits for the No. 3 automaker have been its Jeeps and
trend-setting minivans.
   ``God bless minivans and Jeeps,'' Ben Bidwell, Chrysler Motors'
marketing president said late last month during the corporation's
1989 model introduction.
   Chrysler was the most involved in last year's incentive fire
sales, and it lost money in the process. But some analysts suggest
that offering incentives was the only thing Chrysler could do at
the time, and since then, the company's market share has crept up a
bit.
   ``They bought market share (whose cost) is pretty high,'' said
Don DeScenza of Nomura Securities Inc.
   But consumers are mainly concerned about one thing _ price. And
it appears that prices are going up this coming year, generally
averaging 3 percent to 4 percent above 1988 sticker prices.
   However, said Dick Henderson of the Pershing Division of
Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Inc.,``I can't see how prices on new
vehicles are going to be higher than inflation.''
   ``It's going to be interesting to see how the customer reacts to
the pricing,'' Phillippi said.
   Beyond 1989, though, auto analysts see some dark days.
   ``The big cloud on the horizon is ... aren't we due for a
recession?'' wondered Charles Brady of Oppenheimer & Co.
   ``It's going to be bad in '90 and '91,'' Harari predicted.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
