<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Bankers-Debt     10-01 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bankers-Debt,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Bankers' Confidence in World Credit at All-Time Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The confidence of international bankers in the
creditworthiness of the world's nations has sunk to a 10-year low,
Institutional Investor magazine said Friday.
   Every six months the magazine polls about 100 international
commercial banks to rank the creditworthiness of 112 nations on a
scale of 0 to 100.
   Its September survey found Japan again garnered the most
confidence, with a rating of 94.8. Switzerland was second at 93.9,
West Germany third at 93.1 and the United States fourth at 89.7.
   At the bottom of the heap were Nicaragua, with a 5.2 rating, and
North Korea, with 4.5.
   The average rating of all 112 nations, Institutional Investor
said, hit an all-time low of 38.7.
   ``The new global low is the culmination of a long-term downward
trend in the 10 years that this magazine has been compiling country
credit ratings,'' it said. ``The decline of two tenths of a point
since March 1988 ... seems to reflect an instinctive pessimism,
even a worldweariness, rather than any specific developments.''
   Average country credit ratings have been sinking at a
particularly fast clip since August 1982, when Mexico's
announcement that it could not meet its foreign debt payments
signaled the beginning of a Third World debt crisis that continues.
   Third World debtor nations now owe an estimated $1.2 trillion to
foreign banks, governments, international credit institutions and
other global creditors. The total debt continues to grow as the
debtor nations fall further behind on their payments of principal
and interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
