<DOCNO> AP881001-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f AM-CEOPay Adv03   10-01 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CEO Pay, Adv 03,0281</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release AMs Monday Oct. 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Survey: Service Sector CEOs the Highest Paid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief executive officers at service companies
are the highest paid executives in the country, according to a
survey released Sunday.
   The survey found that the median compensation _ salary plus
bonuses _ for chief executives in 24 service companies was $649,000
from 1986 to 1987. That means half earned more than $649,000 and
half got less.
   The Conference Board, a business-financed research organization,
listed computer services and software, health care and
entertainment-oriented and real estate firms among the service
companies in its survey.
   ``The position of diversified services at the top of the
compensation ladder reflects the significant growth of this
country's service economy,'' said Charles Peck, who studies
compensation for the Conference Board.
   CEOs at 254 manufacturing firms ranked second in compensation,
with a median of $642,000, and executives in 31 energy and natural
resource firms were third with a median of $525,000.
   Ranking fourth were 33 retail and wholesale trade company chief
executives, with a median of $413,000; fifth were 93 commercial
bankers, at $412,000; and sixth were 91 insurance CEOs, at $398,000.
   In seventh place, at the bottom of the list, were 111 utility
executives, whose median salary was $355,000, the Conference Board
said.
   ``The low compensation standing of utilities clearly reflects
the heavy degree of regulation in this industry,'' Peck said.
   ``Compensation in banks and insurance firms has been rising as
these industries become more deregulated and the scope and
responsibilities of the top jobs increases,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Monday Oct. 3</NOTE>
