<HEAD>Ramada Considering Options to Maintain Independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. is considering restructuring its
operations as an alternative to a friendly buyout offer made
earlier this month by the Pritzker family of Chicago, the
Phoenix-based company said Thursday.
   Among Ramada's options are selling some divisions or assets or
negotiating a management buyout, according to securities analysts.
The Pritzker family owns 7.2 percent of Ramada's stock and is the
corporation's largest shareholder.
   Ramada Chairman Richard Snell met Tuesday in Chicago with Jay
Pritzker, president of HCC Corp., an affiliate of the Hyatt hotel
chain. HCC had offered $100 a share, but Ramada's directors
rejected that Sept. 16.
   A Securities and Exchange Commission filing Thursday in
Washington indicated that Pritzker reaffirmed the $368 million
offer for Ramada. The filing said Snell believed there was no
substantial difference between a deal discussed Tuesday and the
rejected offer.
   Daniel Lee, vice president of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New
York, said he was not surprised that Pritzker did not raise his bid.
   ``Why should he be negotiating against himself?'' Lee asked.
``Nobody else has made a higher offer.''
   Lee also said that Ramada may not get a better offer. Ramada's
stock closed Thursday at $9.62{, up 12{ cents from Wednesday, in
New York Stock Exchange trading. Early Friday afternoon, it was
trading at $9.75, up another 12{ cents from Thursday's close.
</TEXT>
