<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv01-02   10-01 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 01-02,0785</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 1-2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gold Coin Sales Soar Following Metal's Drop Below $400</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic athletes aren't the only ones going for the gold lately.
   Precious-metals dealers say sales of gold coins soared as much
as 60 percent in the past week after the yellow metal's price fell
below $400 a troy ounce.
   The jump in demand hasn't been strong enough to push gold's
price back above $400, a key psychological barrier it cracked on
Sept. 21 for the first time in more than 19 months. But many
investors, from individuals to managers of large corporate
portfolios, believe gold below $400 represents a buying opportunity
too good to ignore.
   ``Thank goodness, considering there was virtually no demand for
gold coins before gold dipped below $400,'' said Bruce Kaplan,
senior vice president of A-Mark Precious Metals Inc., a large
dealer based in Santa Monica, Calif.
   ``We've seen a tremendous surge in demand for the U.S. Eagle,
the Canadian Maple Leaf and the Australian Nugget coins,'' he said.
   Kaplan said A-Mark's sales of gold, silver and platinum were up
40 percent during the seven business days ending Thursday compared
with the previous seven business days. Most of that business was in
gold, he said.
   Kaplan said buying activity didn't really take off until gold
dropped to $395 an ounce on Sept. 23. Prices inched higher for most
of the past week, then fell again on Friday.
   Gold for October delivery on New York's Commodity Exchange
settled Friday at $394.40 a troy ounce.
   Gold was valued at around $440 an ounce in early July and at
about $490 in late December.
   James Blanchard, chairman of New Orleans-based precious-metals
dealer Blanchard & Co., reported a 60 percent increase in sales
during the period Sept. 23-28 compared with the previous four
business days.
   ``A lot of people who invest in precious metals are people who
look for bargains and they figure this is the time to go,''
Blanchard said.
   New York-based Deak International Inc. reported an estimated
sales gain of 30 percent to 50 percent in September compared with
August. Spokeswoman Jerri Eskow said most of the orders were from
new customers, many of them first-time buyers.
   Gold's plunge from around $430 an ounce just one month ago was
precipitated by government reports that indicated the U.S.
economy's growth had slowed substantially after the brisk expansion
of the first half.
   Gold is seen as a investment hedge against inflation, which
typically rises in a rapidly expanding economy. The recent signs of
slower economic growth stifled demand for gold, so its price
dropped.
   Most analysts expect gold prices to bottom out somewhere between
$360 and $390 an ounce, so speculators have been buying on price
dips.
   But analysts recommended caution. Richard Levine, vice president
of the precious metals and foreign exchange group of Elders Futures
Inc., said that at current price levels, small investors interested
in gold should spend no more than 50 percent of what they are
prepared to commit to gold or gold products.
   ``I would not commit more than 50 percent because I think the
market is going to have one more major selloff,'' he said.
   ``I think I'd begin to buy on a scaled-down basis,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, precious-metals analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``Realistically speaking, it's not that clear that it's going to
gallop up again, but I'd begin buying from here on into the
(presidential) election,'' she said. ``Then I think that toward the
end of the year, you'll begin to see a shift'' toward higher prices.
   One-ounce coins are the most popular form of gold ownership, and
the U.S. Eagle enjoys the greatest favor among buyers in this
country. Other coins include the Maple Leaf, the Nugget, the
British Brittania and the Chinese Panda.
   Buying and selling is as easy as picking up a telephone and
giving the dealer your credit card nubmer. Many banks and coin
dealers also sell gold coins.
   Dealers generally charge a 5 percent or 6 percent premium over
the spot gold price, plus an additional fee of $3 or $4 for
customers who want to take physical possession of their gold. The
other option is to have the dealer store the gold for you.
   ``A lot of people want something they can touch,'' said Diane
Meagher, manager of Deak International's Chicago office. ``We want
our customers to feel comfortable with what they're holding.''
</TEXT>
